{"title_page": "Buckwheat Boyz", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = peebs needs food\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Miami]], [[Florida]], [[United States]]\n| genre               = [[Miami bass]]\n| years_active        = 1997\u20132002\n| label               = [[Koch Records]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n| current_members     = \n| past_members        = Marcus Bowens<br>Jermaine Fuller<br>J.J. O'Neal<br>Dougy Williams\n}}\nThe '''Buckwheat Boyz''' was an American novelty group founded by Marcus Bowens and Jermaine Fuller, with the later addition of J.J. O'Neal and Dougy Williams. The Buckwheat Boyz were signed by [[Koch Records]], and recorded their first and only full-length record. From this self-titled debut album, the song \"Peanut Butter Jelly Time\" became a popular [[internet meme]] after a [[Adobe Flash|Flash]]-animated music video featuring a dancing banana was created.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peanut Butter Jelly Time|publisher=peanutbutterjellytime.net|url=http://peanutbutterjellytime.net/|accessdate=12 December 2014|date=12 December 2014}}</ref> The popularity of the song increased as it was featured on TV shows such as ''[[The Proud Family]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', and ''[[Regular Show]]''.\n\n==Disbandment==\nIn 2002, founding member and vocalist Jermaine Fuller died during an 11-hour police standoff.  During the standoff, his brother-in-law, [[Snoop Dogg]], attempted to calm Fuller down and convince him to surrender to no avail. Fuller's death directly led to the disbandment of the group.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rapper made plea during standoff|publisher=Las Vegas Sun|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2002/aug/14/rapper-made-plea-during-standoff/|accessdate=9 November 2014|date=14 August 2002}}</ref>\n\n==\"Ice Cream and Cake\" song==\nTheir song \"Ice Cream and Cake\" quickly rose in popularity after being featured in a 2009 [[Baskin-Robbins]] marketing campaign, which included a [[television commercial]] and an ''Ice Cream and Cake Dance Video Contest''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baskinrobbins.co.uk/about_us/the_latest_scoop.html|title=Baskin-Robbins - The Latest Scoop|publisher=Baskin-Robbins|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> In August 2009, Baskin-Robbins kicked off the contest by hosting the ''[[Guinness World Records]] Largest Cheerleading Dance'' event with [[Mario Lopez]] of [[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra TV]] and 225 members of the [http://www.uca.varsity.com/ Universal Cheerleaders Association (UCA)], at the [[University of California Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BASKIN-ROBBINS \"ICE CREAM AND CAKE\" DANCES ITS WAY TO WORLD RECORD |url=http://news.dunkindonuts.com/article_download.cfm?article_id=1013 |publisher=Baskin-Robbins |format=PDF |accessdate=6 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502195022/http://news.dunkindonuts.com/article_download.cfm?article_id=1013 |archivedate=2 May 2012 }}</ref> However, as of August 2011, the Guinness World Records archive states that the record for largest cheerleading dance was set in November 2009 by 297 participants at the [[University of Memphis]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. It is not known whether this event was related to the Baskin-Robbins contest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guinness World Records - Largest cheerleading dance|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/Search/Details/Largestcheerleadingdance/70264.htm|accessdate=5 August 2011|date=7 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924024243/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/Search/Details/Largestcheerleadingdance/70264.htm|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Old Dominion University]] plays \"Ice Cream and Cake\" at home [[Old Dominion Monarchs basketball|basketball]] games at the [[Ted Constant Convocation Center]], and enjoys active crowd dance participation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.odu.edu/ao/news/media.php?todo=details&todo=details&id=14227 |title=ODU Students Rev up Excitement for Big Basketball Weekend, February 13, 2009 |access-date=September 1, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307115733/http://www.odu.edu/ao/news/media.php?todo=details&todo=details&id=14227 |archive-date=March 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyz, Buckwheat}}\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Miami]]\n[[Category:American hip hop DJs]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n\n\n{{US-hiphop-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Buckwheat Boyz\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Miami]], [[Florida]], [[United States]]\n| genre               = [[Miami bass]]\n| years_active        = 1997\u20132002\n| label               = [[Koch Records]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n| current_members     = \n| past_members        = Marcus Bowens<br>Jermaine Fuller<br>J.J. O'Neal<br>Dougy Williams\n}}\nThe '''Buckwheat Boyz''' was an American novelty group founded by Marcus Bowens and Jermaine Fuller, with the later addition of J.J. O'Neal and Dougy Williams. The Buckwheat Boyz were signed by [[Koch Records]], and recorded their first and only full-length record. From this self-titled debut album, the song \"Peanut Butter Jelly Time\" became a popular [[internet meme]] after a [[Adobe Flash|Flash]]-animated music video featuring a dancing banana was created.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peanut Butter Jelly Time|publisher=peanutbutterjellytime.net|url=http://peanutbutterjellytime.net/|accessdate=12 December 2014|date=12 December 2014}}</ref> The popularity of the song increased as it was featured on TV shows such as ''[[The Proud Family]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', and ''[[Regular Show]]''.\n\n==Disbandment==\nIn 2002, founding member and vocalist Jermaine Fuller died during an 11-hour police standoff.  During the standoff, his brother-in-law, [[Snoop Dogg]], attempted to calm Fuller down and convince him to surrender to no avail. Fuller's death directly led to the disbandment of the group.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rapper made plea during standoff|publisher=Las Vegas Sun|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2002/aug/14/rapper-made-plea-during-standoff/|accessdate=9 November 2014|date=14 August 2002}}</ref>\n\n==\"Ice Cream and Cake\" song==\nTheir song \"Ice Cream and Cake\" quickly rose in popularity after being featured in a 2009 [[Baskin-Robbins]] marketing campaign, which included a [[television commercial]] and an ''Ice Cream and Cake Dance Video Contest''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baskinrobbins.co.uk/about_us/the_latest_scoop.html|title=Baskin-Robbins - The Latest Scoop|publisher=Baskin-Robbins|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> In August 2009, Baskin-Robbins kicked off the contest by hosting the ''[[Guinness World Records]] Largest Cheerleading Dance'' event with [[Mario Lopez]] of [[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra TV]] and 225 members of the [http://www.uca.varsity.com/ Universal Cheerleaders Association (UCA)], at the [[University of California Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BASKIN-ROBBINS \"ICE CREAM AND CAKE\" DANCES ITS WAY TO WORLD RECORD |url=http://news.dunkindonuts.com/article_download.cfm?article_id=1013 |publisher=Baskin-Robbins |format=PDF |accessdate=6 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502195022/http://news.dunkindonuts.com/article_download.cfm?article_id=1013 |archivedate=2 May 2012 }}</ref> However, as of August 2011, the Guinness World Records archive states that the record for largest cheerleading dance was set in November 2009 by 297 participants at the [[University of Memphis]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. It is not known whether this event was related to the Baskin-Robbins contest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guinness World Records - Largest cheerleading dance|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/Search/Details/Largestcheerleadingdance/70264.htm|accessdate=5 August 2011|date=7 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924024243/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/Search/Details/Largestcheerleadingdance/70264.htm|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Old Dominion University]] plays \"Ice Cream and Cake\" at home [[Old Dominion Monarchs basketball|basketball]] games at the [[Ted Constant Convocation Center]], and enjoys active crowd dance participation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.odu.edu/ao/news/media.php?todo=details&todo=details&id=14227 |title=ODU Students Rev up Excitement for Big Basketball Weekend, February 13, 2009 |access-date=September 1, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307115733/http://www.odu.edu/ao/news/media.php?todo=details&todo=details&id=14227 |archive-date=March 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyz, Buckwheat}}\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Miami]]\n[[Category:American hip hop DJs]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n\n\n{{US-hiphop-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Peebsxxx", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buckwheat_Boyz"}
{"title_page": "University of the West Indies", "text_new": "{{about|the University of the West Indies system and its flagship constituent unit in [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], [[Jamaica]]|other uses|University of the West Indies (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|University of the French West Indies}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n| name = The University of the West Indies\n| image_name = Coat of arms of the University of the West Indies.png\n| motto = Oriens Ex Occidente Lux ([[Latin]])\n| mottoeng = A Light Rising From The West\n| established = 1948\n| type = Regional university, [[public]], autonomous\n| chancellor = Robert Bermudez\n| vice_chancellor = [[Hilary Beckles]]\n| students = near 50,000 (across 5 campuses)<ref>{{cite web |title=The University of the West Indies |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/university-west-indies |website=THE World University Rankings |publisher=Times Higher Education |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n| city = \n| country = \n| campus = [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], [[Jamaica]] (headquarters)\n| mascot = The Pelican\n| website = [http://www.uwi.edu www.uwi.edu]<br />[http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu UWI Cave Hill]<br />[http://sta.uwi.edu UWI St. Augustine]<br />[http://www.mona.uwi.edu UWI Mona]<br />[http://www.open.uwi.edu UWI Open Campus] <br /> [http://fiveislands.uwi.edu UWI Five Islands Campus]\n| faculty = 1,200\n| affiliations = Association of Commonwealth Universities (ACU)<br /> [[Caribbean Community]]\n}}\n[[File:TnT St. Augustine UWI Campus.jpg|thumb|St. Augustine UWI Campus]]\n[[File:Continuing Promise 2015 150512-A-OM702-004.jpg|thumb]]\n\n'''The University of the West Indies''' ('''UWI'''), originally '''University College of the West Indies''',<ref name=hosp>{{cite web|url=http://uhwi.gov.jm/about/history|title=History of the UHWI - University Hospital of the West Indies|website=uhwi.gov.jm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.uwi.edu/gradingpolicy/scale.html |title = Grading Scale}}</ref> is a public university system established to serve the [[higher education]] needs of the residents of 17 English-speaking [[countries]] and [[Territory (country subdivision)|territories]] in the [[Caribbean]]: [[Anguilla]], [[Antigua and Barbuda]], [[The Bahamas]], [[Barbados]], [[Belize]], [[Bermuda]], [[British Virgin Islands]], [[Cayman Islands]], [[Dominica]], [[Grenada]],  [[Jamaica]], [[Montserrat]], [[St. Kitts and Nevis]], [[St. Lucia]], [[St. Vincent and the Grenadines]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], and [[Turks and Caicos Islands]].\nEach country is either a member of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] or a [[British Overseas Territory]]. The aim of the university is to help 'unlock the potential for economic and cultural growth' in the [[West Indies]], thus allowing improved regional autonomy.<ref>''The University of the West Indies, A Quinquagenary Calendar 1948-1998'',Douglas Hall,1998.Jamaica, The Press, University of the West Indies</ref> The University was originally instituted as an independent external college of the [[University of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uwiarchives.wordpress.com/2015/04/22/happy-89th-birthday-to-the-visitor/|title=Happy 90th Birthday to the Visitor!!!|date=22 April 2015|website=wordpress.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504024227/https://uwiarchives.wordpress.com/2015/04/22/happy-89th-birthday-to-the-visitor/|archivedate=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University has produced students who have excelled in a number of disciplines such as the arts and sciences, business, politics, and sports. Notable alumni and faculty include three [[Nobel Laureates]], 72 [[Rhodes Scholars]], 3 [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]] winners, 1 [[Emmy award]] winner,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.escapeartist.com/blog/antigua-and-barbuda-citizenship-new-university-fund-option/ | title=Antigua and Barbuda Citizenship \u2014 New University Fund Option| date=2018-10-18}}</ref> 1 [[Man Booker Prize]] winner, 1 [[American Book Awards]] winner, 18 current or former Caribbean Heads of Government, an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] medallist and other award winners. The [[University of the West Indies cricket team|university's cricket team]] previously participated in [[Cricket in the West Indies|West Indian domestic cricket]], but now participates as part of a [[Combined Campuses and Colleges cricket team|Combined Campuses and Colleges]] team.\n\nThe UWI campus in [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], [[Jamaica]] serves as the headquarters of the UWI system. Aside from UWI Mona, it has four (4) major university centers: [[University of the West Indies at Cave Hill|UWI Cave Hill]] (Barbados), [[University of the West Indies at St. Augustine|UWI St. Augustine]] (Trinidad and Tobago), [[University of the West Indies at Five Islands|UWI Five Islands]] (Antigua and Barbuda), and the regional [[University of the West Indies Open Campus|UWI Open Campus]] that is scattered among UWI-funding Caribbean nations.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:UWI Mona Campus Main Library.jpg|thumb|Main Library, Mona Campus, Jamaica]]\nThe university was founded in 1948, on the recommendation of the Asquith Commission<ref>[http://www.bcn.cl/obtienearchivo?id=documentos/10221.1/29331/2/213787.pdf \"Report of the Commission on Higher Education in the Colonies\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045338/http://www.bcn.cl/obtienearchivo?id=documentos%2F10221.1%2F29331%2F2%2F213787.pdf |title= |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref> through its sub-committee on the West Indies chaired by Sir James Irvine.<ref>''Report of the West Indies Committee of the Commission on Higher Education in the Colonies'', Presented by the Secretary of State for the Colonies to Parliament by Command of His Majesty June 1945. London, His Majesty\u2019s Stationery Office</ref> The Asquith Commission had been established in 1943 to review the provision of higher education in the British colonies. Initially in a special relationship with the [[University of London]], the then University College of the West Indies (UCWI) was seated at [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], about five miles from [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], Jamaica. The university was based at the [[Gibraltar Camp]] used by [[Evacuation of the Gibraltarian civilian population during World War II|evacuated Gibraltarians during the war]].<ref name=brown>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Suzanne Francis|title=Mona Past and Present: The History and Heritage of the Mona Campus, University of the West Indies|pages=10\u201311|year=2006|publisher=University of the West Indies Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EQ63yTgVkaEC|isbn=9789766401597}}</ref><ref name=\"Tortello\">{{Cite news |url=http://old.jamaica-gleaner.com/pages/history/story0069.html |title=Pieces of the Past: Out Of Many Cultures: Gibraltar Camp a Refuge from war |last=Tortello |first=Rebecca |date=7 November 2005 |work=Jamaica Gleaner  |access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeeking to address a need for medical care the first faculty established was a medical school.<ref name=hosp/> The foundation stone for a hospital was added in 1949 and the University College Hospital of the West Indies opened in 1953. On 18 January 1953, Sir [[Winston Churchill]] visited the hospital on 18 January 1953 and unveiled a plaque in recognition of the contribution made by the government of the United Kingdom to the hospital.<ref name=hosp/> The hospital was renamed the '''University Hospital of the West Indies''' in 1967 when the University gained full university status.<ref name=hosp/> The hospital offers patient care, the hospital also facilitates research and teaching along with the Medical Services department of the Mona campus of the University of the West Indies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/UHWI--UWI-team-up-for-completion-of-hospital-s-overhaul_87950 |title=UHWI, UWI team up for completion of hospital's overhaul |last=Henry |first=Balford |date=29 January 2017 |website=Jamaica Observer |access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University College achieved independent university status in 1962.  The St Augustine Campus in Trinidad, formerly the Imperial College of Tropical Agriculture (ICTA), was established in 1960, followed by a school established along University Row, at the [[Port of Bridgetown|Deep Water Harbour]] of Barbados in 1963, later seated at the present Cave Hill Campus in 1967. The establishment of the Open Campus, University Centres, headed by a Resident Tutor, were established in each of the other 13 contributing territories thereafter.\n\nIn 1950, [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]], the last surviving granddaughter of [[Queen Victoria]], became the first Chancellor of the University College of the West Indies.\n\nSir [[William Arthur Lewis]] was the first Vice-Chancellor under the UWI's independent Charter. A native of [[St Lucia]], he served as the first West Indian Principal of the UCWI from 1958 to 1960 and as Vice-Chancellor from 1960 to 1963. He was succeeded by Sir Philip Sherlock (a Jamaican and one of the UWI's founding fathers) who served as Vice-Chancellor from 1963 to 1969. Sir [[Roy Marshall (academic)|Roy Marshall]], a Barbadian, was the next Vice-Chancellor, serving from 1969 to 1974. He was succeeded by Dr Aston Zachariah Preston, a Jamaican, who died in office on 24 June 1986, having served from 1974. The fifth Vice-Chancellor was Sir Alister McIntyre, who served from 1988 to 1998, followed by alumnus and Professor Emeritus [[Rex Nettleford]] who served from 1998 to 2004. The current Vice-Chancellor is Professor Sir [[Hilary Beckles]], who succeeded Professor E. Nigel Harris in May 2015.\n\nThe [[University of the West Indies Museum]] catalogs and exhibits some of the university's history.\n\n== University of the West Indies System ==\nThe UWI is the largest, most longstanding higher education provider in the Commonwealth Caribbean, with five constituent campuses: \n* [https://www.mona.uwi.edu/ Mona] in Jamaica \n* [[University of the West Indies at St. Augustine|St. Augustine]] in Trinidad and Tobago,<ref name=\"sta.uwi.edu\">{{Cite web | url=https://sta.uwi.edu/internationaloffice/courses |title = Partner Institutions &#124; UWI International Office}}</ref> \n* [[University of the West Indies, Cave Hill|Cave Hill]] in Barbados,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://cavehill.uwi.edu/ |title = The University of the West Indies at Cave Hill, Barbados}}</ref>\n* [[University of the West Indies at Five Islands|Five Islands]], [[Antigua and Barbuda]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwi.edu/featured-story/fiveislandscampus.asp|title=New UWI Campus in Antigua and Barbuda|date=26 June 2019|author=Professor Sir Hilary Beckles (Vice-Chancellor)|work=University of the West Indies}}</ref>\n* [[University of the West Indies Open Campus|Open Campus]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.open.uwi.edu/ | title=Home &#124; WWW.open.uwi.edu}}</ref> serving 17 Caribbean island-nations.\n\nThe following are the satellite campuses of the university system:\n* Mount Hope Campus in Mount Hope, Trinidad and Tobago (houses the Faculty of Medical Sciences of UWI St. Augustine)\n* St. Augustine South Campus at [[Debe]] in the Penal-Debe region, Trinidad and Tobago (extension campus of UWI St. Augustine)<ref>{{cite web |title=Message from the Principal: Welcome to The UWI, St. Augustine South Campus, Penal-Debe |url=https://sta.uwi.edu/uwitoday/archive/august_2015/article2.asp |website=UWI Today |publisher=The University of the West Indies St. Augustine |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kristian |first1=De Silva |title=UWI to move in Debe campus in new academic year |url=https://www.guardian.co.tt/news/uwi-to-move-in-debe-campus-in-new-academic-year-6.2.832291.82fda5b463 |accessdate=29 December 2019 |work=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media |date=25 Apr 2019}}</ref>\n* Western Jamaica Campus in [[Montego Bay]], Jamaica (extension campus of UWI Mona)\n* Centre for Hotel and Tourism Management in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], Bahamas (extension campus of UWI Mona)\n* School of Clinical Medicine and Research in Nassau, Bahamas (extension of the medical programme at UWI St. Augustine)<ref>{{cite web |title=UWI School of Medicine graduates offered training opportunities at PMH |url=http://www.bahamas.gov.bs/wps/portal/public/gov/government/news/uwi%20school%20of%20medicine%20graduates%20offered%20training%20opportunities%20at%20pmh/!ut/p/b1/vZRdr6I6FIZ_y_4BblqgFC6LQEEERL65IaiIoCLyoeCvH3cyyZw5ycy5OTPtVZM36-l6VlMmZRIIJcSxEsdzTMykTf6oynyobk1--TqnQsYBahHCi5aoCQQYAadxyCQcdSETMbGe8FjprVJVvUd_g-tlNq_01R5th0mlci6qIe92TtzJQpQXRycP0ke-VsfIxQAfvV3WJ2ct8lt77Q51Pqc0WT87ZJjQ7anRXs2mQ2PJVs5laTVKlfC9FRi36QJpv96FCVD1oHxO-2QZ7Od2ttwz3Ln-XOQn1khHolS9lrXWpZUQG90PWgec7EXxHUk0PV6khksWtT5JI3sMS5kLFg9BPMrgXkTux8e7-eTdPPjFIuC_3aQ_RxzWl4ABl1AwAwQUgf0e-A0ieQfwjwrUD8G7AiBbD7pAxJjxmRjwmVfPrfE6v7Y1eLJD7bI2JgAqAef5emT7mukdtnZfuxNQgtmrrdn3tY1Vy5Y9-JtDuA1kQtrhUDj_Bv58ZY9yfxpIkSO-NWJ_QxD7ViD8bSD6U0DqWO7yS6kvfynldJ0Ia85R4d8G_v8zXDFptbt-PvfXT_CJeIiQBFlJYDGLIWbCLuGnXWlNCvGy5zm9rO24BY9e1l572V-sUnnpmWe9isSsN8rtwjWGYExvurzoYZbWtnQQqeYUhSZx91W3656dGtGl1O72FT3dYtCN2-WOGg1iWQldB2l_dzi-aNS4oEEclXBNchW5ymiTFJh8WJn7l2ldtb57v67bRalm1X7i9uTY093QD0Fb6uElwYMcRPjgs3pt5yaBCyxKDXY3r2DknvqqjOJmPOV2Nb060T_oMxUf22yTbiaxqxcPVTlJ4cor37-Ird-uBXNNu3lxPtr_3Dz5-PgGRp15-A!!/dl4/d5/L2dBISEvZ0FBIS9nQSEh/ |website=Press Release |publisher=The Government of the Bahamas |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe other contributing countries are served by the Open Campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.open.uwi.edu/|title=The University of the West Indies - Open Campus|accessdate=22 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020191630/http://www.open.uwi.edu/|archivedate=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Proposed ===\nThere have been various proposals to add one or more campuses on other islands to expand the UWI system, such as a campus at Hope, Grenada.<ref>[https://www.gov.gd/egov/news/2012/jul12/20_07_12/item_1/govt_land_UWI.html Government hands over land to UWI]\nFriday, July 20, 2012, St. George's, Grenada</ref><ref>[https://www.caribjournal.com/2012/07/22/grenada-hands-over-land-for-university-of-the-west-indies-campus/ Grenada Hands Over Land for University of the West Indies Campus]</ref> The campus at Five Islands, Antigua and Barbuda opened in 2019.\n\n=== Articulation and Franchised Programmes ===\nIn addition to programmes offered directly by one of the faculties of the University, the UWI also extends accessibility to its programmes through articulation agreements and franchise arrangements with regional institutions. In many of these arrangements, students are able to study in their home countries for the first one or two years before going to a landed campus for the third (and fourth) year.<ref name=\"Martin & Bray\">{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=Michaela |last2=Bray |first2=Mark |title=Tertiary education in small states : planning in the context of globalization |date=2011 |publisher=Unesco Pub. |location=Paris, France |isbn=978-92-803-1358-1 |url=https://unesdoc.unesco.org/in/documentViewer.xhtml?v=2.1.196&id=p::usmarcdef_0000212196&file=/in/rest/annotationSVC/DownloadWatermarkedAttachment/attach_import_15acee17-98ea-49cb-acfb-23bf452ce3d7%3F_%3D212196eng.pdf&locale=en&multi=true&ark=/ark:/48223/pf0000212196/PDF/212196eng.pdf#%5B%7B%22num%22%3A826%2C%22gen%22%3A0%7D%2C%7B%22name%22%3A%22XYZ%22%7D%2Cnull%2Cnull%2C0%5D |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref> In the case of articulation agreements, the local institution develops its own programme and the UWI agrees to recognise it as equivalent to the first year or two of a specific UWI programme. In the case of a franchise programme, the local institution delivers exactly the programme as offered by UWI. This is usually the first year or two, but can be the full bachelor's degree on occasion.\n\n== Global initiatives ==\nThe University of the West Indies has initiated several international partnerships. In 2016, UWI and the Global Institute for Software Technology (GIST) established the UWI-China Institute for Information Technology.<ref name=\"Academia_in_Action\">{{cite web |title=Academia in Action. The UWI at 70: The Next Phase |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/sites/default/files/institution_downloads/uwi_next_phase.pdf |website=Times Higher Education |publisher=University of the West Indies |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref> Starting in the summer of 2018, students in the programme on the Cave Hill and Mona campuses will travel to [[Suchou]], [[China]] for two years. studying both Mandarin and software engineering.<ref>{{cite news |title=Students off to China from UWI to further study Software Engineering |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/students-china-uwi-further-study-software-engineering-1 |accessdate=14 February 2019 |publisher=LOOP News |date=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe UWI-[[SUNY]] Center for Leadership and Sustainable Development (CLSD) was established in 2017 on SUNY's Empire State campus in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=Academia_in_Action /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Simon |first1=Alexandra |title=University of West Indies partners with SUNY |url=https://www.caribbeanlifenews.com/stories/2017/2/cl-uwi-suny-partnership-2017-02-03-bk.html |accessdate=14 February 2019 |publisher=Caribbean Life |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\nThe centre is designed to assist the Commonwealth Caribbean in meeting the [[United Nations]] [[Sustainable Development Goals]]. In addition to research and advocacy, plans are underway to offer a joint master's degree in sustainability and leadership.<ref name=\"VCAR2016/2017\">{{cite web |last1=Beckles |first1=Hilary |title=Vice-Chancellor's Report to University Council 2016/2017 |url=https://www.uwi.edu/vcreport/docs/VCAR.pdf |website=University of the West Indies |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[University of Lagos]] (UNILAG) and the UWI established the  UNILAG-UWI Institute of African and Diaspora Studies.<ref name=Academia_in_Action /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rowe |first1=Sasha |title=UWI, UNILAG agree to African and diaspora studies institute |url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/career/uwi-unilag-agree-to-african-and-diaspora-studies-institute_99252 |accessdate=14 February 2019 |newspaper=Jamaica Observer |date=21 May 2017}}</ref>  The institute conducts research and offers a master's degree in African and Diaspora Studies.<ref name=\"VCAR2016/2017\" />\n\nAlso in 2017, UWI and the [[University of Johannesburg]] (UJ) signed a memorandum of agreement (MoA) to establish the Institute for Global Africa Affairs.<ref name=\"VCAR2016/2017\" /> The Institute was launched in 2018 and will offer a joint master's degree in Global African Studies.<ref>{{cite news |title=UWI and U. of Johannesburg launch Institute for Global African Affairs |url=http://www.looptt.com/content/uwi-and-u-johannesburg-launch-institute-global-african-affairs |accessdate=14 February 2019 |agency=LOOP News |date=24 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, UWI and the [[University of Havana]] inked an agreement to jointly establish the Institute for the Sustainable Development of the Caribbean. UWI Mona will lead the initiative from the UWI side, with the deans of the Faculty of Science and Technology and the Dean of the Faculty of Medical Sciences taking the lead.<ref>{{cite web |title=The UWI-University of Havana Institute for Sustainable Development |url=https://sta.uwi.edu/news/releases/release.asp?id=22037 |website=Campus News |publisher=UWI St. Augustine |accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther joint programmes exist or are in the planning stages.<ref name=Academia_in_Action /> For example, the [[University of New Brunswick]] and the [[University of the West Indies, Cave Hill Campus|Cave Hill Campus]] jointly offer a [https://www.unb.ca/fredericton/kinesiology/graduate/sport-sciences.html Master of Science in Sport Sciences]. [[Brock University]] and UWI have recently signed a memorandum of understanding to consider the establishment of an Institute in Canada-Caribbean Studies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Morrison |first1=Mike |title=Brock in talks with University of West Indies to create Institute for Canada-Caribbean Studies |url=https://brocku.ca/brock-news/2019/04/brock-in-talks-with-university-of-west-indies-to-create-institute-for-canada-caribbean-studies/ |website=The Brock News |publisher=Brock University |accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Faculties ==\nThe University of the West Indies is a multi-campus, international university with several faculties and schools, some of which are replicated on all four physical main campuses. The Open Campus does not have a faculty structure. The distribution of the faculties (called schools at Five Islands) is listed below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Cave Hill Campus\n!Five Islands Campus\n!Mona Campus\n!St. Augustine Campus\n|-\n|Humanities & Education\n|Humanities & Education\n|Humanities & Education\n|Humanities & Education\n|-\n|Law\n|\n|Law\n|Law\n|-\n|Medical Sciences\n|Health & Behavioural Sciences\n|Medical Sciences\n|Medical Sciences\n|-\n|Science & Technology\n|Management, Science & Technology\n|Science & Technology\n|Science & Technology\n|-\n|Social Sciences\n|Health & Behavioural Sciences\n|Social Sciences\n|Social Sciences\n|-\n|Sport\n|\n|Sport\n|Sport\n|-\n|\n|\n|Engineering\n|Engineering\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|Food & Agriculture\n|-\n|Culture, Creative and Performing Arts\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\nA new Faculty of Culture, Creative and Performing Arts has been approved to be established on 1 August 2020 at the Cave Hill Campus.<ref>{{cite news |title=UWI Cave Hill to launch Faculty of Culture, Creative and Performing Arts |url=https://buzz-caribbean.com/article/uwi-cave-hill-to-launch-faculty-of-culture-creative-and-performing-arts/ |accessdate=29 December 2019 |work=Buzz Caribbean |publisher=Ramble Media Corporation |date=27 Nov 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UWI Cave Hill Principal is now Prof. the Most Hon. V. Eudine Barriteau |url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/uwi-cave-hill-principal-now-prof-most-hon-v-eudine-barriteau |accessdate=29 December 2019 |work=Loop New Barbados |publisher=Trend Media |date=30 Nov 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Faculty of Culture, Creative and Performing Arts coming to The UWI, Cave Hill Campus |url=https://www.open.uwi.edu/new-faculty-culture-creative-and-performing-arts-coming-uwi-cave-hill-campus |website=UWI Open Campus News |publisher=The University of the West Indies |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty of Medical Sciences ===\nPrior to the establishment of a medical school in the Caribbean, most doctors were trained in the United Kingdom, with a smaller group trained in the United States of America. This was costly, not attuned to the specific needs of the communities the doctors would serve, and risked the trained doctors remaining in their countries of training.\n\nThe Faculty of Medical Sciences <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://medicine.yale.edu/education/gho/yalestudents/abroad/americari/jamaica.aspx |title = Jamaica}}</ref> was the first faculty to be established in the then University College.<ref name=\"Branday\">{{cite journal |last1=Branday |first1=JM |last2=Carpenter |first2=RA |title=The Evolution of Undergraduate Medical Training at The University of the West Indies, 1948-2008 |journal=West Indian Medical Journal |date=2008 |volume=57 |issue=6 |url=https://www.mona.uwi.edu/fms/wimj/system/files/article_pdfs/branday_the_evolution_of_undergraduate_medical_training_at_the_university_of_the_west_indies_etc.pdf |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> This is because of the pressing need for more (locally trained) doctors to treat conditions such as [[tuberculosis]], [[yaws]], [[tetanus]], [[typhoid]], infant [[malnutrition]] and illnesses related to [[diarrhea]]. The establishment of medical schools in the colonies was replicated in the Gold Coast, Nigeria, Rhodesia and Uganda.<ref name=Branday /> The inaugural entering class in 1948 consisted of 33 students from across the Caribbean, selected from more than 600<ref name=\"Fraser\">{{cite journal |last1=Fraser |first1=HS |title=The Faculties and School of Medical Sciences of The University of the West Indies at its Diamond Jubilee |journal=West Indian Medical Journal |date=2008 |volume=57 |issue=6 |url=https://www.mona.uwi.edu/fms/wimj/system/files/article_pdfs/fraser_the_faculties_and_school_of_medical_sciences_of_the_university_of_the_west_etc.pdf |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> or almost 800<ref name=Branday /> applicants. As the university college was then affiliated with the University of London, the curriculum reflected its curriculum, with the addition of preventative and tropical medicine. Degrees were awarded under the University of London name until 1962, reflective of the role the University played in administering the programme and providing the teaching staff.<ref name=Branday /> In addition to the standard five-year course, a pre-course science year was required for students without adequate preparation in that area. The University Hospital of the West Indies, an acute tertiary hospital, provided the initial context for clinical education.\n\nExpansion of the capacity of the Faculty followed several steps. In addition to population growth, the exodus of medical graduates to North America, never to return, exacerbated the need to increase the output of doctors.<ref name=Fraser /> In the 1960s, it was possible to complete the clinical clerkship element of training in Trinidad and Tobago (at the [[Port of Spain General Hospital]]) and in Barbados (at the [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Bridgetown|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]]), as well as in Jamaica.<ref name=Branday /> In 1989, the medical school at the St. Augustine campus opened. However, rather than adopt the 'traditional' existing curriculum at the Mona school, it adopted a problem-based approach.<ref name=Fraser /> Mona, which had already carried out some curricular reform due to World Health Organization recommendations to place greater emphasis on community health promotion and protection, and St. Augustine, had different medical school curricula, though the graduates took the same qualifying exams. Moreover, St. Augustine's Faculty of Medical Sciences included not just a School of Medicine, but also Schools of Dentistry, Veterinarian Medicine, Nursing and Pharmacy, which necessitated some sharing of resources.<ref name=Branday /><ref name=Fraser /> In 2008, the clerkships in Barbados were fully developed into a medical school at the Cave Hill campus. Around the same time, the UWI School of Clinical Medicine and Research was established from an existing programme allowing clerkships to be undertaken in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], under the direction of the St. Augustine campus.<ref name=Fraser />  The School offers the final two years of the five-year programme.\n\n==== Specialist Medical Training ====\nSimilar to the general training, specialist training was progressively made available through the UWI. For example, anaesthesia was initially provided by untrained doctors, nurses, and pharmacists, leading to high morbidity and mortality rates. Initially, doctors were sent overseas for a year of post-graduate training. While the Faculty was established in 1948, the one-year post-graduate diploma in anaesthetics did not begin until 1966 at the Mona Campus. St. Augustine and Cave Hill added the diploma in 1976. However, Mona was already moving towards a four-year Doctor of Medicine Anaesthetics degree, first offered in 1974. Eventually, this more specialised degree (extended to include ''intensive care'') was extended to the other two campuses in 1984 while the one-year programme was discontinued in 1994.<ref name=\"Anaesthetics\">{{cite journal |last1=Scarlett |first1=MD |last2=Crawford-Sykes |first2=A |last3=Harding |first3=HE |last4=Chen |first4=DR |title=The Development of Postgraduate Anaesthesia and Intensive Care Training at the University of the West Indies |journal=West Indian Medical Journal |date=July 2012 |volume=61 |issue=4 |pages=463\u2013466 |doi=10.7727/wimj.2012.147}}</ref>\n\nWhile improvements were being made to the training of physicians as anaesthesiologists, there continued to be a shortage of trained personnel in rural areas. In Jamaica, an initiative to train nurse anaesthetists started, with nurses first sent to the US and to Cuba, followed by the establishment of the Jamaica School of Nurse Anaesthetists in 1981, which continues to this day (2019) with the Ministry of Health. This is in addition to specialised additional training for nurses in intensive care which began in 1969.<ref name=Anaesthetics />\n\n==== Dentist Training ====\nTwo of the three faculties of medical sciences offer dentistry. The St. Augustine campus was the first to offer a dental school. It opened in 1989, the first dental school in the anglophone Caribbean. The inaugural class of roughly 20 students was mostly from Trinidad and Tobago, with a couple of students each from Jamaica and [[St. Vincent and the Grenadines]]. The initial curriculum was modeled on that found in the UK, with the intention to seek recognition from British authorities. It is possible to the exam for membership of the Faculty of Dental Surgery of the Edinburgh-based Royal College of Surgeons.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Naidu |first1=Rahul |last2=Ramroop |first2=Visha |last3=Rafeek |first3=Reisha |title=An Historical Overview of Dentistry in Trinidad and Tobago |journal=History in Action |date=2010 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201310 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/265424273_An_Historical_Overview_of_Dentistry_in_Trinidad_and_Tobago |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Accreditation ====\nStarting in 2004, the medical programmes in the Caribbean ceased to be accredited by the United Kingdom-based [[General Medical Council]], as the UK re-focussed more on integration with Europe.<ref name=Branday /> UWI was a key player in the establishment of the [[Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and other Health Professions]] (CAAM-HP). The three UWI medical schools are accredited together, despite differences in curriculum, and are currently accredited with conditions.<ref name=\"CAAM\">{{cite web |title=Programs |url=https://www.caam-hp.org/programs |website=Caribbean Accreditation Authority or Education in Medicine and Other Health Professions (CAAM-HP) |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> The dental school at St. Augustine is probationary accredited while the dental school at Mona has accreditation with conditions.<ref name=CAAM /> The veterinarian medical school at St. Augustine is also accredited with conditions.<ref name=CAAM /> Efforts are underway to align the curriculum and admission standards of the three medical schools.<ref name=Fraser />\n\n==== Regional Competition ====\nEven with expansion, the UWI medical schools are facing new competition. Many for-profit medical schools have been established in the Caribbean region, with the first established in [[Grenada]] in 1976.<ref name=Branday /> Generally, these schools cater to students from the United States but they sometimes offer scholarships to local students, providing an alternative to UWI programmes or going abroad for medical education [[Canada]], the [[United Kingdom]] or the [[United States]]. The quality of these offshore medical schools differ,<ref name=Branday /> though some are accredited by the CAAM-HP.<ref name=CAAM />\n\n==== Research ====\nThe Faculty of Medicines has a research arm called the Caribbean Institute for Health Research (CAIHR), formerly the Tropical Medicine Research Institute (TMRI). The CAIHR comprises the George Alleyne Chronic Disease Research Centre, based on the Cave Hill Campus, and three units all based on the Mona Campus: the Tropical Metabolism Research Unit, the Sickle Cell Unit and the Epidemiology Research Unit.<ref name=Fraser /> Continuing medical education is provided in different ways among the various countries with the medical associations taking the lead in some countries and the medical schools in others.<ref name=Fraser />\n\n=== Faculty of Law ===\nPrior to the establishment of the Faculty of Law at the UWI, residents of the anglophone Caribbean would travel primarily to the [[United Kingdom]] to study.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /> There, they would join an [[Inns of Court]] where they received lodging and training and underwent examinations. Naturally, the training focused on the legal system and social context of England, which was not the best foundation upon which to practice in the Caribbean.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /> It was also an expensive endeavor. For the legal profession in England, the influx of prospective lawyers from around the [[Commonwealth of Nations|British Commonwealth]] was beginning to strain resources. Efforts were underway to limit foreign students in legal studies in England and this was another reason to establish legal training in the Caribbean.\n\nThe Faculty of Law was initially established in 1970 at the Cave Hill Campus, in [[Barbados]],<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite web |last1=Barnett |first1=Lloyd |title=Report of the Review Committee on Legal Education in the Caribbean 1996 |url=http://www.clecaribbean.com/barnett.php |website=The Barnett Report |publisher=Council of Legal Education |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> but the first year of the degree was available at each campus (and the [[University of Guyana]] in [[Guyana]]).<ref name=\"Lazarus-Black_Law\">{{cite journal |last1=Lazarus-Black |first1=Mindie |title=After Empire: Training Lawyers as a Postcolonial Enterprise |journal=Small Axe |date=February 2008 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=38\u201356 |doi=10.1215/-12-1-38}}</ref>  This structure served, ''inter alia'', to create a regional institution (the Faculty) and a regional identity within the profession. Incrementally, courses from the second and third year of the law programmes were introduced at St. Augustine and Mona, allowing students to take more and more of the degree on those campuses, rather than having to study at Cave Hill. It is now possible to complete the law degree at each campus.<ref name=Barnett />\n\nFollowing completion of the UWI law degree, graduates who intend to practice must complete a two-year practical professional training programme at one of three law schools in the Caribbean. The [[Eugene Dupuch Law School]] in [[The Bahamas]] is normally for citizens of the Bahamas, the [[British Virgin Islands]] and the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]]. The [[Norman Manley Law School]] in [[Jamaica]] has allocated citizens from [[Anguilla]], [[Antigua and Barbuda]], [[Belize]], Jamaica, [[Montserrat]], and [[St. Kitts and Nevis]]. The [[Hugh Wooding Law School]] in [[Trinidad and Tobago]] serves Barbados, [[Dominica]], [[Grenada]], Guyana, [[St. Lucia]], [[St. Vincent and the Grenadines]], and Trinidad and Tobago.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /><ref name=Barnett /> The three schools were established by the Caribbean Council of Legal Education. Ironically, despite the Faculty of Law having been founded in Barbados, the country does not have a law school, though one has been mooted.<ref>{{cite web |title=Call for Barbados law school |url=http://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/175012/barbados-law-school |website=NationNews |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first law students, beginning studies in October 1970, consisted of 24 students in Jamaica, nineteen in Trinidad and Tobago, 35 in Barbados, and thirteen Guyana.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /> Two years later, almost 300 students were enrolled in the Faculty. The first graduates entered the profession in 1975.\n\nAccess to the Faculty of Law and to the Law Schools are controlled by the institutions. However, costs can vary depending on whether the applicant's country has paid contributory grants to the Faculty or the School. Not all countries did. Therefore, applicants from non-contributing countries would be considered after those from contributing countries and their fees would be higher.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law />\n\n=== Faculty of Sport ===\nLaunched in 2017, the UWI Faculty of Sport integrates teaching and research, professional development, community partnerships, and co- and extra-curricular student sport through three main units: Professional Programmes, Outreach & Projects Unit, Co-curricular & Intramural-Activity Unit and the Academic Programme & Activity Unit. The faculty is made up of four Academies of Sport: Cave Hill Academy of Sport, Open Campus Academy of Sport, Mona Academy of Sport and St Augustine Academy of Sport.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parchment |first1=Rachid |title=UWI Launches Faculty of Sports |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20170727/uwi-launches-faculty-sports |accessdate=2 January 2020 |work=The Gleaner |publisher=RJRGLEANER Communications Group |date=27 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UWI launches Faculty of Sport |url=https://caricom.org/communications/view/uwi-launches-faculty-of-sport |website=CariCom |publisher=Caribbean Community |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== UWI Press ==\nFounded in 1992, the University of the West Indies Press is a department within The University of the West Indies system located in Jamaica.<ref>[http://www.uwipress.com/ University of the West Indies Press], Official website</ref>  Supported by a regionally assembled board or directors, UWI Press acts as the overall publishing arm of the main UWI campuses, and its faculty and student body of the Open Campus where it additionally serves the diverse network of 17 countries and territories.  As an entity that caters to a readership around the world, UWI Press maintains a main commitment to traditional fields of: Caribbean history, social sciences, political science and cultural studies.\n\n== Rankings ==\nAccording to the 2019 Times Higher Education World University Rankings, UWI ranked in the 501-600 band, the first time it has ranked among the 1,258 universities on the list.<ref>{{cite web |title=World University Rankings 2019 |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/world-ranking#!/page/23/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats |website=Times Higher Education |accessdate=13 April 2019|date=2018-09-26 }}</ref> It is the only university from the Caribbean to make the list. Its ranking places it in the top 5% of universities globally and it is the best in the Caribbean.[https://www.uwi.edu/ranking/] The 2019 Times Higher Education ranks UWI Mona 32nd on its Latin America University rankings.<ref>{{cite news |title=New rankings put UWI among top 5 percent of best universities globally. |url=http://www.loopjamaica.com/content/new-rankings-put-uwi-among-top-5-percent-best-universities-globally |accessdate=13 April 2019 |publisher=Loop News |date=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Chancellors of the University ==\n* [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]], 1948\u201371 <ref name = QC>{{cite book|title=The University of the West Indies: A Quinquagenary Calendar, 1948-1998|page=App A}}</ref>\n*Sir [[Hugh Wooding]], 1971\u201374 <ref name=\"QC\" />\n* Sir [[Allen Montgomery Lewis]] 1974\u201389 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[Shridath Ramphal]] 1989\u20132003 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[George Alleyne]] 2003\u20132017 <ref name = QC/>\n* Robert Bermudez 2017\u2013 current\n\n== Vice-Chancellors of the University ==\n'''Principals'''\n\n* Sir [[Thomas Taylor (chemist)|Thomas Taylor]] 1947\u201352 <ref name = QC/> \n* [[Walter Wyatt Grave]] 1953\u201358  <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[William Arthur Lewis]] 1958\u201360  <ref name = QC/>\n\n'''Vice-Chancellors'''\n\n* Sir [[William Arthur Lewis]] 1960\u201363 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir Philip Sherlock 1963\u201369 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[Roy Marshall (academic)|O Roy Marshall]] 1969\u201374 <ref name = QC/>\n* Hon Dr Aston Zachariah Preston 1974\u201386 <ref name = QC/>\n* ''Pro-vice-chancellor L R B Robinson acting 1986\u201388'' <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir Alister McIntyre 1988\u20131998 <ref name = QC/>\n* [[Rex Nettleford]] 1998\u20132004\n* Eon Nigel Harris 2004\u20132015\n* [[Hilary Beckles]] 2015\u2013\n\n== Notable faculty and administrators ==\n*[[Helen Asemota]]: professor of biochemistry and biotechnology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mona.uwi.edu/marcom/newsroom/entry/2828|title=HELEN ASEMOTA PROMOTED TO PROFESSOR {{!}} Marketing and Communications Office, The University of West Indies at Mona|website=www.mona.uwi.edu|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n*[[Elsa Goveia]]: first female professor of UCWI and noted pioneer in West Indian [[historiography]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Higman|first=B. W.|title=General History of the Caribbean|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E12cpltazYgC&pg=PA337|volume=VI: Methodology and historiography of the Caribbean|year=1999|publisher=UNESCO|location=London, England|isbn=978-92-3-103360-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Dr. Elsa Goveia is dead|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/jm/kingston/kingston/kingston-gleaner/clippings/Obituary-Death-Notice/166180/|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=[[Gleaner Company|The Daily Gleaner]]|date=20 March 1980|location=Kingston, Jamaica|via = [[Newspaperarchive.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>\n* [[Patrick Hosein]]: Professor in Computer Science at UWI St Augustine Campus.<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/phosein/ \"Patrick Hosein\"], LinkedIn.</ref>\n* [[Bridget Jones (academic)|Bridget Jones]] (1935-2000): pioneering Literature and language professor from 1964\u20131982, who developed curricula to include Afro-, Anglo- and Franco-Caribbean writers in university syllabai at UWI and in Britain and Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aub-Buscher |first1=Gertrud |title=Bridget Jones |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/apr/17/guardianobituaries |accessdate=6 July 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 April 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509042146/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/apr/17/guardianobituaries |archivedate=9 May 2014 |location=London, England}}</ref>\n* [[Sheila Dorothy King|Dorothy King]]: head of the Microbiology Department of the medical faculty from 1973\u20132001.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Professor of Microbiology: Dr. Sheila King Makes History|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/susun-wilkinson-celebrity-clipping-jul-04-1983-428353/|accessdate=1 February 2018|newspaper=[[The Gleaner (newspaper)|The Gleaner]]|date=4 July 1983|location=Kingstown, Jamaica|page=21|via = [[Newspaperarchive.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>\n* [[Elsa Leo-Rhynie]]: Principal of the Mona campus.\n* [[William Arthur Lewis]]: economist, lecturer, author and joint winner of [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics]] of 1979.\n* [[Albert Belville Lockhart]]:  Consultant and Ophthalmologist, Recipient of the [[Jamaican Order of Merit]], co-inventor of [[Canasol]].<ref name=\"J Homi 1996\">M. E. West and J. Homi. \"Cannabis as a medicine\". ''Br. J. Anaesth'' (1996) 76(1): 167 {{doi|10.1093/bja/76.1.167-a}}</ref>\n* [[Kim Mallalieu]]: Senior Lecturer in Computer and Electrical Engineering at UWI St Augustine.<ref>[https://sta.uwi.edu/eng/electrical/staff/kim_mallalieu.asp \"Dr. Kim Mallalieu\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406110355/https://sta.uwi.edu/eng/electrical/staff/kim_mallalieu.asp |date=2017-04-06 }}, The Faculty of Engineering, UWI St Augustine.</ref><ref>[http://sta.uwi.edu/news/releases/release.asp?id=562 \"UWI Students win MIT Technology Innovation Award\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032703/http://sta.uwi.edu/news/releases/release.asp?id=562 |date=2017-12-01 }}, UWI St Augustine, 21 May 2010.</ref>\n* [[Evelyn O'Callaghan]]: Professor of West Indian literature, Dean of the Faculty of Humanities and Education.\n* [[Donna-Maria Maynard]]: Professor of Psychology, Faculty of Humanities & Education, Cave Hill Campus.\n* [[Orlando Patterson]]: John Cowles Professor of Sociology at Harvard University.<ref>[http://scholar.harvard.edu/patterson/home \"Orlando Patterson\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828212009/http://scholar.harvard.edu/patterson/home |date=2016-08-28 }}, Harvard Department of Sociology.</ref>\n*[[Manley West|Manley Elisha West]]: Professor of Pharmacology, recipient of the [[Jamaican Order of Merit]], co-inventor of [[Canasol]].<ref name=\"J Homi 1996\"/>\n*[[Courtenay Felix Bartholomew]]: the first lecturer and then Professor of Medicine at UWI St Augustine.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://icons.niherst.gov.tt/icon/courtenay-bartholomew-ci1/|title=Courtenay Bartholomew|date=2017-06-23|work=Icons|access-date=2018-11-09|publisher=The National Institute of Higher Education, Research, Science and Technology (NIHERST), [[Government of Trinidad and Tobago]]|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n[[File:WalcottenDeKom.jpg|thumb|Sir Derek Walcott studied at the University of the West Indies]]\n\nUWI graduates who are, or have been, heads of government:\n* [[Kenny Anthony]], former prime minister of St. Lucia\n* [[Owen Arthur]], former prime minister of Barbados\n* [[Dean Barrow]], prime minister of Belize\n* [[Denzil Douglas]], former prime minister of St. Kitts & Nevis\n* [[Rufus Ewing]], premier of the Turks and Caicos Islands\n* [[Bruce Golding]], former prime minister of Jamaica\n* [[Ralph Gonsalves]], prime minister of St. Vincent and the Grenadines\n* [[David A. Granger]], president of Guyana\n* [[Andrew Holness]], prime minister of Jamaica[[File:Andrew Holness cropped.jpg|thumb|Andrew Holness]]\n* [[Patrick Manning]], former prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago\n* [[Hubert Minnis]], prime minister of The Bahamas\n* [[Keith Mitchell]], prime minister of Grenada\n* [[Joseph Walcott Parry]], former premier of Nevis\n* [[P. J. Patterson]], former prime minister of Jamaica\n* [[Kamla Persad-Bissessar]], first female prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago\n* [[Keith Rowley]]: prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago[[File:KeithRowley.jpg|thumb|244x244px|[[Keith Rowley]]: prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n* [[Lloyd Erskine Sandiford]], former prime minister of Barbados\n* [[Kennedy A. Simmonds]], former prime minister of St. Kitts & Nevis\n* [[Orlando Smith]], chief minister of the British Virgin Islands\n* [[Freundel Stuart]], former prime minister of Barbados\n* [[David Thompson (Barbadian politician)|David Thompson]], former prime minister of Barbados\n\nGraduates in other fields:\n* [[Sharon Aarons]], Australian soil scientist\n* [[Anita Allen (judge)|Dame Anita Allen]], president of the Court of Appeal of The Bahamas\n* [[Faris Al-Rawi]], Attorney General of Trinidad and Tobago\n* [[Pamela Coke-Hamilton]] Director of International Trade for [[UNCTAD]] \n* [[Merceline Dahl-Regis]], Bahamian physician, former Chief Medical Officer of the Bahamas\n* [[Edwidge Danticat]], Haitian poet and writer\n* [[Fae Ellington]], Jamaican media personality and lecturer\n* [[Burton P. C. Hall]], judge of the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia]] and former Chief Justice of The Bahamas\n* [[Marlon James (novelist)|Marlon James]], Jamaican-born winner of the 2015 Man Booker Prize for Fiction\n* [[Kwame Dawes]]\n*[[Joan Latchman]], Director of the University of the West Indies Seismic Research Centre\n* [[Dolliver Nelson]], member of the [[International Tribunal for the Law of the Sea]]\n* [[Kris Rampersad]], journalist, author, cultural advocate\n* [[Patrick Lipton Robinson]], judge of the [[International Court of Justice]]\n* [[Walter Rodney]], Guyanese historian and political activist\n* [[Richard Sealy]], Barbadian Tourism Minister\n* [[Olive Senior]], Jamaican novelist and writer\n* [[Sheik Mohamed Khan]], Climate Change Expert, Ministry of Agriculture, Government of Guyana\n* [[Shafimana Ueitele]], Namibian lawyer \n* [[Derek Walcott]], Nobel Prize for Literature (1992)\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Jamaica|Trinidad|Caribbean}}\n* [[Agence universitaire de la Francophonie]]\n* [[Association of Commonwealth Universities]]\n* [[University of the West Indies Museum]]\n* [[University of Guyana]]\n* [[University of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n* [[University of Technology, Jamaica]]\n* [[University of the Bahamas]]\n* [[University of the French West Indies]]\n* [[University of French Guiana]]\n* [[Savacou (sculpture)|Savacou]], a sculpture on the Mona site\n* [[University of the South Pacific]], a similar university for Pacific Island states\n* [[Historically black colleges and universities]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official|http://www.uwi.edu/ }}\n\n=== Main Campus websites ===\n* [http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu/ Cave Hill Campus, Barbados]\n* [http://www.mona.uwi.edu/ Mona Campus, Jamaica]\n* [http://www.open.uwi.edu/index.php/ Open Campus]\n* [http://www.sta.uwi.edu/ St. Augustine Campus, Trinidad & Tobago]\n* [http://fiveislands.uwi.edu/ Five Islands Campus, Antigua & Barbuda]\n\n==== Regional Campuses ====\n* [https://www.mona.uwi.edu/wjc/ Western Jamaica Campus]\n* [http://www.uwichsb.org/ Cave Hill School of Business]\n* [http://sta.uwi.edu/fms Eric Williams Medical Sciences Complex, Mount Hope, Trinidad and Tobago]\n\n=== Other links ===\n* [http://wikimapia.org/#lat=18.002978&lon=-76.744566&z=15&l=0&m=b&v=8 Aerial view of Mona Campus]\n* [http://barbadosbymap.com/index.php?mapSet=27&mapItem=108 Satellite view of the Cave Hill campus]\n* [https://www.uwi.edu/ProgrammesbyCampus.asp List of Programmes offered through UWI]\n\n=== Caribbean Studies ===\n*[https://www.mona.uwi.edu/humed/ics/ Institute of Caribbean Studies, UWI, Mona]\n*[http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu/fhe/LLL/graduate-studies/interdisciplinary-ma-in-caribbean-studies.aspx Interdisciplinary MA in Caribbean Studies, UWI, Cave Hill]\n*[https://sta.uwi.edu/fhe/dlcc/culturalstudies.asp Caribbean Cultural Studies, UWI, St. Augustine]\n\n{{University of the West Indies}}\n{{Caribbean topic|List of universities and colleges in}}\n{{Education in British Overseas Territories}}\n{{Americas topic|Education in}}\n{{coord|18.0029784|-76.744566|region:JM_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Indies, University Of The}}\n[[Category:University of the West Indies]]\n[[Category:Universities in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:British West Indies|University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1948]]\n[[Category:1948 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Saint Andrew Parish, Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Education in British Overseas Territories]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the University of the West Indies system and its flagship constituent unit in [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], [[Jamaica]]|other uses|University of the West Indies (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|University of the French West Indies}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n| name = The University of the West Indies\n| image_name = Coat of arms of the University of the West Indies.png\n| motto = Oriens Ex Occidente Lux ([[Latin]])\n| mottoeng = A Light Rising From The West\n| established = 1948\n| type = Regional university, [[public]], autonomous\n| chancellor = Robert Bermudez\n| vice_chancellor = [[Hilary Beckles]]\n| students = near 50,000 (across 5 campuses)<ref>{{cite web |title=The University of the West Indies |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/university-west-indies |website=THE World University Rankings |publisher=Times Higher Education |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n| city = \n| country = \n| campus = [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], [[Jamaica]] (headquarters)\n| mascot = The Pelican\n| website = [http://www.uwi.edu www.uwi.edu]<br />[http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu UWI Cave Hill]<br />[http://sta.uwi.edu UWI St. Augustine]<br />[http://www.mona.uwi.edu UWI Mona]<br />[http://www.open.uwi.edu UWI Open Campus] <br /> [http://fiveislands.uwi.edu UWI Five Islands Campus]\n| faculty = 1,200\n| affiliations = Association of Commonwealth Universities (ACU)<br /> [[Caribbean Community]]\n}}\n[[File:TnT St. Augustine UWI Campus.jpg|thumb|St. Augustine UWI Campus]]\n[[File:Continuing Promise 2015 150512-A-OM702-004.jpg|thumb]]\n\n'''The University of the West Indies''' ('''UWI'''), originally '''University College of the West Indies''',<ref name=hosp>{{cite web|url=http://uhwi.gov.jm/about/history|title=History of the UHWI - University Hospital of the West Indies|website=uhwi.gov.jm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.uwi.edu/gradingpolicy/scale.html |title = Grading Scale}}</ref> is a public university system established to serve the [[higher education]] needs of the residents of 17 English-speaking [[countries]] and [[Territory (country subdivision)|territories]] in the [[Caribbean]]: [[Anguilla]], [[Antigua and Barbuda]], [[The Bahamas]], [[Barbados]], [[Belize]], [[Bermuda]], [[British Virgin Islands]], [[Cayman Islands]], [[Dominica]], [[Grenada]],  [[Jamaica]], [[Montserrat]], [[St. Kitts and Nevis]], [[St. Lucia]], [[St. Vincent and the Grenadines]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], and [[Turks and Caicos Islands]].\nEach country is either a member of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] or a [[British Overseas Territory]]. The aim of the university is to help 'unlock the potential for economic and cultural growth' in the [[West Indies]], thus allowing improved regional autonomy.<ref>''The University of the West Indies, A Quinquagenary Calendar 1948-1998'',Douglas Hall,1998.Jamaica, The Press, University of the West Indies</ref> The University was originally instituted as an independent external college of the [[University of London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uwiarchives.wordpress.com/2015/04/22/happy-89th-birthday-to-the-visitor/|title=Happy 90th Birthday to the Visitor!!!|date=22 April 2015|website=wordpress.com|accessdate=4 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504024227/https://uwiarchives.wordpress.com/2015/04/22/happy-89th-birthday-to-the-visitor/|archivedate=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University has produced students who have excelled in a number of disciplines such as the arts and sciences, business, politics, and sports. Notable alumni and faculty include three [[Nobel Laureates]], 72 [[Rhodes Scholars]], 3 [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]] winners, 1 [[Emmy award]] winner,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.escapeartist.com/blog/antigua-and-barbuda-citizenship-new-university-fund-option/ | title=Antigua and Barbuda Citizenship \u2014 New University Fund Option| date=2018-10-18}}</ref> 1 [[Man Booker Prize]] winner, 1 [[American Book Awards]] winner, 18 current or former Caribbean Heads of Government, an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] medallist and other award winners. The [[University of the West Indies cricket team|university's cricket team]] previously participated in [[Cricket in the West Indies|West Indian domestic cricket]], but now participates as part of a [[Combined Campuses and Colleges cricket team|Combined Campuses and Colleges]] team.\n\nThe UWI campus in [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], [[Jamaica]] serves as the headquarters of the UWI system. Aside from UWI Mona, it has four (4) major university centers: [[University of the West Indies at Cave Hill|UWI Cave Hill]] (Barbados), [[University of the West Indies at St. Augustine|UWI St. Augustine]] (Trinidad and Tobago), [[University of the West Indies at Five Islands|UWI Five Islands]] (Antigua and Barbuda), and the regional [[University of the West Indies Open Campus|UWI Open Campus]] that is scattered among UWI-funding Caribbean nations.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:UWI Mona Campus Main Library.jpg|thumb|Main Library, Mona Campus, Jamaica]]\nThe university was founded in 1948, on the recommendation of the Asquith Commission<ref>[http://www.bcn.cl/obtienearchivo?id=documentos/10221.1/29331/2/213787.pdf \"Report of the Commission on Higher Education in the Colonies\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045338/http://www.bcn.cl/obtienearchivo?id=documentos%2F10221.1%2F29331%2F2%2F213787.pdf |title= |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref> through its sub-committee on the West Indies chaired by Sir James Irvine.<ref>''Report of the West Indies Committee of the Commission on Higher Education in the Colonies'', Presented by the Secretary of State for the Colonies to Parliament by Command of His Majesty June 1945. London, His Majesty\u2019s Stationery Office</ref> The Asquith Commission had been established in 1943 to review the provision of higher education in the British colonies. Initially in a special relationship with the [[University of London]], the then University College of the West Indies (UCWI) was seated at [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]], about five miles from [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], Jamaica. The university was based at the [[Gibraltar Camp]] used by [[Evacuation of the Gibraltarian civilian population during World War II|evacuated Gibraltarians during the war]].<ref name=brown>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Suzanne Francis|title=Mona Past and Present: The History and Heritage of the Mona Campus, University of the West Indies|pages=10\u201311|year=2006|publisher=University of the West Indies Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EQ63yTgVkaEC|isbn=9789766401597}}</ref><ref name=\"Tortello\">{{Cite news |url=http://old.jamaica-gleaner.com/pages/history/story0069.html |title=Pieces of the Past: Out Of Many Cultures: Gibraltar Camp a Refuge from war |last=Tortello |first=Rebecca |date=7 November 2005 |work=Jamaica Gleaner  |access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeeking to address a need for medical care the first faculty established was a medical school.<ref name=hosp/> The foundation stone for a hospital was added in 1949 and the University College Hospital of the West Indies opened in 1953. On 18 January 1953, Sir [[Winston Churchill]] visited the hospital on 18 January 1953 and unveiled a plaque in recognition of the contribution made by the government of the United Kingdom to the hospital.<ref name=hosp/> The hospital was renamed the '''University Hospital of the West Indies''' in 1967 when the University gained full university status.<ref name=hosp/> The hospital offers patient care, the hospital also facilitates research and teaching along with the Medical Services department of the Mona campus of the University of the West Indies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/UHWI--UWI-team-up-for-completion-of-hospital-s-overhaul_87950 |title=UHWI, UWI team up for completion of hospital's overhaul |last=Henry |first=Balford |date=29 January 2017 |website=Jamaica Observer |access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University College achieved independent university status in 1962.  The St Augustine Campus in Trinidad, formerly the Imperial College of Tropical Agriculture (ICTA), was established in 1960, followed by a school established along University Row, at the [[Port of Bridgetown|Deep Water Harbour]] of Barbados in 1963, later seated at the present Cave Hill Campus in 1967. The establishment of the Open Campus, University Centres, headed by a Resident Tutor, were established in each of the other 13 contributing territories thereafter.\n\nIn 1950, [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]], the last surviving granddaughter of [[Queen Victoria]], became the first Chancellor of the University College of the West Indies.\n\nSir [[William Arthur Lewis]] was the first Vice-Chancellor under the UWI's independent Charter. A native of [[St Lucia]], he served as the first West Indian Principal of the UCWI from 1958 to 1960 and as Vice-Chancellor from 1960 to 1963. He was succeeded by Sir Philip Sherlock (a Jamaican and one of the UWI's founding fathers) who served as Vice-Chancellor from 1963 to 1969. Sir [[Roy Marshall (academic)|Roy Marshall]], a Barbadian, was the next Vice-Chancellor, serving from 1969 to 1974. He was succeeded by Dr Aston Zachariah Preston, a Jamaican, who died in office on 24 June 1986, having served from 1974. The fifth Vice-Chancellor was Sir Alister McIntyre, who served from 1988 to 1998, followed by alumnus and Professor Emeritus [[Rex Nettleford]] who served from 1998 to 2004. The current Vice-Chancellor is Professor Sir [[Hilary Beckles]], who succeeded Professor E. Nigel Harris in May 2015.\n\nThe [[University of the West Indies Museum]] catalogs and exhibits some of the university's history.\n\n== University of the West Indies System ==\nThe UWI is the largest, most longstanding higher education provider in the Commonwealth Caribbean, with five constituent campuses: \n* [https://www.mona.uwi.edu/ Mona] in Jamaica \n* [[University of the West Indies at St. Augustine|St. Augustine]] in Trinidad and Tobago,<ref name=\"sta.uwi.edu\">{{Cite web | url=https://sta.uwi.edu/internationaloffice/courses |title = Partner Institutions &#124; UWI International Office}}</ref> \n* [[University of the West Indies, Cave Hill|Cave Hill]] in Barbados,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://cavehill.uwi.edu/ |title = The University of the West Indies at Cave Hill, Barbados}}</ref>\n* [[University of the West Indies at Five Islands|Five Islands]], [[Antigua and Barbuda]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwi.edu/featured-story/fiveislandscampus.asp|title=New UWI Campus in Antigua and Barbuda|date=26 June 2019|author=Professor Sir Hilary Beckles (Vice-Chancellor)|work=University of the West Indies}}</ref>\n* [[University of the West Indies Open Campus | Open Campus ]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.open.uwi.edu/ | title=Home &#124; WWW.open.uwi.edu}}</ref> serving 17 Caribbean island-nations.\n\nThe following are the satellite campuses of the university system:\n* Mount Hope Campus in Mount Hope, Trinidad and Tobago (houses the Faculty of Medical Sciences of UWI St. Augustine)\n* St. Augustine South Campus at [[Debe]] in the Penal-Debe region, Trinidad and Tobago (extension campus of UWI St. Augustine)<ref>{{cite web |title=Message from the Principal: Welcome to The UWI, St. Augustine South Campus, Penal-Debe |url=https://sta.uwi.edu/uwitoday/archive/august_2015/article2.asp |website=UWI Today |publisher=The University of the West Indies St. Augustine |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kristian |first1=De Silva |title=UWI to move in Debe campus in new academic year |url=https://www.guardian.co.tt/news/uwi-to-move-in-debe-campus-in-new-academic-year-6.2.832291.82fda5b463 |accessdate=29 December 2019 |work=Trinidad and Tobago Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media |date=25 Apr 2019}}</ref>\n* Western Jamaica Campus in [[Montego Bay]], Jamaica (extension campus of UWI Mona)\n* Centre for Hotel and Tourism Management in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], Bahamas (extension campus of UWI Mona)\n* School of Clinical Medicine and Research in Nassau, Bahamas (extension of the medical programme at UWI St. Augustine)<ref>{{cite web |title=UWI School of Medicine graduates offered training opportunities at PMH |url=http://www.bahamas.gov.bs/wps/portal/public/gov/government/news/uwi%20school%20of%20medicine%20graduates%20offered%20training%20opportunities%20at%20pmh/!ut/p/b1/vZRdr6I6FIZ_y_4BblqgFC6LQEEERL65IaiIoCLyoeCvH3cyyZw5ycy5OTPtVZM36-l6VlMmZRIIJcSxEsdzTMykTf6oynyobk1--TqnQsYBahHCi5aoCQQYAadxyCQcdSETMbGe8FjprVJVvUd_g-tlNq_01R5th0mlci6qIe92TtzJQpQXRycP0ke-VsfIxQAfvV3WJ2ct8lt77Q51Pqc0WT87ZJjQ7anRXs2mQ2PJVs5laTVKlfC9FRi36QJpv96FCVD1oHxO-2QZ7Od2ttwz3Ln-XOQn1khHolS9lrXWpZUQG90PWgec7EXxHUk0PV6khksWtT5JI3sMS5kLFg9BPMrgXkTux8e7-eTdPPjFIuC_3aQ_RxzWl4ABl1AwAwQUgf0e-A0ieQfwjwrUD8G7AiBbD7pAxJjxmRjwmVfPrfE6v7Y1eLJD7bI2JgAqAef5emT7mukdtnZfuxNQgtmrrdn3tY1Vy5Y9-JtDuA1kQtrhUDj_Bv58ZY9yfxpIkSO-NWJ_QxD7ViD8bSD6U0DqWO7yS6kvfynldJ0Ia85R4d8G_v8zXDFptbt-PvfXT_CJeIiQBFlJYDGLIWbCLuGnXWlNCvGy5zm9rO24BY9e1l572V-sUnnpmWe9isSsN8rtwjWGYExvurzoYZbWtnQQqeYUhSZx91W3656dGtGl1O72FT3dYtCN2-WOGg1iWQldB2l_dzi-aNS4oEEclXBNchW5ymiTFJh8WJn7l2ldtb57v67bRalm1X7i9uTY093QD0Fb6uElwYMcRPjgs3pt5yaBCyxKDXY3r2DknvqqjOJmPOV2Nb060T_oMxUf22yTbiaxqxcPVTlJ4cor37-Ird-uBXNNu3lxPtr_3Dz5-PgGRp15-A!!/dl4/d5/L2dBISEvZ0FBIS9nQSEh/ |website=Press Release |publisher=The Government of the Bahamas |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe other contributing countries are served by the Open Campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.open.uwi.edu/|title=The University of the West Indies - Open Campus|accessdate=22 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020191630/http://www.open.uwi.edu/|archivedate=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Proposed ===\nThere have been various proposals to add one or more campuses on other islands to expand the UWI system, such as a campus at Hope, Grenada<ref>[https://www.gov.gd/egov/news/2012/jul12/20_07_12/item_1/govt_land_UWI.html Government hands over land to UWI]\nFriday, July 20, 2012, St. George's, Grenada</ref><ref>[https://www.caribjournal.com/2012/07/22/grenada-hands-over-land-for-university-of-the-west-indies-campus/ Grenada Hands Over Land for University of the West Indies Campus]</ref>. The campus at Five Islands, Antigua and Barbuda opened in 2019.\n\n=== Articulation and Franchised Programmes ===\nIn addition to programmes offered directly by one of the faculties of the University, the UWI also extends accessibility to its programmes through articulation agreements and franchise arrangements with regional institutions. In many of these arrangements, students are able to study in their home countries for the first one or two years before going to a landed campus for the third (and fourth) year.<ref name=\"Martin & Bray\">{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=Michaela |last2=Bray |first2=Mark |title=Tertiary education in small states : planning in the context of globalization |date=2011 |publisher=Unesco Pub. |location=Paris, France |isbn=978-92-803-1358-1 |url=https://unesdoc.unesco.org/in/documentViewer.xhtml?v=2.1.196&id=p::usmarcdef_0000212196&file=/in/rest/annotationSVC/DownloadWatermarkedAttachment/attach_import_15acee17-98ea-49cb-acfb-23bf452ce3d7%3F_%3D212196eng.pdf&locale=en&multi=true&ark=/ark:/48223/pf0000212196/PDF/212196eng.pdf#%5B%7B%22num%22%3A826%2C%22gen%22%3A0%7D%2C%7B%22name%22%3A%22XYZ%22%7D%2Cnull%2Cnull%2C0%5D |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref> In the case of articulation agreements, the local institution develops its own programme and the UWI agrees to recognise it as equivalent to the first year or two of a specific UWI programme. In the case of a franchise programme, the local institution delivers exactly the programme as offered by UWI. This is usually the first year or two, but can be the full bachelor's degree on occasion.\n\n== Global initiatives ==\nThe University of the West Indies has initiated several international partnerships. In 2016, UWI and the Global Institute for Software Technology (GIST) established the UWI-China Institute for Information Technology.<ref name=\"Academia_in_Action\">{{cite web |title=Academia in Action. The UWI at 70: The Next Phase |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/sites/default/files/institution_downloads/uwi_next_phase.pdf |website=Times Higher Education |publisher=University of the West Indies |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref> Starting in the summer of 2018, students in the programme on the Cave Hill and Mona campuses will travel to [[Suchou]], [[China]] for two years. studying both Mandarin and software engineering.<ref>{{cite news |title=Students off to China from UWI to further study Software Engineering |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/students-china-uwi-further-study-software-engineering-1 |accessdate=14 February 2019 |publisher=LOOP News |date=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe UWI-[[SUNY]] Center for Leadership and Sustainable Development (CLSD) was established in 2017 on SUNY's Empire State campus in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=Academia_in_Action /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Simon |first1=Alexandra |title=University of West Indies partners with SUNY |url=https://www.caribbeanlifenews.com/stories/2017/2/cl-uwi-suny-partnership-2017-02-03-bk.html |accessdate=14 February 2019 |publisher=Caribbean Life |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\nThe centre is designed to assist the Commonwealth Caribbean in meeting the [[United Nations]] [[Sustainable Development Goals]]. In addition to research and advocacy, plans are underway to offer a joint master's degree in sustainability and leadership.<ref name=\"VCAR2016/2017\">{{cite web |last1=Beckles |first1=Hilary |title=Vice-Chancellor's Report to University Council 2016/2017 |url=https://www.uwi.edu/vcreport/docs/VCAR.pdf |website=University of the West Indies |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[University of Lagos]] (UNILAG) and the UWI established the  UNILAG-UWI Institute of African and Diaspora Studies.<ref name=Academia_in_Action /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rowe |first1=Sasha |title=UWI, UNILAG agree to African and diaspora studies institute |url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/career/uwi-unilag-agree-to-african-and-diaspora-studies-institute_99252 |accessdate=14 February 2019 |newspaper=Jamaica Observer |date=21 May 2017}}</ref>  The institute conducts research and offers a master's degree in African and Diaspora Studies.<ref name=\"VCAR2016/2017\" />\n\nAlso in 2017, UWI and the [[University of Johannesburg]] (UJ) signed a memorandum of agreement (MoA) to establish the Institute for Global Africa Affairs.<ref name=\"VCAR2016/2017\" /> The Institute was launched in 2018 and will offer a joint master's degree in Global African Studies.<ref>{{cite news |title=UWI and U. of Johannesburg launch Institute for Global African Affairs |url=http://www.looptt.com/content/uwi-and-u-johannesburg-launch-institute-global-african-affairs |accessdate=14 February 2019 |agency=LOOP News |date=24 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, UWI and the [[University of Havana]] inked an agreement to jointly establish the Institute for the Sustainable Development of the Caribbean. UWI Mona will lead the initiative from the UWI side, with the deans of the Faculty of Science and Technology and the Dean of the Faculty of Medical Sciences taking the lead.<ref>{{cite web |title=The UWI-University of Havana Institute for Sustainable Development |url=https://sta.uwi.edu/news/releases/release.asp?id=22037 |website=Campus News |publisher=UWI St. Augustine |accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther joint programmes exist or are in the planning stages.<ref name=Academia_in_Action /> For example, the [[University of New Brunswick]] and the [[University of the West Indies, Cave Hill Campus|Cave Hill Campus]] jointly offer a [https://www.unb.ca/fredericton/kinesiology/graduate/sport-sciences.html Master of Science in Sport Sciences]. [[Brock University]] and UWI have recently signed a memorandum of understanding to consider the establishment of an Institute in Canada-Caribbean Studies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Morrison |first1=Mike |title=Brock in talks with University of West Indies to create Institute for Canada-Caribbean Studies |url=https://brocku.ca/brock-news/2019/04/brock-in-talks-with-university-of-west-indies-to-create-institute-for-canada-caribbean-studies/ |website=The Brock News |publisher=Brock University |accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Faculties ==\nThe University of the West Indies is a multi-campus, international university with several faculties and schools, some of which are replicated on all four physical main campuses. The Open Campus does not have a faculty structure. The distribution of the faculties (called schools at Five Islands) is listed below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Cave Hill Campus\n!Five Islands Campus\n!Mona Campus\n!St. Augustine Campus\n|-\n|Humanities & Education\n|Humanities & Education\n|Humanities & Education\n|Humanities & Education\n|-\n|Law\n|\n|Law\n|Law\n|-\n|Medical Sciences\n|Health & Behavioural Sciences\n|Medical Sciences\n|Medical Sciences\n|-\n|Science & Technology\n|Management, Science & Technology\n|Science & Technology\n|Science & Technology\n|-\n|Social Sciences\n|Health & Behavioural Sciences\n|Social Sciences\n|Social Sciences\n|-\n|Sport\n|\n|Sport\n|Sport\n|-\n|\n|\n|Engineering\n|Engineering\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|Food & Agriculture\n|-\n|Culture, Creative and Performing Arts\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\nA new Faculty of Culture, Creative and Performing Arts has been approved to be established on 1 August 2020 at the Cave Hill Campus.<ref>{{cite news |title=UWI Cave Hill to launch Faculty of Culture, Creative and Performing Arts |url=https://buzz-caribbean.com/article/uwi-cave-hill-to-launch-faculty-of-culture-creative-and-performing-arts/ |accessdate=29 December 2019 |work=Buzz Caribbean |publisher=Ramble Media Corporation |date=27 Nov 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UWI Cave Hill Principal is now Prof. the Most Hon. V. Eudine Barriteau |url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/uwi-cave-hill-principal-now-prof-most-hon-v-eudine-barriteau |accessdate=29 December 2019 |work=Loop New Barbados |publisher=Trend Media |date=30 Nov 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Faculty of Culture, Creative and Performing Arts coming to The UWI, Cave Hill Campus |url=https://www.open.uwi.edu/new-faculty-culture-creative-and-performing-arts-coming-uwi-cave-hill-campus |website=UWI Open Campus News |publisher=The University of the West Indies |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty of Medical Sciences ===\nPrior to the establishment of a medical school in the Caribbean, most doctors were trained in the United Kingdom, with a smaller group trained in the United States of America. This was costly, not attuned to the specific needs of the communities the doctors would serve, and risked the trained doctors remaining in their countries of training.\n\nThe Faculty of Medical Sciences <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://medicine.yale.edu/education/gho/yalestudents/abroad/americari/jamaica.aspx |title = Jamaica}}</ref> was the first faculty to be established in the then University College.<ref name=\"Branday\">{{cite journal |last1=Branday |first1=JM |last2=Carpenter |first2=RA |title=The Evolution of Undergraduate Medical Training at The University of the West Indies, 1948-2008 |journal=West Indian Medical Journal |date=2008 |volume=57 |issue=6 |url=https://www.mona.uwi.edu/fms/wimj/system/files/article_pdfs/branday_the_evolution_of_undergraduate_medical_training_at_the_university_of_the_west_indies_etc.pdf |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> This is because of the pressing need for more (locally trained) doctors to treat conditions such as [[tuberculosis]], [[yaws]], [[tetanus]], [[typhoid]], infant [[malnutrition]] and illnesses related to [[diarrhea]]. The establishment of medical schools in the colonies was replicated in the Gold Coast, Nigeria, Rhodesia and Uganda.<ref name=Branday /> The inaugural entering class in 1948 consisted of 33 students from across the Caribbean, selected from more than 600<ref name=\"Fraser\">{{cite journal |last1=Fraser |first1=HS |title=The Faculties and School of Medical Sciences of The University of the West Indies at its Diamond Jubilee |journal=West Indian Medical Journal |date=2008 |volume=57 |issue=6 |url=https://www.mona.uwi.edu/fms/wimj/system/files/article_pdfs/fraser_the_faculties_and_school_of_medical_sciences_of_the_university_of_the_west_etc.pdf |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> or almost 800<ref name=Branday /> applicants. As the university college was then affiliated with the University of London, the curriculum reflected its curriculum, with the addition of preventative and tropical medicine. Degrees were awarded under the University of London name until 1962, reflective of the role the University played in administering the programme and providing the teaching staff.<ref name=Branday /> In addition to the standard five-year course, a pre-course science year was required for students without adequate preparation in that area. The University Hospital of the West Indies, an acute tertiary hospital, provided the initial context for clinical education.\n\nExpansion of the capacity of the Faculty followed several steps. In addition to population growth, the exodus of medical graduates to North America, never to return, exacerbated the need to increase the output of doctors.<ref name=Fraser /> In the 1960s, it was possible to complete the clinical clerkship element of training in Trinidad and Tobago (at the [[Port of Spain General Hospital]]) and in Barbados (at the [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Bridgetown|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]]), as well as in Jamaica.<ref name=Branday /> In 1989, the medical school at the St. Augustine campus opened. However, rather than adopt the 'traditional' existing curriculum at the Mona school, it adopted a problem-based approach.<ref name=Fraser /> Mona, which had already carried out some curricular reform due to World Health Organization recommendations to place greater emphasis on community health promotion and protection, and St. Augustine, had different medical school curricula, though the graduates took the same qualifying exams. Moreover, St. Augustine's Faculty of Medical Sciences included not just a School of Medicine, but also Schools of Dentistry, Veterinarian Medicine, Nursing and Pharmacy, which necessitated some sharing of resources.<ref name=Branday /><ref name=Fraser /> In 2008, the clerkships in Barbados were fully developed into a medical school at the Cave Hill campus. Around the same time, the UWI School of Clinical Medicine and Research was established from an existing programme allowing clerkships to be undertaken in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], under the direction of the St. Augustine campus.<ref name=Fraser />  The School offers the final two years of the five-year programme.\n\n==== Specialist Medical Training ====\nSimilar to the general training, specialist training was progressively made available through the UWI. For example, anaesthesia was initially provided by untrained doctors, nurses, and pharmacists, leading to high morbidity and mortality rates. Initially, doctors were sent overseas for a year of post-graduate training. While the Faculty was established in 1948, the one-year post-graduate diploma in anaesthetics did not begin until 1966 at the Mona Campus. St. Augustine and Cave Hill added the diploma in 1976. However, Mona was already moving towards a four-year Doctor of Medicine Anaesthetics degree, first offered in 1974. Eventually, this more specialised degree (extended to include ''intensive care'') was extended to the other two campuses in 1984 while the one-year programme was discontinued in 1994.<ref name=\"Anaesthetics\">{{cite journal |last1=Scarlett |first1=MD |last2=Crawford-Sykes |first2=A |last3=Harding |first3=HE |last4=Chen |first4=DR |title=The Development of Postgraduate Anaesthesia and Intensive Care Training at the University of the West Indies |journal=West Indian Medical Journal |date=July 2012 |volume=61 |issue=4 |pages=463\u2013466 |doi=10.7727/wimj.2012.147}}</ref>\n\nWhile improvements were being made to the training of physicians as anaesthesiologists, there continued to be a shortage of trained personnel in rural areas. In Jamaica, an initiative to train nurse anaesthetists started, with nurses first sent to the US and to Cuba, followed by the establishment of the Jamaica School of Nurse Anaesthetists in 1981, which continues to this day (2019) with the Ministry of Health. This is in addition to specialised additional training for nurses in intensive care which began in 1969.<ref name=Anaesthetics />\n\n==== Dentist Training ====\nTwo of the three faculties of medical sciences offer dentistry. The St. Augustine campus was the first to offer a dental school. It opened in 1989, the first dental school in the anglophone Caribbean. The inaugural class of roughly 20 students was mostly from Trinidad and Tobago, with a couple of students each from Jamaica and [[St. Vincent and the Grenadines]]. The initial curriculum was modeled on that found in the UK, with the intention to seek recognition from British authorities. It is possible to the exam for membership of the Faculty of Dental Surgery of the Edinburgh-based Royal College of Surgeons.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Naidu |first1=Rahul |last2=Ramroop |first2=Visha |last3=Rafeek |first3=Reisha |title=An Historical Overview of Dentistry in Trinidad and Tobago |journal=History in Action |date=2010 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=1-10 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/265424273_An_Historical_Overview_of_Dentistry_in_Trinidad_and_Tobago |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Accreditation ====\nStarting in 2004, the medical programmes in the Caribbean ceased to be accredited by the United Kingdom-based [[General Medical Council]], as the UK re-focussed more on integration with Europe.<ref name=Branday /> UWI was a key player in the establishment of the [[Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and other Health Professions]] (CAAM-HP). The three UWI medical schools are accredited together, despite differences in curriculum, and are currently accredited with conditions.<ref name=\"CAAM\">{{cite web |title=Programs |url=https://www.caam-hp.org/programs |website=Caribbean Accreditation Authority or Education in Medicine and Other Health Professions (CAAM-HP) |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref> The dental school at St. Augustine is probationary accredited while the dental school at Mona has accreditation with conditions.<ref name=CAAM /> The veterinarian medical school at St. Augustine is also accredited with conditions.<ref name=CAAM /> Efforts are underway to align the curriculum and admission standards of the three medical schools.<ref name=Fraser />\n\n==== Regional Competition ====\nEven with expansion, the UWI medical schools are facing new competition. Many for-profit medical schools have been established in the Caribbean region, with the first established in [[Grenada]] in 1976.<ref name=Branday /> Generally, these schools cater to students from the United States but they sometimes offer scholarships to local students, providing an alternative to UWI programmes or going abroad for medical education [[Canada]], the [[United Kingdom]] or the [[United States]]. The quality of these offshore medical schools differ,<ref name=Branday /> though some are accredited by the CAAM-HP.<ref name=CAAM />\n\n==== Research ====\nThe Faculty of Medicines has a research arm called the Caribbean Institute for Health Research (CAIHR), formerly the Tropical Medicine Research Institute (TMRI). The CAIHR comprises the George Alleyne Chronic Disease Research Centre, based on the Cave Hill Campus, and three units all based on the Mona Campus: the Tropical Metabolism Research Unit, the Sickle Cell Unit and the Epidemiology Research Unit.<ref name=Fraser /> Continuing medical education is provided in different ways among the various countries with the medical associations taking the lead in some countries and the medical schools in others.<ref name=Fraser />\n\n=== Faculty of Law ===\nPrior to the establishment of the Faculty of Law at the UWI, residents of the anglophone Caribbean would travel primarily to the [[United Kingdom]] to study.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /> There, they would join an [[Inns of Court]] where they received lodging and training and underwent examinations. Naturally, the training focused on the legal system and social context of England, which was not the best foundation upon which to practice in the Caribbean.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /> It was also an expensive endeavor. For the legal profession in England, the influx of prospective lawyers from around the [[Commonwealth of Nations|British Commonwealth]] was beginning to strain resources. Efforts were underway to limit foreign students in legal studies in England and this was another reason to establish legal training in the Caribbean.\n\nThe Faculty of Law was initially established in 1970 at the Cave Hill Campus, in [[Barbados]],<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite web |last1=Barnett |first1=Lloyd |title=Report of the Review Committee on Legal Education in the Caribbean 1996 |url=http://www.clecaribbean.com/barnett.php |website=The Barnett Report |publisher=Council of Legal Education |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> but the first year of the degree was available at each campus (and the [[University of Guyana]] in [[Guyana]]).<ref name=\"Lazarus-Black_Law\">{{cite journal |last1=Lazarus-Black |first1=Mindie |title=After Empire: Training Lawyers as a Postcolonial Enterprise |journal=Small Axe |date=February 2008 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=38\u201356 |doi=10.1215/-12-1-38}}</ref>  This structure served, ''inter alia'', to create a regional institution (the Faculty) and a regional identity within the profession. Incrementally, courses from the second and third year of the law programmes were introduced at St. Augustine and Mona, allowing students to take more and more of the degree on those campuses, rather than having to study at Cave Hill. It is now possible to complete the law degree at each campus.<ref name=Barnett />\n\nFollowing completion of the UWI law degree, graduates who intend to practice must complete a two-year practical professional training programme at one of three law schools in the Caribbean. The [[Eugene Dupuch Law School]] in [[The Bahamas]] is normally for citizens of the Bahamas, the [[British Virgin Islands]] and the [[Turks and Caicos Islands]]. The [[Norman Manley Law School]] in [[Jamaica]] has allocated citizens from [[Anguilla]], [[Antigua and Barbuda]], [[Belize]], Jamaica, [[Montserrat]], and [[St. Kitts and Nevis]]. The [[Hugh Wooding Law School]] in [[Trinidad and Tobago]] serves Barbados, [[Dominica]], [[Grenada]], Guyana, [[St. Lucia]], [[St. Vincent and the Grenadines]], and Trinidad and Tobago.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /><ref name=Barnett /> The three schools were established by the Caribbean Council of Legal Education. Ironically, despite the Faculty of Law having been founded in Barbados, the country does not have a law school, though one has been mooted.<ref>{{cite web |title=Call for Barbados law school |url=http://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/175012/barbados-law-school |website=NationNews |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first law students, beginning studies in October 1970, consisted of 24 students in Jamaica, nineteen in Trinidad and Tobago, 35 in Barbados, and thirteen Guyana.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law /> Two years later, almost 300 students were enrolled in the Faculty. The first graduates entered the profession in 1975.\n\nAccess to the Faculty of Law and to the Law Schools are controlled by the institutions. However, costs can vary depending on whether the applicant's country has paid contributory grants to the Faculty or the School. Not all countries did. Therefore, applicants from non-contributing countries would be considered after those from contributing countries and their fees would be higher.<ref name=Lazarus-Black_Law />\n\n=== Faculty of Sport ===\nLaunched in 2017, the UWI Faculty of Sport integrates teaching and research, professional development, community partnerships, and co- and extra-curricular student sport through three main units: Professional Programmes, Outreach & Projects Unit, Co-curricular & Intramural-Activity Unit and the Academic Programme & Activity Unit. The faculty is made up of four Academies of Sport: Cave Hill Academy of Sport, Open Campus Academy of Sport, Mona Academy of Sport and St Augustine Academy of Sport.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parchment |first1=Rachid |title=UWI Launches Faculty of Sports |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/sports/20170727/uwi-launches-faculty-sports |accessdate=2 January 2020 |work=The Gleaner |publisher=RJRGLEANER Communications Group |date=27 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UWI launches Faculty of Sport |url=https://caricom.org/communications/view/uwi-launches-faculty-of-sport |website=CariCom |publisher=Caribbean Community |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== UWI Press ==\nFounded in 1992, the University of the West Indies Press is a department within The University of the West Indies system located in Jamaica.<ref>[http://www.uwipress.com/ University of the West Indies Press], Official website</ref>  Supported by a regionally assembled board or directors, UWI Press acts as the overall publishing arm of the main UWI campuses, and its faculty and student body of the Open Campus where it additionally serves the diverse network of 17 countries and territories.  As an entity that caters to a readership around the world, UWI Press maintains a main commitment to traditional fields of: Caribbean history, social sciences, political science and cultural studies.\n\n== Rankings ==\nAccording to the 2019 Times Higher Education World University Rankings, UWI ranked in the 501-600 band, the first time it has ranked among the 1,258 universities on the list.<ref>{{cite web |title=World University Rankings 2019 |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/world-ranking#!/page/23/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats |website=Times Higher Education |accessdate=13 April 2019|date=2018-09-26 }}</ref> It is the only university from the Caribbean to make the list. Its ranking places it in the top 5% of universities globally and it is the best in the Caribbean.[https://www.uwi.edu/ranking/] The 2019 Times Higher Education ranks UWI Mona 32nd on its Latin America University rankings.<ref>{{cite news |title=New rankings put UWI among top 5 percent of best universities globally. |url=http://www.loopjamaica.com/content/new-rankings-put-uwi-among-top-5-percent-best-universities-globally |accessdate=13 April 2019 |publisher=Loop News |date=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Chancellors of the University ==\n* [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]], 1948\u201371 <ref name = QC>{{cite book|title=The University of the West Indies: A Quinquagenary Calendar, 1948-1998|page=App A}}</ref>\n*Sir [[Hugh Wooding]], 1971\u201374 <ref name=\"QC\" />\n* Sir [[Allen Montgomery Lewis]] 1974\u201389 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[Shridath Ramphal]] 1989\u20132003 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[George Alleyne]] 2003\u20132017 <ref name = QC/>\n* Robert Bermudez 2017\u2013 current\n\n== Vice-Chancellors of the University ==\n'''Principals'''\n\n* Sir [[Thomas Taylor (chemist)|Thomas Taylor]] 1947\u201352 <ref name = QC/> \n* [[Walter Wyatt Grave]] 1953\u201358  <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[William Arthur Lewis]] 1958\u201360  <ref name = QC/>\n\n'''Vice-Chancellors'''\n\n* Sir [[William Arthur Lewis]] 1960\u201363 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir Philip Sherlock 1963\u201369 <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir [[Roy Marshall (academic)|O Roy Marshall]] 1969\u201374 <ref name = QC/>\n* Hon Dr Aston Zachariah Preston 1974\u201386 <ref name = QC/>\n* ''Pro-vice-chancellor L R B Robinson acting 1986\u201388'' <ref name = QC/>\n* Sir Alister McIntyre 1988\u20131998 <ref name = QC/>\n* [[Rex Nettleford]] 1998\u20132004\n* Eon Nigel Harris 2004\u20132015\n* [[Hilary Beckles]] 2015\u2013\n\n== Notable faculty and administrators ==\n*[[Helen Asemota]]: professor of biochemistry and biotechnology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mona.uwi.edu/marcom/newsroom/entry/2828|title=HELEN ASEMOTA PROMOTED TO PROFESSOR {{!}} Marketing and Communications Office, The University of West Indies at Mona|website=www.mona.uwi.edu|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n*[[Elsa Goveia]]: first female professor of UCWI and noted pioneer in West Indian [[historiography]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Higman|first=B. W.|title=General History of the Caribbean|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E12cpltazYgC&pg=PA337|volume=VI: Methodology and historiography of the Caribbean|year=1999|publisher=UNESCO|location=London, England|isbn=978-92-3-103360-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Dr. Elsa Goveia is dead|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/jm/kingston/kingston/kingston-gleaner/clippings/Obituary-Death-Notice/166180/|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=[[Gleaner Company|The Daily Gleaner]]|date=20 March 1980|location=Kingston, Jamaica|via = [[Newspaperarchive.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>\n* [[Patrick Hosein]]: Professor in Computer Science at UWI St Augustine Campus.<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/phosein/ \"Patrick Hosein\"], LinkedIn.</ref>\n* [[Bridget Jones (academic)|Bridget Jones]] (1935-2000): pioneering Literature and language professor from 1964\u20131982, who developed curricula to include Afro-, Anglo- and Franco-Caribbean writers in university syllabai at UWI and in Britain and Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aub-Buscher |first1=Gertrud |title=Bridget Jones |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/apr/17/guardianobituaries |accessdate=6 July 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 April 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509042146/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/apr/17/guardianobituaries |archivedate=9 May 2014 |location=London, England}}</ref>\n* [[Sheila Dorothy King|Dorothy King]]: head of the Microbiology Department of the medical faculty from 1973\u20132001.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Professor of Microbiology: Dr. Sheila King Makes History|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/susun-wilkinson-celebrity-clipping-jul-04-1983-428353/|accessdate=1 February 2018|newspaper=[[The Gleaner (newspaper)|The Gleaner]]|date=4 July 1983|location=Kingstown, Jamaica|page=21|via = [[Newspaperarchive.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>\n* [[Elsa Leo-Rhynie]]: Principal of the Mona campus.\n* [[William Arthur Lewis]]: economist, lecturer, author and joint winner of [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics]] of 1979.\n* [[Albert Belville Lockhart]]:  Consultant and Ophthalmologist, Recipient of the [[Jamaican Order of Merit]], co-inventor of [[Canasol]].<ref name=\"J Homi 1996\">M. E. West and J. Homi. \"Cannabis as a medicine\". ''Br. J. Anaesth'' (1996) 76(1): 167 {{doi|10.1093/bja/76.1.167-a}}</ref>\n* [[Kim Mallalieu]]: Senior Lecturer in Computer and Electrical Engineering at UWI St Augustine.<ref>[https://sta.uwi.edu/eng/electrical/staff/kim_mallalieu.asp \"Dr. Kim Mallalieu\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406110355/https://sta.uwi.edu/eng/electrical/staff/kim_mallalieu.asp |date=2017-04-06 }}, The Faculty of Engineering, UWI St Augustine.</ref><ref>[http://sta.uwi.edu/news/releases/release.asp?id=562 \"UWI Students win MIT Technology Innovation Award\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032703/http://sta.uwi.edu/news/releases/release.asp?id=562 |date=2017-12-01 }}, UWI St Augustine, 21 May 2010.</ref>\n* [[Evelyn O'Callaghan]]: Professor of West Indian literature, Dean of the Faculty of Humanities and Education.\n* [[Donna-Maria Maynard]]: Professor of Psychology, Faculty of Humanities & Education, Cave Hill Campus.\n* [[Orlando Patterson]]: John Cowles Professor of Sociology at Harvard University.<ref>[http://scholar.harvard.edu/patterson/home \"Orlando Patterson\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828212009/http://scholar.harvard.edu/patterson/home |date=2016-08-28 }}, Harvard Department of Sociology.</ref>\n*[[Manley West|Manley Elisha West]]: Professor of Pharmacology, recipient of the [[Jamaican Order of Merit]], co-inventor of [[Canasol]].<ref name=\"J Homi 1996\"/>\n*[[Courtenay Felix Bartholomew]]: the first lecturer and then Professor of Medicine at UWI St Augustine.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://icons.niherst.gov.tt/icon/courtenay-bartholomew-ci1/|title=Courtenay Bartholomew|date=2017-06-23|work=Icons|access-date=2018-11-09|publisher=The National Institute of Higher Education, Research, Science and Technology (NIHERST), [[Government of Trinidad and Tobago]]|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n[[File:WalcottenDeKom.jpg|thumb|Sir Derek Walcott studied at the University of the West Indies]]\n\nUWI graduates who are, or have been, heads of government:\n* [[Kenny Anthony]], former prime minister of St. Lucia\n* [[Owen Arthur]], former prime minister of Barbados\n* [[Dean Barrow]], prime minister of Belize\n* [[Denzil Douglas]], former prime minister of St. Kitts & Nevis\n* [[Rufus Ewing]], premier of the Turks and Caicos Islands\n* [[Bruce Golding]], former prime minister of Jamaica\n* [[Ralph Gonsalves]], prime minister of St. Vincent and the Grenadines\n* [[David A. Granger]], president of Guyana\n* [[Andrew Holness]], prime minister of Jamaica[[File:Andrew Holness cropped.jpg|thumb|Andrew Holness]]\n* [[Patrick Manning]], former prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago\n* [[Hubert Minnis]], prime minister of The Bahamas\n* [[Keith Mitchell]], prime minister of Grenada\n* [[Joseph Walcott Parry]], former premier of Nevis\n* [[P. J. Patterson]], former prime minister of Jamaica\n* [[Kamla Persad-Bissessar]], first female prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago\n* [[Keith Rowley]]: prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago[[File:KeithRowley.jpg|thumb|244x244px|[[Keith Rowley]]: prime minister of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n* [[Lloyd Erskine Sandiford]], former prime minister of Barbados\n* [[Kennedy A. Simmonds]], former prime minister of St. Kitts & Nevis\n* [[Orlando Smith]], chief minister of the British Virgin Islands\n* [[Freundel Stuart]], former prime minister of Barbados\n* [[David Thompson (Barbadian politician)|David Thompson]], former prime minister of Barbados\n\nGraduates in other fields:\n* [[Sharon Aarons]], Australian soil scientist\n* [[Anita Allen (judge)|Dame Anita Allen]], president of the Court of Appeal of The Bahamas\n* [[Faris Al-Rawi]], Attorney General of Trinidad and Tobago\n* [[Pamela Coke-Hamilton]] Director of International Trade for [[UNCTAD]] \n* [[Merceline Dahl-Regis]], Bahamian physician, former Chief Medical Officer of the Bahamas\n* [[Edwidge Danticat]], Haitian poet and writer\n* [[Fae Ellington]], Jamaican media personality and lecturer\n* [[Burton P. C. Hall]], judge of the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia]] and former Chief Justice of The Bahamas\n* [[Marlon James (novelist)|Marlon James]], Jamaican-born winner of the 2015 Man Booker Prize for Fiction\n* [[Kwame Dawes]]\n*[[Joan Latchman]], Director of the [[University of the West Indies]] Seismic Research Centre\n* [[Dolliver Nelson]], member of the [[International Tribunal for the Law of the Sea]]\n* [[Kris Rampersad]], journalist, author, cultural advocate\n* [[Patrick Lipton Robinson]], judge of the [[International Court of Justice]]\n* [[Walter Rodney]], Guyanese historian and political activist\n* [[Richard Sealy]], Barbadian Tourism Minister\n* [[Olive Senior]], Jamaican novelist and writer\n* [[Sheik Mohamed Khan]], Climate Change Expert, Ministry of Agriculture, Government of Guyana\n* [[Shafimana Ueitele]], Namibian lawyer \n* [[Derek Walcott]], Nobel Prize for Literature (1992)\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Jamaica|Trinidad|Caribbean}}\n* [[Agence universitaire de la Francophonie]]\n* [[Association of Commonwealth Universities]]\n* [[University of the West Indies Museum]]\n* [[University of Guyana]]\n* [[University of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n* [[University of Technology, Jamaica]]\n* [[University of the Bahamas]]\n* [[University of the French West Indies]]\n* [[University of French Guiana]]\n* [[Savacou (sculpture)|Savacou]], a sculpture on the Mona site\n* [[University of the South Pacific]], a similar university for Pacific Island states\n* [[Historically black colleges and universities]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official|http://www.uwi.edu/ }}\n\n=== Main Campus websites ===\n* [http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu/ Cave Hill Campus, Barbados]\n* [http://www.mona.uwi.edu/ Mona Campus, Jamaica]\n* [http://www.open.uwi.edu/index.php/ Open Campus]\n* [http://www.sta.uwi.edu/ St. Augustine Campus, Trinidad & Tobago]\n* [http://fiveislands.uwi.edu/ Five Islands Campus, Antigua & Barbuda] \n\n==