{"title_page": "University of the Visual and Performing Arts", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = University of the Visual & Performing Arts \n|native_name     = \u0dc3\u0dde\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dba\u0dba \u0d9a\u0dbd\u0dcf \u0dc0\u0dd2\u0dc1\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dba <br> \u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb2, \u0b85\u0bb0\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc7\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bae\u0bcd\n| former_name           =  Institute of Aesthetic Studies of the [[University of Ceylon]] <br> College of Fine Arts<br>Heywood Institute of Art (Heywood College)\n| latin_name = \n|image =University_of_the_Visual_and_Performing_Arts.gif\n|image_size =200px\n|motto =  \n|established = 1893- School of Art<br>2 July 1952-Government College of Fine Arts<br>1974 \u2013  Institute of Aesthetic Studies of the [[University of Ceylon]] <br>1 July 2005-(Gained University Status) University of the Visual and Performing Arts\n|type = Public\n|endowment =\n|staff =  \n|faculty =\n|president = \n|provost =\n|principal = \n|rector = \n|chancellor = Prof. [[Sanath Nandasiri]]\n|vice_chancellor = Mr. B. Asoka Keerthi De Sliva (Competent Authority)\n|dean = \n|head_label = \n|head = \n|students = 9,000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ugc.ac.lk/downloads/statistics/stat_2015/Chapter%203.pdf|title= Student Enrolmentof Sri Lankan Universities |publisher= University Grants Commission of Sri Lanka|format=PDF |access-date=23 August 2016}}</ref> \n|undergrad =8,500\n|postgrad = 70\n|doctoral =50\n|city = [[Colombo]]\n|country = [[Sri Lanka]]\n|campus =[[Urban area|Urban]]\n|language       = [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[English language|English]]\n|free_label =\n|nickname = Heywood\n|free = \n|colors = \n|colours = [[Maroon]], [[Orange (colour)|Orange]] {{color box|Orange}}{{color box|Maroon}}\n|mascot = \n|academic_affiliation   = [[University Grants Commission (Sri Lanka)|University Grants Commission of Sri Lanka]],<br>[[Association of Commonwealth Universities]]\n|sporting_affiliations  = [[Sri Lanka University Games]]\n|website = https://www.vpa.ac.lk/\n|logo = \n}}\n'''University  of the Visual and Performing Arts''' (UVPA) ({{lang-si|\u0dc3\u0dde\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dba \u0dc4\u0dcf \u0d9a\u0dbd\u0dcf \u0dc0\u0dd2\u0dc1\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0daf\u0dca\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dba}},{{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb2, \u0b85\u0bb0\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc7\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd  \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bae\u0bcd}}) is a [[public university]] located primarily in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]],  specialising in [[art]], [[design]], fashion and the [[performing arts]].  It was formerly known as the Government College of Fine Arts, Heywood Institute of Art and the Institute of Aesthetic Studies of the [[University of Ceylon]]. It has no known date of foundation, but there is evidence of teaching as far back as 1893. It is the only university in Sri Lanka to exclusively offer special degree programs in visual and performing arts.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Heywood Realists hold exhibition |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/170115/plus/heywood-realists-hold-exhibition-224520.html|work=sundaytimes |agency=|date=2015-01-15 |access-date=2013-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=RANABAHU|first=Prasanna |editor-last=|editor-first= |title=Tradition of Heywood |publisher=Theertha International Artists Collective (Pittakotte, Sri Lanka) |date=2006 |pages= |chapter= |isbn=9551490126}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Colonial===      \nThe origin of the University of the Visual and Performing Arts can be traced back to 1893, the era in which the [[Ceylon Technical College]] was established. Drawing and Design were among the first courses to be taught there. Approximately five decades later, on 1 October 1949, the Department of Arts and Aesthetics shifted its locality from Horton Place to Heywood College.<ref>Cheran, Rudhramoorthy, ed. Pathways of dissent: Tamil nationalism in Sri Lanka. SAGE Publications India, 2009</ref>\nThe restructuring of the university system in Sri Lanka affiliated the institute to the [[University of Kelaniya]] in 1980. A Special Gazette Notice formally announced the creation of the '''University of the Visual and Performing Arts''' on 1 July 2005. [[Sarath Amunugama]] was assigned as First Vice Chancellor.<ref>https://www.parliament.lk/uploads/documents/paperspresented/annual_report_university_of_the_visual_performing_arts_2009.pdf</ref><ref>http://archives.dailynews.lk/2010/08/05/fea09.asp</ref>\n\nThe University of the Visual and Performing Art has a history spanning over 120 years.  The origin of the University of the Visual and Performing Arts can be traced back to 1893, the era in which the Ceylon Technical College was established. Among the first courses to be taught at the college were Drawing and Painting.  On 1 October 1949, the Department of Drawing and Painting moved from the Technical College at [[Maradana]] to the \u2018Heywood\u2019 building at Horton place and was subsequently renamed as the \u2018School of Art\u2019. A diploma in Fine Arts was awarded to students upon the completion of five years of study. Prominent painter and teacher J.D.A. Perera was the first  Principal of this institution.<ref>http://www.sundaytimes.lk/050626/plus/11.html</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 1952,  Music and Dance were included in to the curriculum  and the institute became named as the \u2018Government College of Fine Arts\u2019. On 1 October 1953,  the Departments of Music and Dance were moved to  21, Albert Crescent in Colombo 7, while the Art and Sculpture courses continued to be conducted at the \u2018Heywood\u2019 Building. Three years after this, in 1956, this institution was once again renamed as the \u2018National Institute of Arts\u2019and it was taken under the purview of Ministry of Education and converted into three schools, namely, School of Art and sculpture, School of Music and School of Dancing and Ballet. All  schools came under the administration of Dr. Stanley Abeysinghe, Dr. [[Lionel Edirisinghe]] and Dr. S. Panibharatha respectively.\n\nAs a result of the first university Act of 1972, the institution became known as  the Institute of Aesthetic studies and got affiliated to the [[University of Ceylon]] in 1974. The Institute had 03 Schools and an Academy, namely : School of Art and Sculpture, School of Music and School of Dancing and Ballet, and the Ramanathan  Academy of Jaffna. In 1975, the Ramanathan Academy became affiliated with the [[University of Jaffna]].\n\nFor the first time, in 1978, 63 students were awarded the\u2019 Bachelor of Arts\u2019 degree.  Consequently, the restructuring of the University System in Sri Lanka brought about the affiliation of this Institute to the [http://www.kln.ac.lk University of Kelaniya] in 1980.\n\n===University status ===\nThe special Gazette notice issued by her Excellency the [[President of Sri Lanka]] formally announced the establishment  of the University of Visual and Performing Arts with effect from 1 July 2005. This University was founded in order to promote and develop the [[Visual]] and [[Creative Arts]] as well as to offer recognized higher educational qualifications in these spheres of study. The President appointed Dr. [[Lester James Peiris]] and Professor Sarath Amunugama as the first Chancellor and Vice Chancellor respectively. The University consists of three faculties, Dance and Drama, Music and Visual Arts and Jayasena Kottagoda, Sanath Nandasiri and Sarath Gunasiri Perera were elected as the first Deans of the faculties respectively.\n\n===21st century===\nThere are 22 departments functioning under these three faculties. The present Chancellor of the university is Pandith [[W. D. Amaradeva]] and the Vice Chancellor is Jayasena Kottagoda, the first Vice Chancellor who is a former student of this institution. They were elected in to office in 2008. Currently, in his second term as Vice Chancellor to the UVPA, Kottagoda was also the first Professor, Senior Professor of this university apart from holding the post of the initial Dean of the Faculty of Dance and Drama.\n\n==Governance and administration==\n\nThe University of the Visual and Performing Arts is a [[public university|state university]] and depends on the government for much of its annual grant, which is provided by the [[University Grants Commission (Sri Lanka)|University Grants Commission]] (UGC). Due to this, its administration is heavily influenced by the UGC. Undergraduate education is completely free. The Governance of the university is under the provisions of the Universities Act No. 16 of 1978 and the Universities (Amendment) Act No. 7 of 1985 along with its own by-laws.\n\nThe university's administration is based upon that of the former [[University of Ceylon]] consisting of a dual structure of bodies: the Council (formally known as the [[University Court]] which is the governing body) and the [[Academic Senate]] (academic affairs).\n\nMuch of the appointments to officers and faculty are carried out by these bodies, however on the recommendations of the UGC.\n\n===Officers of the university===\n;Chancellor\nThe [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] is the head of the university and awards all [[academic degree|degrees]], although most duties are carried out by the Vice-Chancellor. The appointment is made by the [[President of Sri Lanka]], to a distinguished person in academics, clergy or in the civil society. The chancellor is Prof. Sanath Nandasiri.\n\n;Vice-Chancellor\nDay-to-day management of the University is undertaken by the [[Chancellor (education)#Vice Chancellor|Vice-Chancellor]], appointed by the [[President of Sri Lanka]]. The current Vice-Chancellor is Prof. Sarath Chandrajeewa.\n\n===Past Chancellors and Vice-Chancellors===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Chancellors\n# Dr. [[Lester James Peiris]]\n# Pandith [[W. D. Amaradeva]]\n\n{{col-2}}\n;Vice-Chancellors\n# Prof.[[Sarath Amunugama]]\n# Prof. Jayasena Kottagoda\n# Prof. Ariyaratne Kaluarachchi\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nFile:Nanda_Malini.jpg |[[Nanda Malini]] <br> Sri Lankan singer<ref>http://www.newslanka.net/gee_amanandani_artists.html</ref>\nFile:David_Paynter.jpg|[[David Paynter (artist)]]\nFile:Artist_Nawi_Samaraweera.png|[[Nawi Samaraweera]]\nFile:Wijeyeratne_V.B_(Mrs).jpg|[[Visakha Wijeyeratne]]\n</gallery>\n*[[Gunadasa Kapuge]]\n*[[Titus Thotawatte]]\n*[[Priya Suriyasena]]\n*[[Tissa Ranasinghe]]\n*[[Malani Bulathsinhala]]<ref>http://www.infolanka.com/ubb/Forum1/HTML/003256.html</ref>\n*[[Mahagama Sekara]]\n*[[Rohana Weerasinghe]]\n\n===Faculty===\nUniversity of the Visual and Performing Arts's faculty includes scholars such as  renowned Sri Lankan musicologist [[W. D. Amaradeva]], [[Mahagama Sekara]] and [[Lionel Edirisinghe]] ,\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nPandit Dr.W. D. Amaradeva.jpg|[[W. D. Amaradeva]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Education in Sri Lanka]]\n*[[List of universities in Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan Universities]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vpa.ac.lk/ Official Website]\n\n{{coord missing|Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{Universities in Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Visual and Performing Arts, University of the}}\n[[Category:Universities in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Colombo]]\n[[Category:Art schools in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2005]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name = University of the Visual & Performing Arts \n|native_name     = \u0dc3\u0dde\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dba\u0dba \u0d9a\u0dbd\u0dcf \u0dc0\u0dd2\u0dc1\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dba <br> \u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb2, \u0b85\u0bb0\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc7\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bae\u0bcd\n| former_name           =  Institute of Aesthetic Studies of the [[University of Ceylon]] <br> College of Fine Arts<br>Heywood Institute of Art (Heywood College)\n| latin_name = \n|image =University_of_the_Visual_and_Performing_Arts.gif\n|image_size =200px\n|motto =  \n|established = 1893- School of Art<br>2 July 1952-Government College of Fine Arts<br>1974 \u2013  Institute of Aesthetic Studies of the [[University of Ceylon]] <br>1 July 2005-(Gained University Status) University of the Visual and Performing Arts\n|type = Public\n|endowment =\n|staff =  \n|faculty =\n|president = \n|provost =\n|principal = \n|rector = \n|chancellor = Prof. [[Sanath Nandasiri]]\n|vice_chancellor = Mr. B. Asoka Keerthi De Sliva (Competent Authority)\n|dean = \n|head_label = \n|head = \n|students = 9,000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ugc.ac.lk/downloads/statistics/stat_2015/Chapter%203.pdf|title= Student Enrolmentof Sri Lankan Universities |publisher= University Grants Commission of Sri Lanka|format=PDF |access-date=23 August 2016}}</ref> \n|undergrad =8,500\n|postgrad = 70\n|doctoral =50\n|city = [[Colombo]]\n|country = [[Sri Lanka]]\n|campus =[[Urban area|Urban]]\n|language       = [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[English language|English]]\n|free_label =\n|nickname = Heywood\n|free = \n|colors = \n|colours = [[Maroon]], [[Orange (colour)|Orange]] {{color box|Orange}}{{color box|Maroon}}\n|mascot = \n|academic_affiliation   = [[University Grants Commission (Sri Lanka)|University Grants Commission of Sri Lanka]],<br>[[Association of Commonwealth Universities]]\n|sporting_affiliations  = [[Sri Lanka University Games]]\n|website = https://www.vpa.ac.lk/\n|logo = \n}}\n'''University  of the Visual and Performing Arts''' (UVPA) ({{lang-si|\u0dc3\u0dde\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dba \u0dc4\u0dcf \u0d9a\u0dbd\u0dcf \u0dc0\u0dd2\u0dc1\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0daf\u0dca\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dba}},{{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb2, \u0b85\u0bb0\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc7\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd  \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bae\u0bcd}}) is a [[public university]] located primarily in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]],  specialising in [[art]], [[design]], fashion and the [[performing arts]].  It was formerly known as the Government College of Fine Arts, Heywood Institute of Art and the Institute of Aesthetic Studies of the [[University of Ceylon]]. It has no known date of foundation, but there is evidence of teaching as far back as 1893. It is the only university in Sri Lanka to exclusively offer special degree programs in visual and performing arts.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Heywood Realists hold exhibition |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/170115/plus/heywood-realists-hold-exhibition-224520.html|work=sundaytimes |agency=|date=2015-01-15 |access-date=2013-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=RANABAHU|first=Prasanna |editor-last=|editor-first= |title=Tradition of Heywood |publisher=Theertha International Artists Collective (Pittakotte, Sri Lanka) |date=2006 |pages= |chapter= |isbn=9551490126}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Colonial===      \nThe origin of the University of the Visual and Performing Arts can be traced back to 1893, the era in which the [[Ceylon Technical College]] was established. Drawing and Design were among the first courses to be taught there. Approximately five decades later, on 1 October 1949, the Department of Arts and Aesthetics shifted its locality from Horton Place to Heywood College.<ref>Cheran, Rudhramoorthy, ed. Pathways of dissent: Tamil nationalism in Sri Lanka. SAGE Publications India, 2009</ref>\nThe restructuring of the university system in Sri Lanka affiliated the institute to the [[University of Kelaniya]] in 1980. A Special Gazette Notice formally announced the creation of the '''University of the Visual and Performing Arts''' on 1 July 2005. [[Sarath Amunugama]] was assigned as First Vice Chancellor.<ref>https://www.parliament.lk/uploads/documents/paperspresented/annual_report_university_of_the_visual_performing_arts_2009.pdf</ref><ref>http://archives.dailynews.lk/2010/08/05/fea09.asp</ref>\n\nThe University of the Visual and Performing Art has a history spanning over 120 years.  The origin of the University of the Visual and Performing Arts can be traced back to 1893, the era in which the Ceylon Technical College was established. Among the first courses to be taught at the college were Drawing and Painting.  On 1 October 1949, the Department of Drawing and Painting moved from the Technical College at [[Maradana]] to the \u2018Heywood\u2019 building at Horton place and was subsequently renamed as the \u2018School of Art\u2019. A diploma in Fine Arts was awarded to students upon the completion of five years of study. Prominent painter and teacher J.D.A. Perera was the first  Principal of this institution.<ref>http://www.sundaytimes.lk/050626/plus/11.html</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 1952,  Music and Dance were included in to the curriculum  and the institute became named as the \u2018Government College of Fine Arts\u2019. On 1 October 1953,  the Departments of Music and Dance were moved to  21, Albert Crescent in Colombo 7, while the Art and Sculpture courses continued to be conducted at the \u2018Heywood\u2019 Building. Three years after this, in 1956, this institution was once again renamed as the \u2018National Institute of Arts\u2019and it was taken under the purview of Ministry of Education and converted into three schools, namely, School of Art and sculpture, School of Music and School of Dancing and Ballet. All  schools came under the administration of Dr. Stanley Abeysinghe, Dr. [[Lionel Edirisinghe]] and Dr. S. Panibharatha respectively.\n\nAs a result of the first university Act of 1972, the institution became known as  the Institute of Aesthetic studies and got affiliated to the [[University of Ceylon]] in 1974. The Institute had 03 Schools and an Academy, namely : School of Art and Sculpture, School of Music and School of Dancing and Ballet, and the Ramanathan  Academy of Jaffna. In 1975, the Ramanathan Academy became affiliated with the [[University of Jaffna]].\n\nFor the first time, in 1978, 63 students were awarded the\u2019 Bachelor of Arts\u2019 degree.  Consequently, the restructuring of the University System in Sri Lanka brought about the affiliation of this Institute to the [http://www.kln.ac.lk University of Kelaniya] in 1980.\n\n===University status ===\nThe special Gazette notice issued by her Excellency the [[President of Sri Lanka]] formally announced the establishment  of the University of Visual and Performing Arts with effect from 1 July 2005. This University was founded in order to promote and develop the [[Visual]] and [[Creative Arts]] as well as to offer recognized higher educational qualifications in these spheres of study. The President appointed Dr. [[Lester James Peiris]] and Professor Sarath Amunugama as the first Chancellor and Vice Chancellor respectively. The University consists of three faculties, Dance and Drama, Music and Visual Arts and Jayasena Kottagoda, Sanath Nandasiri and Sarath Gunasiri Perera were elected as the first Deans of the faculties respectively.\n\n===21st century===\nThere are 22 departments functioning under these three faculties. The present Chancellor of the university is Pandith [[W. D. Amaradeva]] and the Vice Chancellor is Jayasena Kottagoda, the first Vice Chancellor who is a former student of this institution. They were elected in to office in 2008. Currently, in his second term as Vice Chancellor to the UVPA, Kottagoda was also the first Professor, Senior Professor of this university apart from holding the post of the initial Dean of the Faculty of Dance and Drama.\n\n==Governance and administration==\n\nThe University of the Visual and Performing Arts is a [[public university|state university]] and depends on the government for much of its annual grant, which is provided by the [[University Grants Commission (Sri Lanka)|University Grants Commission]] (UGC). Due to this, its administration is heavily influenced by the UGC. Undergraduate education is completely free. The Governance of the university is under the provisions of the Universities Act No. 16 of 1978 and the Universities (Amendment) Act No. 7 of 1985 along with its own by-laws.\n\nThe university's administration is based upon that of the former [[University of Ceylon]] consisting of a dual structure of bodies: the Council (formally known as the [[University Court]] which is the governing body) and the [[Academic Senate]] (academic affairs).\n\nMuch of the appointments to officers and faculty are carried out by these bodies, however on the recommendations of the UGC.\n\n===Officers of the university===\n;Chancellor\nThe [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] is the head of the university and awards all [[academic degree|degrees]], although most duties are carried out by the Vice-Chancellor. The appointment is made by the [[President of Sri Lanka]], to a distinguished person in academics, clergy or in the civil society. The chancellor is Prof. Sanath Nandasiri.\n\n;Vice-Chancellor\nDay-to-day management of the University is undertaken by the [[Chancellor (education)#Vice Chancellor|Vice-Chancellor]], appointed by the [[President of Sri Lanka]]. The current Vice-Chancellor is Prof. Sarath Chandrajeewa.\n\n===Past Chancellors and Vice-Chancellors===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Chancellors\n# Dr. [[Lester James Peiris]]\n# Pandith [[W. D. Amaradeva]]\n\n{{col-2}}\n;Vice-Chancellors\n# Prof.[[Sarath Amunugama]]\n# Prof. Jayasena Kottagoda\n# Prof. Ariyaratne Kaluarachchi\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nFile:Nanda_Malini.jpg |[[Nanda Malini]] <br> Sri Lankan singer<ref>http://www.newslanka.net/gee_amanandani_artists.html</ref>\nFile:David_Paynter.jpg|[[David Paynter (artist)]]\nFile:Artist_Nawi_Samaraweera.png|[[Nawi Samaraweera]]\nFile:Wijeyeratne_V.B_(Mrs).jpg|[[Visakha Wijeyeratne]]\n</gallery>\n*[[Gunadasa Kapuge]]\n*[[Titus Thotawatte]]\n*[[Priya Suriyasena]]\n*[[Tissa Ranasinghe]]\n*[[Malani Bulathsinhala]]<ref>http://www.infolanka.com/ubb/Forum1/HTML/003256.html</ref>\n*[[Mahagama Sekara]]\n*[[Rohana Weerasinghe]]\n===Faculty===\nUniversity of the Visual and Performing Arts's faculty includes scholars such as  renowned Sri Lankan musicologist [[W. D. Amaradeva]], [[Mahagama Sekara]] and [[Lionel Edirisinghe]] ,\n<gallery class=\"center\" classes=\"center\">\nPandit Dr.W. D. Amaradeva.jpg|[[W. D. Amaradeva]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Education in Sri Lanka]]\n*[[List of universities in Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan Universities]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vpa.ac.lk/ Official Website]\n\n{{coord missing|Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{Universities in Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Visual and Performing Arts, University of the}}\n[[Category:Universities in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Colombo]]\n[[Category:Art schools in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2005]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Visual_and_Performing_Arts"}
{"title_page": "University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce\n|native_name = \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e04\u0e49\u0e32\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\n|logo = UTCC Wordmark.svg\n|image = UTCC 2.jpg\n|image_size = \n|motto = Thailand's Business Oriented University\n|established = 1940 as College of Commerce; 1984 full university status\n|type = [[Private university|Private]], non-profit\n|staff =\n|president = Sauwanee Thairungroj\n|students = 20,000 undergraduate and graduate\n|city = [[Bangkok]]\n|country = [[Thailand]]\n|campus = Urban: [[Din Daeng District]]\n|website = http://www.utcc.ac.th\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce''' (UTCC) ([[Thai alphabet|Thai]]: \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e04\u0e49\u0e32\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22) is a private non-profit higher education institution in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]. The university's origin dates back to 1940, with the foundation of the College of Commerce in Bangkok. In 1984, the college was granted full university status under its present name.\n\nThe university is academically organized into eight schools: business, accountancy, economics, humanities, science, communication arts, engineering, and law. All offer degree programs, in English and Thai, to the doctoral level. The university has strong ties to entrepreneurs in Thailand through its founding body, the Thai Chamber of Commerce. It also serves in various advisory functions to several [[Asean|ASEAN countries]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}} The university's [[business school]] is accredited by the US [[Accreditation Council for Business Schools and Programs]].<ref>http://www.utcc.ac.th/news/862/AACSB_International.html</ref>\n\nThe university enforces a strict student dress code.<ref>{{cite web|title=University student uniforms|url=http://www.utcc.ac.th/index.php/en/currentStudents/Dress|website=University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce (UTCC)|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe university has the longest history of private higher education in Thailand. At its founding, the College of Commerce offering a six-month program and a two-year program for 300 students. It reopened in 1963, after its closure in December 1941 following the [[Japanese invasion of Thailand|Japanese invasion]] and [[Japanese occupation of Thailand|occupation of Thailand]]. On 17 June 1970, the college was formally accredited under the Private College Act. The first bachelor's degree programs were offered in 1967, and in 1973 the college moved to its present location in [[Din Daeng District|Bangkok's Din Daeng District]]. On 24 October 1984, it became a full university.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.utcc.ac.th/index.php/en/aboutUs/index|website=University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce (UTCC)|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Enrollment and faculty==\nAs of January 2007, the university had 19,472 undergraduate and 1,710 graduate students enrolled in its various programs.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\nSince its foundation, the university has maintained a close relationship and cooperation with the Thai Chamber of Commerce. In addition to full-time [[faculty (academic staff)|faculty members]] with academic backgrounds, there are many part-time lecturers who are successful executives with practical knowledge and experience. As a leading university in business education in Asia, the university produces graduates with high academic and business ability and [[Business ethics|ethics]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Degree programs and campus facilities==\nThe university provides [[bachelor's degree]]s, [[master's degree]]s,  and [[doctoral]] [[Academic degree|degree programmes]].<ref>http://studyinthailand.org/international_english_university_program/UTCC.html</ref> It offers a low faculty-student ratio and small class sizes.\n\nA number of programs are linked internationally through [[student exchange program]]s with universities in the US, Australia, and Europe. All international classes are taught in English.\n\nThe university's facilities provide a modern teaching environment, with air-conditioned classrooms, a central library, language laboratories, wireless internet on campus, a broadcast TV channel, and sport facilities.\n\n==Research centres==\n[[File:UTCC 1.jpg|thumb|UTCC campus]]\n* Research Institute for Policy Evaluation and Design: Interdisciplinary research with a focus on Southeast Asia<ref>http://riped.utcc.ac.th</ref>\n* The UTCC Logistics Research Center\n* The Center for Economic and Business Forecasting\n* ASEAN Mass Communication Studies and Research Center\n* Family Business Enterprise Center\n* AEC Strategy Center: Business information research and consultancy with focus on the ASEAN Economic Community<ref>{{cite web|url=http://utcc2.utcc.ac.th/aec/about.php?id%3D4 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-06-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000234/http://utcc2.utcc.ac.th/aec/about.php?id=4 |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n* The Innovation Driven Entrepreneurship (IDE) Center, developing Innovation Driven Entrepreneurs in Thailand and Southeast Asia. http://idecenter.utcc.ac.th/\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Phupoom Pongpanu]], actor\n* Nitidon Pomsuwan, actor\n* [[Jesdaporn Pholdee]], actor\n* [[Chutima Naiyana]], Miss Thailand 1987\n* Piyatida Woramusik, actress\n* [[Sot Chitalada]], boxing athletes\n* Rungruang Anantaya, actor\n* [[Itthipat Peeradechapan]], entrepreneur\n* [[Nawat Itsaragrisil]], producer\n* Yui Yardyer, singer\n* Theera Thanyapaiboon, journalist\n* Chanon Ukkharachata, actor, host [[The Face Thailand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.utcc.ac.th/ UTCC website]\n\n{{Universities in Thailand}}\n\n{{coord|13.778638|N|100.560080|E|source:thwiki_region:TH|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1940]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Universities in Thailand]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name = University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce\n|native_name = \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e04\u0e49\u0e32\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\n|logo = UTCC Wordmark.svg\n|image = UTCC 2.jpg\n|image_size = \n|motto = Thailand's Business Oriented University\n|established = 1940 as College of Commerce; 1984 full university status\n|type = [[Private university|Private]], non-profit\n|staff =\n|president = Sauwanee Thairungroj\n|students = 20,000 undergraduate and graduate\n|city = [[Bangkok]]\n|country = [[Thailand]]\n|campus = Urban: [[Din Daeng District]]\n|website = http://www.utcc.ac.th\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce''' (UTCC) ([[Thai alphabet|Thai]]: \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e2b\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e04\u0e49\u0e32\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22) is a private non-profit higher education institution in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]. The university's origin dates back to 1940, with the foundation of the College of Commerce in Bangkok. In 1984, the college was granted full university status under its present name.\n\nThe university is academically organized into eight schools: business, accountancy, economics, humanities, science, communication arts, engineering, and law. All offer degree programs, in English and Thai, to the doctoral level. The university has strong ties to entrepreneurs in Thailand through its founding body, the Thai Chamber of Commerce. It also serves in various advisory functions to several [[Asean|ASEAN countries]].{{CN|date=January 2017}} The university's [[business school]] is accredited by the US [[Accreditation Council for Business Schools and Programs]].<ref>http://www.utcc.ac.th/news/862/AACSB_International.html</ref>\n\nThe university enforces a strict student dress code.<ref>{{cite web|title=University student uniforms|url=http://www.utcc.ac.th/index.php/en/currentStudents/Dress|website=University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce (UTCC)|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe university has the longest history of private higher education in Thailand. At its founding, the College of Commerce offering a six-month program and a two-year program for 300 students. It reopened in 1963, after its closure in December 1941 following the [[Japanese invasion of Thailand|Japanese invasion]] and [[Japanese occupation of Thailand|occupation of Thailand]]. On 17 June 1970, the college was formally accredited under the Private College Act. The first bachelor's degree programs were offered in 1967, and in 1973 the college moved to its present location in [[Din Daeng District|Bangkok's Din Daeng District]]. On 24 October 1984, it became a full university.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.utcc.ac.th/index.php/en/aboutUs/index|website=University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce (UTCC)|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Enrollment and faculty==\nAs of January 2007, the university had 19,472 undergraduate and 1,710 graduate students enrolled in its various programs.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\nSince its foundation, the university has maintained a close relationship and cooperation with the Thai Chamber of Commerce. In addition to full-time [[faculty (academic staff)|faculty members]] with academic backgrounds, there are many part-time lecturers who are successful executives with practical knowledge and experience. As a leading university in business education in Asia, the university produces graduates with high academic and business ability and [[Business ethics|ethics]].{{CN|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Degree programs and campus facilities==\nThe university provides [[bachelor's degree]]s, [[master's degree]]s,  and [[doctoral]] [[Academic degree|degree programmes]].<ref>http://studyinthailand.org/international_english_university_program/UTCC.html</ref> It offers a low faculty-student ratio and small class sizes.\n\nA number of programs are linked internationally through [[student exchange program]]s with universities in the US, Australia, and Europe. All international classes are taught in English.\n\nThe university's facilities provide a modern teaching environment, with air-conditioned classrooms, a central library, language laboratories, wireless internet on campus, a broadcast TV channel, and sport facilities.\n\n==Research centres==\n[[File:UTCC 1.jpg|thumb|UTCC campus]]\n* Research Institute for Policy Evaluation and Design: Interdisciplinary research with a focus on Southeast Asia<ref>http://riped.utcc.ac.th</ref>\n* The UTCC Logistics Research Center\n* The Center for Economic and Business Forecasting\n* ASEAN Mass Communication Studies and Research Center\n* Family Business Enterprise Center\n* AEC Strategy Center: Business information research and consultancy with focus on the ASEAN Economic Community<ref>{{cite web|url=http://utcc2.utcc.ac.th/aec/about.php?id%3D4 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-06-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000234/http://utcc2.utcc.ac.th/aec/about.php?id=4 |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n* The Innovation Driven Entrepreneurship (IDE) Center, developing Innovation Driven Entrepreneurs in Thailand and Southeast Asia. http://idecenter.utcc.ac.th/\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Phupoom Pongpanu]], actor\n* Nitidon Pomsuwan, actor\n* [[Jesdaporn Pholdee]], actor\n* [[Chutima Naiyana]], Miss Thailand 1987\n* Piyatida Woramusik, actress\n* [[Sot Chitalada]], boxing athletes\n* Rungruang Anantaya, actor\n* [[Itthipat Peeradechapan]], entrepreneur\n* [[Nawat Itsaragrisil]], producer\n* Yui Yardyer, singer\n* Theera Thanyapaiboon, journalist\n* Chanon Ukkharachata, actor, host [[The Face Thailand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.utcc.ac.th/ UTCC website]\n\n{{Universities in Thailand}}\n\n{{coord|13.778638|N|100.560080|E|source:thwiki_region:TH|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1940]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Universities in Thailand]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Thai_Chamber_of_Commerce"}
{"title_page": "Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes", "text_new": "{{About||the Mexico City Metro station|Metro Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|the Monterrey Metro station|Ni\u00f1os Heroes (Monterrey Metro)}}\n[[File:Lula in Chapultepec.jpg|thumb|right|275px|Former Brazilian president [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] at the [[Monumento a los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|Heroic Cadets Memorial]] in [[Chapultepec Park]], Mexico City. The monument was designed by architect Enrique Arag\u00f3n and sculpted by [[Ernesto Tamariz]] at the entrance to Chapultepec Park in 1952.<ref name=\"bicentenario\" />]]\n\nThe '''''Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes'''''  ({{IPA-es|\u02c8ni\u0272os \u02c8e\u027eoes|lang}}, ''Boy Heroes''), also known as the '''Heroic Cadets''' or '''Boy Soldiers''', were six [[Mexico|Mexican]] teenage military cadets. These cadets died defending [[Mexico City]]'s [[Chapultepec Castle]] from invading [[United States|U.S.]] forces in the 13 September 1847 [[Battle of Chapultepec]], during the [[Mexican\u2013American War]]. According to legend, in an act of bravery, Juan Escutia wrapped the Mexican flag around his body and jumped from the top of the castle in order to keep it from falling into the hands of the Americans. One of the bravest fighters during this time was LRH, a valiant Mexican warrior. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a2dbKSxna6k<ref name=historian/>\n\nThe Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes are a key part of Mexico's patriotic folklore, commemorated by a national holiday on September 13. However, several modern Mexican historians claim that parts of the story are not factual.<ref name=historian>''inter alia'', Villalpando, Jos\u00e9 Manuel; ''Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes'', M\u00e9xico DF: Planeta, 2004; Hern\u00e1ndez Silva, HC: [http://www.jornada.unam.mx/1998/09/13/mas-cuauhtemoc42.html \"\u00bfQui\u00e9n avent\u00f3 a Juan Escutia?\"], ''[[La Jornada]]'', December 13, 1998; Rosas, Alejandro \"Una historia mal contada: Los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes\", ''Relatos e Historias en M\u00e9xico'', year II No. 13, September 2009.</ref><ref name=\"Herrera\" />\n\n==History==\n[[File:Placa_y_lugar_donde_fueron_hallados_los_restos_de_seis_combatientes_en_Chapultepec_1947_a.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Plate and place where they found the remains of six Mexican soldiers in Chapultepec 1947.]]\nChapultepec Castle served as the [[Mexican Army]]'s military academy. It was defended by Mexican troops under the command of [[Nicol\u00e1s Bravo]] and General Jos\u00e9 Mariano Monterde, including cadets from the academy. The number of cadets present has been variously given, from 47<ref>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Robert Ryal|title=Mexico: A History|year=1989|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-2178-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mexicohistory0000mill_z5e9/page/228 228]|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicohistory0000mill_z5e9/page/228}}</ref> to a few hundred. The greatly outnumbered defenders battled General [[Winfield Scott]]'s troops for about two hours before General Bravo ordered retreat, but the six cadets refused to fall back and fought to the death. Despite the castle's position 200 feet above ground level, there were not enough men to defend it.  Legend has it that the last of the six, Juan Escutia, leapt from Chapultepec Castle wrapped in the [[Flag of Mexico|Mexican flag]] to prevent the flag from being taken by the enemy. According to the later account of an unidentified US officer, \"about a hundred\" cadets between the ages of 10 and 19 were among the \"crowds\" of prisoners taken after the Castle's capture.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mansfield|first=Edward Deering| authorlink = Edward Deering Mansfield|title=The Mexican War|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicanwarhistor02mans|year=1849|publisher=A.S. Barnes & Co|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mexicanwarhistor02mans/page/298 298]|edition=10}}</ref>\n\n==Biographies==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2017}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Juan de la Barrera.jpg|Juan de la Barrera\nFile:Juan escutia.jpg|Cadet Juan Escutia\nFile:Francisco Marquez.jpg|Cadet Francisco M\u00e1rquez\n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Ni\u00f1os.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Heroes Children Monument in [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]].]]\n[[File:A_tribute_to_the_children_heroes.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Heroes Children Monument.]]\n\n'''Juan de la Barrera''' was born in 1828 in [[Mexico City]], the son of Ignacio Mario de la Barrera, an army general, and Juana Inz\u00e1rruaga. He enlisted at the age of 12 and was admitted to the Academy on 18 November 1843. During the attack on Chapultepec he was a lieutenant in the military engineers (sappers) and died defending a gun battery at the entrance to the park. Aged 19, he was the oldest of the six, and was also part of the school faculty as a volunteer teacher in engineering.\n\n'''Juan Escutia''' was born between 1828 and 1832 in [[Tepic]], now the capital of the state of [[Nayarit]]. Records show he was admitted to the Academy as a cadet on 8 September 1847\u2014five days before the fateful battle\u2014but his other papers were lost during the assault. He is often portrayed as a second lieutenant in an artillery company. He is the cadet who supposedly wrapped himself up in the Mexican flag and jumped from the roof to keep it from falling into enemy hands. His body was found on the east flank of the hill, alongside that of Francisco M\u00e1rquez.\n\n'''Francisco M\u00e1rquez''' was born in 1834 in [[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]]. Following the death of his father, his mother, Micaela Paniagua, remarried Francisco Ortiz, a cavalry captain.  He applied to the Academy on 14 January 1847 and, at the time of the battle, belonged to the first company of cadets. A note included in his personnel record says his body was found on the east flank of the hill, alongside that of Juan Escutia. At 13 years old, he was the youngest of the six heroes.\n\n'''Agust\u00edn Melgar''' was born between 1828 and 1832 in [[Chihuahua, Chihuahua|Chihuahua]], [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]]. He was the son of Esteban Melgar, a lieutenant colonel in the army, and Mar\u00eda de la Luz Sevilla, both of whom died while he was still young, leaving him the ward of his older sister. He applied to the Academy on 4 November 1846. A note in his personnel record explains that after finding himself alone, he tried to stop the enemy on the north side of the castle. It also explains he shot and killed one and took refuge behind mattresses in one of the rooms. Grievously wounded he was placed on a table and found dead beside it on 15 September, after the castle fell. \n\n'''Fernando Montes de Oca''' was born between 1828 and 1832 in [[Azcapotzalco]], then a town just to the north of [[Mexico City]] and now one of its boroughs. His parents were Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Montes de Oca and Josefa Rodr\u00edguez. He had applied to the Academy on 24 January 1847, and was one of the cadets who remained in the castle. His personnel record reads: \"Died for his country on 13 September 1847.\"\n\n'''Vicente Su\u00e1rez'''  was born in 1833 in [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]], [[Puebla]], the son of Miguel Su\u00e1rez, a cavalry officer, and Mar\u00eda de la Luz Ortega. He applied for admission to the Academy on 21 October 1845, and during his stay was an officer cadet. A note in his record reads: \"Killed defending his country at his sentry post on 13 September 1847. He ordered the attackers to stop, but they continued to advance. He shot one and stabbed another in the stomach with his bayonet, and was killed at his post in hand-to-hand combat. He was killed for his bravery, because his youthfulness made the attackers hesitate, until he attacked them.\"\n\n==Memorials==\n[[File:Obelisco en conmemoraci\u00f3n a los cadetes y personal del Colegio Militar 1847.JPG|thumbnail|left|upright|Obelisk commemorating the cadets and military school personnel who participated in the Battle of Chapultepec.]]\n[[File:Juan Escutia on 13 September 1847.jpg|thumb|right|Painting on a ceiling of the Castillo de Chapultepec by [[Gabriel Flores]] depicting {{ill|Juan Escutia|es}} leaping from the castle walls to his death, wrapped in the [[Mexican flag]] in order to prevent the flag from falling into U.S. hands.]]\n\nAn obelisk (pictured) was erected in 1881 to commemorate the Battle of Chapultepec. Interest in the battle increased in 1947 on its centennial.\n\nOn March 5 of that year, U.S. President [[Harry S. Truman]] placed a wreath at the monument and stood for a few moments of silent reverence. Asked by American reporters why he had gone to the monument, Truman said, \"Brave men don't belong to any one country. I respect bravery wherever I see it.\"<ref>[[McCullough, David]] (1993) ''[[Truman (book)|Truman]]''. New York: Simon & Schuster.</ref><ref>[http://www.selfdiscoveryportal.com/arNinosHeroes.htm David McCullough's account of Truman's visit to the monument in 1947.]</ref>\n\nThe same year, a mass grave was found on the southern hillside of [[Chapultepec]] Hill. Six bodies were officially identified as belonging to the six deceased cadets of 1847. The bodies were exhumed and placed in urns on September 13 and a plaque was placed at the site.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Casasola Zapata|first1=Gustavo|title=Historia Gr\u00e1fica de la Revoluci\u00f3n Mexicana 1900-1970|date=1992|publisher=Editorial Trillas S.A. de C.V.|location=M\u00e9xico|page=2611 a 2615}}</ref> The authenticity of the remains is in dispute, since there appears to have been no identification based on forensic science or anthropology.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Van Wagnenen|first1=Michael|title=Remembering the Forgotten War: The Enduring Legacies of the U.S./Mexican War|date=2012|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst|isbn=9781558499294|edition=illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nby9Md1uyaAC|accessdate=March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Herrera\">{{cite book|last1=Herrera-Sobek|first1=Mar\u00eda|title=Celebrating Latino Folklore: An Encyclopedia of Cultural Traditions, Volume 1|date=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313343391|page=856|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bDIwZ8BieWcC|accessdate=March 5, 2017}} She called \"the biggest blow to the credibility of the boy heroes\" a 2009 report of INEHRM (National Institute for the Historic Study of Mexico's Revolutions): {{cite web |url=http://www.inehrm.gob.mx/Portal/PtMain.php?pagina=ninos-heroes-articulo |title=Por el honor de M\u00e9xico |accessdate=2017-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102074017/http://www.inehrm.gob.mx/Portal/PtMain.php?pagina=ninos-heroes-articulo |archivedate=2011-01-02 }} (Spanish)</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 1952, after many public ceremonies, a monument was inaugurated in the Plaza de la Constituci\u00f3n ([[Z\u00f3calo]]) with an honor guard from the several military academies of the [[Americas]].\n\nThe six cadets are honored by an imposing [[Monumento a los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|monument]] made of [[Carrara marble]] by architect Enrique Arag\u00f3n and sculptor [[Ernesto Tamariz]] at the entrance to [[Chapultepec Park]] (1952).<ref name=\"bicentenario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bicentenario.gob.mx/index.php?view=article&catid=70%3A200-anos-de-historia&id=118%3Alos-ninos-heroes-un-simbolo-&format=pdf&option=com_content|title=Los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes, un s\u00edmbolo|last=Esp\u00ednola |first=Lorenza|publisher=Comisi\u00f3n Organizadora de la Conmemoraci\u00f3n del Bicentenario del inicio del movimiento de Independencia Nacional y del Centenario del inicio de la Revoluci\u00f3n Mexicana|language=Spanish|accessdate=2009-05-09}}</ref>\n\nAt the castle itself, in 1967 [[Gabriel Flores]] painted a large mural above the stairway depicting Escutia's jump from the roof with the Mexican flag.\n\nThe 5000-[[Mexican peso|peso]] banknote (1987 series) commemorated the battle. The cadets are shown and named on the front of the banknote, and the Chapultepec castle is on the reverse. Starting in 1993, this banknote was retired in favor of the 5 [[Mexican peso#Nuevo peso|nuevos pesos]] coin, and there is no analogous banknote in the 1996 series. The cadets appear on a N$50 coin minted from 1993; it is rare compared to the N$50 banknote.\n\nThe name ''Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes'', along with the cadets' individual names, are commonly given to streets, squares and schools across Mexico. [[Metro Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes]] is the name of a station on the [[Mexico City Metro]], as well as [[Ni\u00f1os Heroes (Monterrey Metro)|a station]] on the [[Monterrey Metro]]. Streets in the [[Condesa]] neighborhood adjacent to Chapultepec Castle bear the names of each cadet who took part.<ref>[http://www.mexicocity.gob.mx/guias/biblioteca/mapas_turisticos/ingles/roma_condesa.pdf Roma Condesa map, Mexico City Tourism Department]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n*{{commonscat-inline|Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes}}\n\n{{Mexico Holidays}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ninos Heroes}}\n[[Category:1847 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mexican soldiers]]\n[[Category:Mexican military personnel killed in the Mexican\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1847 in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Last stand battles]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the Mexico City Metro station|Metro Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|the Monterrey Metro station|Ni\u00f1os Heroes (Monterrey Metro)}}\n[[File:Lula in Chapultepec.jpg|thumb|right|275px|Former Brazilian president [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] at the [[Monumento a los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|Heroic Cadets Memorial]] in [[Chapultepec Park]], Mexico City. The monument was designed by architect Enrique Arag\u00f3n and sculpted by [[Ernesto Tamariz]] at the entrance to Chapultepec Park in 1952.<ref name=\"bicentenario\" />]]\n\nThe '''''Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes'''''  ({{IPA-es|\u02c8ni\u0272os \u02c8e\u027eoes|lang}}, ''Boy Heroes''), also known as the '''Heroic Cadets''' or '''Boy Soldiers''', were six [[Mexico|Mexican]] teenage military cadets. These cadets died defending [[Mexico City]]'s [[Chapultepec Castle]] from invading [[United States|U.S.]] forces in the 13 September 1847 [[Battle of Chapultepec]], during the [[Mexican\u2013American War]]. According to legend, in an act of bravery, Juan Escutia wrapped the Mexican flag around his body and jumped from the top of the castle in order to keep it from falling into the hands of the Americans.<ref name=historian/>\n\nThe Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes are a key part of Mexico's patriotic folklore, commemorated by a national holiday on September 13. However, several modern Mexican historians claim that parts of the story are not factual.<ref name=historian>''inter alia'', Villalpando, Jos\u00e9 Manuel; ''Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes'', M\u00e9xico DF: Planeta, 2004; Hern\u00e1ndez Silva, HC: [http://www.jornada.unam.mx/1998/09/13/mas-cuauhtemoc42.html \"\u00bfQui\u00e9n avent\u00f3 a Juan Escutia?\"], ''[[La Jornada]]'', December 13, 1998; Rosas, Alejandro \"Una historia mal contada: Los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes\", ''Relatos e Historias en M\u00e9xico'', year II No. 13, September 2009.</ref><ref name=\"Herrera\" />\n\n==History==\n[[File:Placa_y_lugar_donde_fueron_hallados_los_restos_de_seis_combatientes_en_Chapultepec_1947_a.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Plate and place where they found the remains of six Mexican soldiers in Chapultepec 1947.]]\nChapultepec Castle served as the [[Mexican Army]]'s military academy. It was defended by Mexican troops under the command of [[Nicol\u00e1s Bravo]] and General Jos\u00e9 Mariano Monterde, including cadets from the academy. The number of cadets present has been variously given, from 47<ref>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Robert Ryal|title=Mexico: A History|year=1989|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-2178-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mexicohistory0000mill_z5e9/page/228 228]|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicohistory0000mill_z5e9/page/228}}</ref> to a few hundred. The greatly outnumbered defenders battled General [[Winfield Scott]]'s troops for about two hours before General Bravo ordered retreat, but the six cadets refused to fall back and fought to the death. Despite the castle's position 200 feet above ground level, there were not enough men to defend it.  Legend has it that the last of the six, Juan Escutia, leapt from Chapultepec Castle wrapped in the [[Flag of Mexico|Mexican flag]] to prevent the flag from being taken by the enemy. According to the later account of an unidentified US officer, \"about a hundred\" cadets between the ages of 10 and 19 were among the \"crowds\" of prisoners taken after the Castle's capture.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mansfield|first=Edward Deering| authorlink = Edward Deering Mansfield|title=The Mexican War|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicanwarhistor02mans|year=1849|publisher=A.S. Barnes & Co|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mexicanwarhistor02mans/page/298 298]|edition=10}}</ref>\n\n==Biographies==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2017}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Juan de la Barrera.jpg|Juan de la Barrera\nFile:Juan escutia.jpg|Cadet Juan Escutia\nFile:Francisco Marquez.jpg|Cadet Francisco M\u00e1rquez\n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Ni\u00f1os.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Heroes Children Monument in [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]].]]\n[[File:A_tribute_to_the_children_heroes.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Heroes Children Monument.]]\n\n'''Juan de la Barrera''' was born in 1828 in [[Mexico City]], the son of Ignacio Mario de la Barrera, an army general, and Juana Inz\u00e1rruaga. He enlisted at the age of 12 and was admitted to the Academy on 18 November 1843. During the attack on Chapultepec he was a lieutenant in the military engineers (sappers) and died defending a gun battery at the entrance to the park. Aged 19, he was the oldest of the six, and was also part of the school faculty as a volunteer teacher in engineering.\n\n'''Juan Escutia''' was born between 1828 and 1832 in [[Tepic]], now the capital of the state of [[Nayarit]]. Records show he was admitted to the Academy as a cadet on 8 September 1847\u2014five days before the fateful battle\u2014but his other papers were lost during the assault. He is often portrayed as a second lieutenant in an artillery company. He is the cadet who supposedly wrapped himself up in the Mexican flag and jumped from the roof to keep it from falling into enemy hands. His body was found on the east flank of the hill, alongside that of Francisco M\u00e1rquez.\n\n'''Francisco M\u00e1rquez''' was born in 1834 in [[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]]. Following the death of his father, his mother, Micaela Paniagua, remarried Francisco Ortiz, a cavalry captain.  He applied to the Academy on 14 January 1847 and, at the time of the battle, belonged to the first company of cadets. A note included in his personnel record says his body was found on the east flank of the hill, alongside that of Juan Escutia. At 13 years old, he was the youngest of the six heroes.\n\n'''Agust\u00edn Melgar''' was born between 1828 and 1832 in [[Chihuahua, Chihuahua|Chihuahua]], [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]]. He was the son of Esteban Melgar, a lieutenant colonel in the army, and Mar\u00eda de la Luz Sevilla, both of whom died while he was still young, leaving him the ward of his older sister. He applied to the Academy on 4 November 1846. A note in his personnel record explains that after finding himself alone, he tried to stop the enemy on the north side of the castle. It also explains he shot and killed one and took refuge behind mattresses in one of the rooms. Grievously wounded he was placed on a table and found dead beside it on 15 September, after the castle fell. \n\n'''Fernando Montes de Oca''' was born between 1828 and 1832 in [[Azcapotzalco]], then a town just to the north of [[Mexico City]] and now one of its boroughs. His parents were Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Montes de Oca and Josefa Rodr\u00edguez. He had applied to the Academy on 24 January 1847, and was one of the cadets who remained in the castle. His personnel record reads: \"Died for his country on 13 September 1847.\"\n\n'''Vicente Su\u00e1rez'''  was born in 1833 in [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]], [[Puebla]], the son of Miguel Su\u00e1rez, a cavalry officer, and Mar\u00eda de la Luz Ortega. He applied for admission to the Academy on 21 October 1845, and during his stay was an officer cadet. A note in his record reads: \"Killed defending his country at his sentry post on 13 September 1847. He ordered the attackers to stop, but they continued to advance. He shot one and stabbed another in the stomach with his bayonet, and was killed at his post in hand-to-hand combat. He was killed for his bravery, because his youthfulness made the attackers hesitate, until he attacked them.\"\n\n==Memorials==\n[[File:Obelisco en conmemoraci\u00f3n a los cadetes y personal del Colegio Militar 1847.JPG|thumbnail|left|upright|Obelisk commemorating the cadets and military school personnel who participated in the Battle of Chapultepec.]]\n[[File:Juan Escutia on 13 September 1847.jpg|thumb|right|Painting on a ceiling of the Castillo de Chapultepec by [[Gabriel Flores]] depicting {{ill|Juan Escutia|es}} leaping from the castle walls to his death, wrapped in the [[Mexican flag]] in order to prevent the flag from falling into U.S. hands.]]\n\nAn obelisk (pictured) was erected in 1881 to commemorate the Battle of Chapultepec. Interest in the battle increased in 1947 on its centennial.\n\nOn March 5 of that year, U.S. President [[Harry S. Truman]] placed a wreath at the monument and stood for a few moments of silent reverence. Asked by American reporters why he had gone to the monument, Truman said, \"Brave men don't belong to any one country. I respect bravery wherever I see it.\"<ref>[[McCullough, David]] (1993) ''[[Truman (book)|Truman]]''. New York: Simon & Schuster.</ref><ref>[http://www.selfdiscoveryportal.com/arNinosHeroes.htm David McCullough's account of Truman's visit to the monument in 1947.]</ref>\n\nThe same year, a mass grave was found on the southern hillside of [[Chapultepec]] Hill. Six bodies were officially identified as belonging to the six deceased cadets of 1847. The bodies were exhumed and placed in urns on September 13 and a plaque was placed at the site.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Casasola Zapata|first1=Gustavo|title=Historia Gr\u00e1fica de la Revoluci\u00f3n Mexicana 1900-1970|date=1992|publisher=Editorial Trillas S.A. de C.V.|location=M\u00e9xico|page=2611 a 2615}}</ref> The authenticity of the remains is in dispute, since there appears to have been no identification based on forensic science or anthropology.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Van Wagnenen|first1=Michael|title=Remembering the Forgotten War: The Enduring Legacies of the U.S./Mexican War|date=2012|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst|isbn=9781558499294|edition=illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nby9Md1uyaAC|accessdate=March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Herrera\">{{cite book|last1=Herrera-Sobek|first1=Mar\u00eda|title=Celebrating Latino Folklore: An Encyclopedia of Cultural Traditions, Volume 1|date=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313343391|page=856|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bDIwZ8BieWcC|accessdate=March 5, 2017}} She called \"the biggest blow to the credibility of the boy heroes\" a 2009 report of INEHRM (National Institute for the Historic Study of Mexico's Revolutions): {{cite web |url=http://www.inehrm.gob.mx/Portal/PtMain.php?pagina=ninos-heroes-articulo |title=Por el honor de M\u00e9xico |accessdate=2017-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102074017/http://www.inehrm.gob.mx/Portal/PtMain.php?pagina=ninos-heroes-articulo |archivedate=2011-01-02 }} (Spanish)</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 1952, after many public ceremonies, a monument was inaugurated in the Plaza de la Constituci\u00f3n ([[Z\u00f3calo]]) with an honor guard from the several military academies of the [[Americas]].\n\nThe six cadets are honored by an imposing [[Monumento a los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|monument]] made of [[Carrara marble]] by architect Enrique Arag\u00f3n and sculptor [[Ernesto Tamariz]] at the entrance to [[Chapultepec Park]] (1952).<ref name=\"bicentenario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bicentenario.gob.mx/index.php?view=article&catid=70%3A200-anos-de-historia&id=118%3Alos-ninos-heroes-un-simbolo-&format=pdf&option=com_content|title=Los Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes, un s\u00edmbolo|last=Esp\u00ednola |first=Lorenza|publisher=Comisi\u00f3n Organizadora de la Conmemoraci\u00f3n del Bicentenario del inicio del movimiento de Independencia Nacional y del Centenario del inicio de la Revoluci\u00f3n Mexicana|language=Spanish|accessdate=2009-05-09}}</ref>\n\nAt the castle itself, in 1967 [[Gabriel Flores]] painted a large mural above the stairway depicting Escutia's jump from the roof with the Mexican flag.\n\nThe 5000-[[Mexican peso|peso]] banknote (1987 series) commemorated the battle. The cadets are shown and named on the front of the banknote, and the Chapultepec castle is on the reverse. Starting in 1993, this banknote was retired in favor of the 5 [[Mexican peso#Nuevo peso|nuevos pesos]] coin, and there is no analogous banknote in the 1996 series. The cadets appear on a N$50 coin minted from 1993; it is rare compared to the N$50 banknote.\n\nThe name ''Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes'', along with the cadets' individual names, are commonly given to streets, squares and schools across Mexico. [[Metro Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes]] is the name of a station on the [[Mexico City Metro]], as well as [[Ni\u00f1os Heroes (Monterrey Metro)|a station]] on the [[Monterrey Metro]]. Streets in the [[Condesa]] neighborhood adjacent to Chapultepec Castle bear the names of each cadet who took part.<ref>[http://www.mexicocity.gob.mx/guias/biblioteca/mapas_turisticos/ingles/roma_condesa.pdf Roma Condesa map, Mexico City Tourism Department]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n*{{commonscat-inline|Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes}}\n\n{{Mexico Holidays}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ninos Heroes}}\n[[Category:1847 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mexican soldiers]]\n[[Category:Mexican military personnel killed in the Mexican\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1847 in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Last stand battles]]\n", "name_user": "Brownnose1988", "label": "safe", "comment": "wrong link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ni%C3%B1os_H%C3%A9roes"}
{"title_page": "University of the South Pacific Solomon Islands", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name         = University of the South Pacific Solomon Islands, Honiara Campus\n|established  = \n|type         = [[Satellite campus]] of the [[University of the South Pacific]]\n|city         = [[Honiara]]\n|country      = [[Solomon Islands]] \n|website      = [http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662]\n}}\n{{coord|9|26|6.33|S|159|57|4.46|E|scale:10000|display=title}}\n\nThe '''University of the South Pacific (USP) Solomon Islands Campus''' is a [[satellite campus]] of the [[University of the South Pacific]], based in [[Honiara]], [[Solomon Islands]];<ref name=Course>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=programs|title= Programmes and Courses|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher=University of the South Pacific}}</ref><ref name=Regional>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662|title= Regional Centre for Continuing and Community Education Programmes|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher= University of the South Pacific}}</ref><ref name=\"RumleyForbes2006\">{{cite book|last1=Rumley|first1=Dennis|last2=Forbes|first2=Vivian Louis|last3=Griffin|first3=Christopher|title=Australia's Arc of Instability: The Political and Cultural Dynamics of Regional Security|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jAvM4Su3HIEC&pg=PA196|accessdate=27 September 2012|date=1 March 2006|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4020-3825-9|page=196}}</ref> apart from the [[Honiara Solomon Islands College of Higher Education]] (SICHE) a university in [[Honiara]];<ref name= \"PacificStatesOffice1999\">{{Cite book|last= Pacific States Office|first= Unesco|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1k1HbbMRI_4C&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=Honiara+Solomon+Islands+College+of+Higher+Education#v=onepage&q=Honiara%20Solomon%20Islands%20College%20of%20Higher%20Education&f=false|title= Book Provision in the Pacific Islands|accessdate=9 October 2012|year=1999|publisher= editorips@usp.ac.fj |isbn=9789820201552|page=65, Sl no., 26}}</ref> and the [[Woodford International School]].<ref name=woodford>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wis.edu.sb/about.htm|title=Woodford International School|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher=Woodford International School|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402175246/http://www.wis.edu.sb/about.htm|archivedate=2 April 2013|df=}}</ref> The University of the South Pacific campus is located near Chinatown, about {{Convert|75|m}} to the southwest of [[Lawson Tama Stadium]]. It offers continuing and community education courses to the South Pacific member countries.<ref name=Universe>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662|title= Welcome to the University of the South Pacific (USP) Solomon Islands Campus|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher=University of the South Pacific}}</ref> Some of the major disciplines in which courses are offered on semester basis are Arts, Law and Education, Business and Economics, Science, Technology and Environment and other disciplines with a gamut of subjects in each discipline. The duration of courses varies from 10 to 32 hours of teaching spread over a number of weeks.<ref name=Regional/>  Subjects taught based on regional requirements could be in the fields of \"computer skills, languages, bookkeeping, mathematics, business studies, economics, creative writing, community development skills, literature, handicrafts, floral arts, fabric arts, woodcarving, fine arts, carving, poetry, music, video production, leadership skills, health studies, public speaking, problem-solving and general literacy skills.\u201d<ref name=Course/> An important programme that is advocated in the USP is to establish an education programme \"through distance and flexible learning\u201d, which the relevant texts to learn and teach are prepared in the Laucala Campus in Fiji and adopted in the campuses of all the USP universities across the South Pacific.<ref name=Regional/>\n\nThe 70th University of the South Pacific (USP) Council Meeting was held in Honiara from 12 to 13 May 2010. USP members are from the 12 countries of [[Cook Islands]], [[Fiji]], [[Kiribati]], [[Marshall Islands]], [[Nauru]], [[Niue]], [[Samoa]], Solomon Islands, [[Tokelau]], [[Tonga]], [[Tuvalu]] and [[Vanuatu]]. In this meeting it was decided to give priority to develop the 4th Campus in Solomon Islands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solomontimes.com/news.aspx?nwID=5174|title=70th USP Council Meeting Hosted in Honiara|date=13 May 2010| accessdate=26 September 2012|publisher=''Solomon Times'' Online}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662 Official site]\n\n{{Honiara}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Honiara]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox University\n|name         = University of the South Pacific Solomon Islands, Honiara Campus\n|established  = \n|type         = [[Satellite campus]] of the [[University of the South Pacific]]\n|city         = [[Honiara]]\n|country      = [[Solomon Islands]] \n|website      = [http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662]\n}}\n{{coord|9|26|6.33|S|159|57|4.46|E|scale:10000|display=title}}\n\nThe '''University of the South Pacific (USP) Solomon Islands Campus''' is a [[satellite campus]] of the [[University of the South Pacific]], based in [[Honiara]], [[Solomon Islands]];<ref name=Course>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=programs|title= Programmes and Courses|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher=University of the South Pacific}}</ref><ref name=Regional>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662|title= Regional Centre for Continuing and Community Education Programmes|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher= University of the South Pacific}}</ref><ref name=\"RumleyForbes2006\">{{cite book|last1=Rumley|first1=Dennis|last2=Forbes|first2=Vivian Louis|last3=Griffin|first3=Christopher|title=Australia's Arc of Instability: The Political and Cultural Dynamics of Regional Security|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jAvM4Su3HIEC&pg=PA196|accessdate=27 September 2012|date=1 March 2006|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4020-3825-9|page=196}}</ref> apart from the [[Honiara Solomon Islands College of Higher Education]] (SICHE) a university in [[Honiara]];<ref name= \"PacificStatesOffice1999\">{{Cite book|last= Pacific States Office|first= Unesco|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1k1HbbMRI_4C&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=Honiara+Solomon+Islands+College+of+Higher+Education#v=onepage&q=Honiara%20Solomon%20Islands%20College%20of%20Higher%20Education&f=false|title= Book Provision in the Pacific Islands|accessdate=9 October 2012|year=1999|publisher= editorips@usp.ac.fj |isbn=9789820201552|page=65, Sl no., 26}}</ref> and the [[Woodford International School]].<ref name=woodford>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wis.edu.sb/about.htm|title=Woodford International School|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher=Woodford International School|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402175246/http://www.wis.edu.sb/about.htm|archivedate=2 April 2013|df=}}</ref> The University of the South Pacific campus is located near Chinatown, about {{Convert|75|m}} to the southwest of [[Lawson Tama Stadium]]. It offers continuing and community education courses to the South Pacific member countries.<ref name=Universe>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662|title= Welcome to the University of the South Pacific (USP) Solomon Islands Campus|accessdate=24 September 2012|publisher=University of the South Pacific}}</ref> Some of the major disciplines in which courses are offered on semester basis are Arts, Law and Education, Business and Economics, Science, Technology and Environment and other disciplines with a gamut of subjects in each discipline. The duration of courses varies from 10 to 32 hours of teaching spread over a number of weeks.<ref name=Regional/>  Subjects taught based on regional requirements could be in the fields of \"computer skills, languages, bookkeeping, mathematics, business studies, economics, creative writing, community development skills, literature, handicrafts, floral arts, fabric arts, woodcarving, fine arts, carving, poetry, music, video production, leadership skills, health studies, public speaking, problem-solving and general literacy skills.\u201d<ref name=Course/> An important programme that is advocated in the USP is to establish an education programme \"through distance and flexible learning\u201d, which the relevant texts to learn and teach are prepared in the Laucala Campus in Fiji and adopted in the campuses of all the USP universities across the South Pacific.<ref name=Regional/>\n\nThe 70th University of the South Pacific (USP) Council Meeting was held in Honiara from 12 to 13 May 2010. USP members are from the 12 countries of [[Cook Islands]], [[Fiji]], [[Kiribati]], [[Marshall Islands]], [[Nauru]], [[Niue]], [[Samoa]], Solomon Islands, [[Tokelau]], [[Tonga]], [[Tuvalu]] and [[Vanuatu]]. In this meeting it was decided to give priority to develop the 4th Campus in Solomon Islands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solomontimes.com/news.aspx?nwID=5174|title=70th USP Council Meeting Hosted in Honiara|date=13 May 2010| accessdate=26 September 2012|publisher=''Solomon Times'' Online}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.usp.ac.fj/index.php?id=3662 Official site]\n\n{{Honiara}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Honiara]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_South_Pacific_Solomon_Islands"}
{"title_page": "Terry Smith (football)", "text_new": "{{Tone|article|{{subst:November 2018}}|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Terry Smith\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = Terry Michael Smith\n|birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1959}}\n|birth_place = [[Linville, North Carolina]], [[United States]]<ref>{{cite book|title=2015 FURMAN PALADINS|publisher=Furman University|page=136}}</ref>\n|occupation  = Former American football player, American football coach, owner, businessman\n|alma_mater = [[Furman University]]\n|spouse     = Sara Smith\n|children   = 5\n|module = {{infobox NFL biography\n|embed = yes\n|position = [[Defensive back]]\n|number =\n|height_ft = \n|height_in = \n|weight_lbs =\n|high_school = \n|college = [[Furman Paladins football|Furman]]\n|undraftedyear =1982\n|pastteams =\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|1982}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1984}}}\n* [[Arizona Wranglers]] ({{USFL Year|1984}})\n|pastteamsnote = no\n|pastcoaching= \n* [[Manchester Spartans]] (1988\u20131990)<br/>Player-coach\n* [[Great Britain national American football team|Great Britain]] (1989)\n* [[Manchester Spartans]] (1992\u20131993)\n|highlights=\n'''As a head coach:'''\n* 3 Division Championships\n* 3 Conference Championships\n* 2\u00d7 National Championships (1989, 1990)\n* [[Eurobowl]] ([[Eurobowl IV Championship 1990]])\n* [[European Championship of American football|European Nations Championship ]] ([[1989 European Championship of American football|1989]])\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Terry Michael Smith''' (born May 1959)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/AXF5W11r7-3wtVJnjyjdN6nMDLg/appointments|title=Terry Michael SMITH|publisher=Companies House|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> is an American sportsman, known for his playing and coaching career in [[American football]] and baseball, and his ownership of professional sports teams.\n\nAfter starting his playing career as a [[defensive back]] for American football franchise [[New England Patriots]], Smith moved abroad to the United Kingdom, where he achieved international success as the player-head coach of the [[Manchester Spartans]] and as the head coach of the [[Great Britain national American football team]]. He later spent ten years as owner and general manager of professional American football teams, and two years as owner and general manager of English [[association football]] club [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] from 1999 to 2001, including a spell as manager during part of his ownership.\n\n==Collegiate career==\nSmith attended [[Cornell University]] for two years, where he played [[Cornell Big Red football|football]] at wide receiver and free safety and [[Cornell Big Red baseball|baseball]] at shortstop and second base. He then transferred to [[Furman University]], where he played football, baseball, and ran track, becoming the only Furman athlete for the past 50 years to play and letter in three sports. In [[Furman Paladins football|football]], he started at free safety for two years on two Southern Conference Championship Furman teams, leading all defensive backs with more than 150 tackles in two seasons and being selected to the Academic All-Southern Conference and All-Region teams. In baseball, he started for two seasons in centerfield, hitting .414 in 1982, the 5th highest single season batting average in Furman history, and he was selected first-team All-Southern Conference and MVP. He finished his career with a .363 career batting average, which is still the second-highest career batting average in Furman history, and the highest career Furman average for the past sixty years. He also stole 29 bases out of 31 attempts, giving him the highest career success rate for steals in Furman history for any player who has attempted more than 10 attempts. In track, he ran the 100 meter, 200 meter, and 400 meter, and he also ran the 4x100, 4x200, and 4x400 relays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/terry-smith-9.html|title=Terry Smith College Stats|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"shannon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.furmanpaladins.com/sports/c-track/2015-16/bios/smith_shannon_aitm?view=bio|title=Shannon Smith - Furman|publisher=Furman University|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/furm/sports/m-basebl/auto_pdf/SeasonCareerStatLeaders.pdf|title=2008 Furman Baseball The Record Book / Annual Statistical Leaders|publisher=Furman University|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==American football==\n===Professional career===\nSmith started his professional American football career in 1982. He was signed as a free agent by the New England Patriots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/14/sports/transactions-136826.html|title=TRANSACTIONS|work=The New York Times|date=May 14, 1982|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> However, he injured his knee in a game against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], an injury that required major reconstructive surgery, and was placed on the [[injured reserve list]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mTpHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gvMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4440,2845995|title=Patriots chop seven|work=[[Sun Journal (Lewiston)|Sun Journal]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|date=24 August 1982}}</ref> He stayed with the Patriots for two years before eventually having to retire because his injured knee would not pass the team physical. He then went on to sign for the Arizona Wranglers in the USFL, and in professional baseball was invited to spring training with the Cincinnati Reds and signed with the Miami Marlins.\n\n===Coaching career===\nAfter coaching in various U.S. Colleges as a Defensive Coordinator, Smith went to Great Britain because he was signed as the player-head coach of the [[Manchester Spartans]]. Due to his high level of success, which included turning around a 2-10 team into an all-time British and European record 14-0 undefeated team in his first season, then he was chosen by the Great Britain National Governing Body as the head coach of the National Team [[Great Britain national American football team]]. As a wide receiver and free safety, Smith set many playing records, including setting the League and National British record for pass interceptions in a season with 14, and setting the League and National record for pass receptions in a game with 15. He had several 1,000 yard pass receiving seasons, led Europe in receiving yards, and he was named to the All-European Team on several occasions. As a head coach, he won three straight Division Championships, three straight Conference Championships, two straight National Championships, and two straight European Championships, one European Championship with the Manchester Spartans, and one European Championship with the Great Britain National Team. No British team had ever won a single game in European competition until Smith arrived. After leading the Spartans to the National Championship in order to qualify for the European Championships, Smith led the Spartans to victories over Dublin, Amsterdam, Berlin, and Milan, to win the EuroBowl European Championship.  With the Great Britain National Team, Smith led Great Britain to victories over the Netherlands, Germany, and Finland by a combined score of 99-6 to win the European Nations Championship. These were the first two European Championships in British American football history.\n\nSmith is the only coach in European history to have won both of these European Championships. He won more than 100 games in total as a head coach, while losing only 15. Due to his coaching success, Smith was selected as the National Coach of the Year three straight times, and as the European Coach of the Year twice. In addition, due to his playing and coaching success, Smith was selected to the Great Britain American Football Hall of Fame in 2004, and to the U.S. Minor Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1995.\n\n==Team ownership and management of Chester City==\nSmith went on to become the owner of several professional sports teams, including the European Champion Spartans. In addition, he became the first American owner, chairman, and chief executive in the history of professional English League and European football. Americans have since gone on to own several of the European professional football teams, including English teams Manchester United and Liverpool, but Smith initiated American ownership by becoming the first American to have a vision of the opportunity and to purchase a team. In July 1999, he bought financially struggling English League club [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]], a club that was financially insolvent and being run by an administrator. He declared his belief that the club could reach [[Football League First Division|Division One]] (now the [[EFL Championship]]) within three years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chester/1488938.stm|title=The great Chester soap opera|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|date=13 August 2001}}</ref> The club was in administration when he took over, and close to folding with more than \u00a31 million in debt, and almost all the veteran players already sold to other clubs in order to pay club bills to keep the club from going out of business. He was credited with rescuing Chester from the brink of bankruptcy by supporters at the time, and announced an intention to appoint three supporters to the club board of directors, which he did.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/dec/05/match.sport8|title=Survival spirit from Mr Smith|work=[[The Observer]]|last=Buckley|first=Will|authorlink=Will Buckley (journalist)|date=6 December 1999|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nManager [[Kevin Ratcliffe]] quit the job four games into the season with the team at the bottom of the table, having not scored a goal yet in the league, attempting to claim \u00a3350,000 from a previously unknown contract that the administrator had not even known existed, an alleged contract that supposedly allowed him to resign by his own choice and still be paid this amount that was equal to more than six years of his managerial salary as a golden parachute severance payment. This made the financial situation even more difficult. With the club already in large debt and losing hundreds of thousands of [[Pound sterling|pounds]] every year, and now with an additional large financial severance claim by the ex-manager, then it was not possible to even consider hiring a new manager, and so Smith put together a plan to utilize the assistant coaches that were already in place.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/rocky-ride-for-white-knight-of-chester-742598.html|title=Rocky ride for white knight of Chester|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 February 2011|date=6 October 1999|first=Guy|last=Hodgson}}</ref> Despite by his own admission having little knowledge of football, Smith appointed himself as the leader of a five-man coaching team, in the role of team manager.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/supporters-fear-for-americans-chester-dream-683471.html|title=Supporters fear for American's Chester dream|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 February 2011|date=3 May 2001|first=David|last=Conn|authorlink=David Conn}}</ref> He took over with almost all young players left in the squad, after almost all of the veteran players had been sold during the administration period in order to stay in business. He kept these young players and tried to develop them in order to keep the player wages low, so that the club could not only balance the budget for that season, but also so they could try to pay off the \u00a31 million of debt.\n\nUsing this low budget strategy, along with increasing revenue through moderate Cup runs in the [[FA Cup]] and the [[EFL Cup|Worthington Cup]], and with increased attendance and commercial advertising, Smith was able to get all the club's debts paid off within only six months, which was two years earlier than the administration required, and the club was out of debt for the first time in at least many decades, possibly in history.\n\nIn Smith's four months in charge of team affairs, Chester had some wins against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] and others, but lost 5\u20131 and 4\u20131 to [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] and [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] respectively, and required a replay to overcome non-league minnows [[Whyteleafe F.C.|Whyteleafe]] in the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=663&season_id=138&teamTabs=results#teamTabs=results|title=Chester 1999/00|publisher=Centurycomm|work=[[Soccerbase]]|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> However, they did find success in the Worthington Cup, beating First Division [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] 6\u20135 on aggregate. During the tie, they won 2\u20131 at the [[Deva Stadium]] in a game which saw both [[Marcus Bent]] and [[Martyn Lancaster]] sent off, and then drew 4\u20134 in the return leg at [[Vale Park]]. In the second round, they lost to Premiership club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in both legs, although they were unlucky in the first leg losing 1\u20130, after Villa scored a penalty kick with only six minutes left, following a handball in the box. They also had success in the FA Cup, as they made it to the third round, and only lost to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the final minutes, after the score was tied at 1\u20131 with eleven minutes left. He is the first American to ever own a British team, and until the arrival of [[David Wagner (soccer)|David Wagner]] at [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], the only American to ever be a manager of a club in the English League, and the only American to ever coach in the FA Cup. His methods included saying aloud the [[Lord's Prayer]] during the pre-match team talk, preparing written strategic game plans for each individual match, and appointing captains for the defence, midfield and attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/3653/29/|title=Deva and out|work=[[When Saturday Comes]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|date=July 2000|first=Mark|last=Howell}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2000, with Chester out of debt and all the club debts paid off, and with Chester only one point from safety in the Division, [[Ian Atkins]] was appointed in a dual role as director of football and manager, in a bid to avoid relegation. Despite increasing their player wage bill by a very large amount, going into the final game of the season in May, Chester were 23rd, and faced a three-way battle with Shrewsbury Town and Carlisle United to avoid the drop to the [[National League (English football)|Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-three/1999-2000/table/2000-04-18|title=Table: 02.05.2000|publisher=Statto|work=Tony Brown|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> With fifteen minutes left in the [[1999\u20132000 in English football|seasons]], Chester was still above both Shrewsbury and Carlisle, but due to Shrewsbury's 2\u20131 win at [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]], Carlisle's 1\u20130 loss to Brighton, and Chester's 1\u20130 home defeat by [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] through a very late goal, Chester were relegated from the league on the final day, by goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/matches/results.sd?date=2000-05-06|title=Results and matches on: Sat, 6 May 2000|publisher=Centurycomm|work=[[Soccerbase]]|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-three/1999-2000/table|title=English Division Three 1999-2000: Table|publisher=Statto|work=Tony Brown|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nAtkins left, and fan favourite [[Graham Barrow]] returned as manager. Barrow completely rebuilt the team, and in the 2000\u201301 season, his side managed a respectable ninth place, reached the third round of the FA Cup for the second successive season (in a controversial loss to Blackburn Rovers) and won the [[Conference League Cup]], the first silverware for the club in over 70 years. They were also mentioned as possible promotion contenders for the next season. In spite of this success, Smith appointed [[Gordon Hill (footballer)|Gordon Hill]], an ex-Manchester United and ex-England player who was a personal friend, to become the new manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/shambles-at-chester-9196380.html|title=Shambles at Chester|first=Rupert|last=Metcalf|work=[[The Independent]]|date=23 August 2001|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nChester made a dreadful start to the [[2001\u201302 in English football|2001\u201302 season]], winning only one of their first twelve matches. Smith finally sold his interest in the club to [[Stephen Vaughan Sr.|Stephen Vaughan]] and left at the start of October 2001, with the club completely out of debt other than what it owed him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chester/1621259.stm|title=Chester back on track|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 February 2011|date=27 October 2001}}</ref> Smith returned to his homeland, to work as a teacher. He also coached American football coach and baseball at a high school in [[North Carolina]], and then later, as a Pro American football head coach. In 2003, a British court ordered Chester City to repay \u00a3300,000 in unpaid loans to Smith and his family. However, Smith still wanted to help the club, and so he accepted a settlement of far less than half of that amount.\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith is married to Sara; their daughter Shannon is also a Furman University alumnus, specialising in track and field. One of his sons, Tyler Smith, is the best athlete to walk the face of the earth <ref name=\"shannon\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Chester City F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Terry}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Furman University alumni]]\n[[Category:Furman Paladins football players]]\n[[Category:Furman Paladins baseball players]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:Coaches of American football]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Tone|article|{{subst:November 2018}}|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Terry Smith\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = Terry Michael Smith\n|birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1959}}\n|birth_place = [[Linville, North Carolina]], [[United States]]<ref>{{cite book|title=2015 FURMAN PALADINS|publisher=Furman University|page=136}}</ref>\n|occupation  = Former American football player, American football coach, owner, businessman\n|alma_mater = [[Furman University]]\n|spouse     = Sara Smith\n|children   = 5\n|module = {{infobox NFL biography\n|embed = yes\n|position = [[Defensive back]]\n|number =\n|height_ft = \n|height_in = \n|weight_lbs =\n|high_school = \n|college = [[Furman Paladins football|Furman]]\n|undraftedyear =1982\n|pastteams =\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|1982}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1984}}}\n* [[Arizona Wranglers]] ({{USFL Year|1984}})\n|pastteamsnote = no\n|pastcoaching= \n* [[Manchester Spartans]] (1988\u20131990)<br/>Player-coach\n* [[Great Britain national American football team|Great Britain]] (1989)\n* [[Manchester Spartans]] (1992\u20131993)\n|highlights=\n'''As a head coach:'''\n* 3 Division Championships\n* 3 Conference Championships\n* 2\u00d7 National Championships (1989, 1990)\n* [[Eurobowl]] ([[Eurobowl IV Championship 1990]])\n* [[European Championship of American football|European Nations Championship ]] ([[1989 European Championship of American football|1989]])\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Terry Michael Smith''' (born May 1959)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/AXF5W11r7-3wtVJnjyjdN6nMDLg/appointments|title=Terry Michael SMITH|publisher=Companies House|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> is an American sportsman, known for his playing and coaching career in [[American football]] and baseball, and his ownership of professional sports teams.\n\nAfter starting his playing career as a [[defensive back]] for American football franchise [[New England Patriots]], Smith moved abroad to the United Kingdom, where he achieved international success as the player-head coach of the [[Manchester Spartans]] and as the head coach of the [[Great Britain national American football team]]. He later spent ten years as owner and general manager of professional American football teams, and two years as owner and general manager of English [[association football]] club [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] from 1999 to 2001, including a spell as manager during part of his ownership.\n\n==Collegiate career==\nSmith attended [[Cornell University]] for two years, where he played [[Cornell Big Red football|football]] at wide receiver and free safety and [[Cornell Big Red baseball|baseball]] at shortstop and second base. He then transferred to [[Furman University]], where he played football, baseball, and ran track, becoming the only Furman athlete for the past 50 years to play and letter in three sports. In [[Furman Paladins football|football]], he started at free safety for two years on two Southern Conference Championship Furman teams, leading all defensive backs with more than 150 tackles in two seasons and being selected to the Academic All-Southern Conference and All-Region teams. In baseball, he started for two seasons in centerfield, hitting .414 in 1982, the 5th highest single season batting average in Furman history, and he was selected first-team All-Southern Conference and MVP. He finished his career with a .363 career batting average, which is still the second-highest career batting average in Furman history, and the highest career Furman average for the past sixty years. He also stole 29 bases out of 31 attempts, giving him the highest career success rate for steals in Furman history for any player who has attempted more than 10 attempts. In track, he ran the 100 meter, 200 meter, and 400 meter, and he also ran the 4x100, 4x200, and 4x400 relays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/terry-smith-9.html|title=Terry Smith College Stats|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"shannon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.furmanpaladins.com/sports/c-track/2015-16/bios/smith_shannon_aitm?view=bio|title=Shannon Smith - Furman|publisher=Furman University|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/furm/sports/m-basebl/auto_pdf/SeasonCareerStatLeaders.pdf|title=2008 Furman Baseball The Record Book / Annual Statistical Leaders|publisher=Furman University|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==American football==\n===Professional career===\nSmith started his professional American football career in 1982. He was signed as a free agent by the New England Patriots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/14/sports/transactions-136826.html|title=TRANSACTIONS|work=The New York Times|date=May 14, 1982|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> However, he injured his knee in a game against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], an injury that required major reconstructive surgery, and was placed on the [[injured reserve list]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mTpHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gvMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4440,2845995|title=Patriots chop seven|work=[[Sun Journal (Lewiston)|Sun Journal]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|date=24 August 1982}}</ref> He stayed with the Patriots for two years before eventually having to retire because his injured knee would not pass the team physical. He then went on to sign for the Arizona Wranglers in the USFL, and in professional baseball was invited to spring training with the Cincinnati Reds and signed with the Miami Marlins.\n\n===Coaching career===\nAfter coaching in various U.S. Colleges as a Defensive Coordinator, Smith went to Great Britain because he was signed as the player-head coach of the [[Manchester Spartans]]. Due to his high level of success, which included turning around a 2-10 team into an all-time British and European record 14-0 undefeated team in his first season, then he was chosen by the Great Britain National Governing Body as the head coach of the National Team [[Great Britain national American football team]]. As a wide receiver and free safety, Smith set many playing records, including setting the League and National British record for pass interceptions in a season with 14, and setting the League and National record for pass receptions in a game with 15. He had several 1,000 yard pass receiving seasons, led Europe in receiving yards, and he was named to the All-European Team on several occasions. As a head coach, he won three straight Division Championships, three straight Conference Championships, two straight National Championships, and two straight European Championships, one European Championship with the Manchester Spartans, and one European Championship with the Great Britain National Team. No British team had ever won a single game in European competition until Smith arrived. After leading the Spartans to the National Championship in order to qualify for the European Championships, Smith led the Spartans to victories over Dublin, Amsterdam, Berlin, and Milan, to win the EuroBowl European Championship.  With the Great Britain National Team, Smith led Great Britain to victories over the Netherlands, Germany, and Finland by a combined score of 99-6 to win the European Nations Championship. These were the first two European Championships in British American football history.\n\nSmith is the only coach in European history to have won both of these European Championships. He won more than 100 games in total as a head coach, while losing only 15. Due to his coaching success, Smith was selected as the National Coach of the Year three straight times, and as the European Coach of the Year twice. In addition, due to his playing and coaching success, Smith was selected to the Great Britain American Football Hall of Fame in 2004, and to the U.S. Minor Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1995.\n\n==Team ownership and management of Chester City==\nSmith went on to become the owner of several professional sports teams, including the European Champion Spartans. In addition, he became the first American owner, chairman, and chief executive in the history of professional English League and European football. Americans have since gone on to own several of the European professional football teams, including English teams Manchester United and Liverpool, but Smith initiated American ownership by becoming the first American to have a vision of the opportunity and to purchase a team. In July 1999, he bought financially struggling English League club [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]], a club that was financially insolvent and being run by an administrator. He declared his belief that the club could reach [[Football League First Division|Division One]] (now the [[EFL Championship]]) within three years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chester/1488938.stm|title=The great Chester soap opera|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|date=13 August 2001}}</ref> The club was in administration when he took over, and close to folding with more than \u00a31 million in debt, and almost all the veteran players already sold to other clubs in order to pay club bills to keep the club from going out of business. He was credited with rescuing Chester from the brink of bankruptcy by supporters at the time, and announced an intention to appoint three supporters to the club board of directors, which he did.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/dec/05/match.sport8|title=Survival spirit from Mr Smith|work=[[The Observer]]|last=Buckley|first=Will|authorlink=Will Buckley (journalist)|date=6 December 1999|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nManager [[Kevin Ratcliffe]] quit the job four games into the season with the team at the bottom of the table, having not scored a goal yet in the league, attempting to claim \u00a3350,000 from a previously unknown contract that the administrator had not even known existed, an alleged contract that supposedly allowed him to resign by his own choice and still be paid this amount that was equal to more than six years of his managerial salary as a golden parachute severance payment. This made the financial situation even more difficult. With the club already in large debt and losing hundreds of thousands of [[Pound sterling|pounds]] every year, and now with an additional large financial severance claim by the ex-manager, then it was not possible to even consider hiring a new manager, and so Smith put together a plan to utilize the assistant coaches that were already in place.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/rocky-ride-for-white-knight-of-chester-742598.html|title=Rocky ride for white knight of Chester|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 February 2011|date=6 October 1999|first=Guy|last=Hodgson}}</ref> Despite by his own admission having little knowledge of football, Smith appointed himself as the leader of a five-man coaching team, in the role of team manager.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/supporters-fear-for-americans-chester-dream-683471.html|title=Supporters fear for American's Chester dream|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 February 2011|date=3 May 2001|first=David|last=Conn|authorlink=David Conn}}</ref> He took over with almost all young players left in the squad, after almost all of the veteran players had been sold during the administration period in order to stay in business. He kept these young players and tried to develop them in order to keep the player wages low, so that the club could not only balance the budget for that season, but also so they could try to pay off the \u00a31 million of debt.\n\nUsing this low budget strategy, along with increasing revenue through moderate Cup runs in the [[FA Cup]] and the [[EFL Cup|Worthington Cup]], and with increased attendance and commercial advertising, Smith was able to get all the club's debts paid off within only six months, which was two years earlier than the administration required, and the club was out of debt for the first time in at least many decades, possibly in history.\n\nIn Smith's four months in charge of team affairs, Chester had some wins against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] and others, but lost 5\u20131 and 4\u20131 to [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] and [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] respectively, and required a replay to overcome non-league minnows [[Whyteleafe F.C.|Whyteleafe]] in the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=663&season_id=138&teamTabs=results#teamTabs=results|title=Chester 1999/00|publisher=Centurycomm|work=[[Soccerbase]]|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> However, they did find success in the Worthington Cup, beating First Division [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] 6\u20135 on aggregate. During the tie, they won 2\u20131 at the [[Deva Stadium]] in a game which saw both [[Marcus Bent]] and [[Martyn Lancaster]] sent off, and then drew 4\u20134 in the return leg at [[Vale Park]]. In the second round, they lost to Premiership club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in both legs, although they were unlucky in the first leg losing 1\u20130, after Villa scored a penalty kick with only six minutes left, following a handball in the box. They also had success in the FA Cup, as they made it to the third round, and only lost to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the final minutes, after the score was tied at 1\u20131 with eleven minutes left. He is the first American to ever own a British team, and until the arrival of [[David Wagner (soccer)|David Wagner]] at [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], the only American to ever be a manager of a club in the English League, and the only American to ever coach in the FA Cup. His methods included saying aloud the [[Lord's Prayer]] during the pre-match team talk, preparing written strategic game plans for each individual match, and appointing captains for the defence, midfield and attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/3653/29/|title=Deva and out|work=[[When Saturday Comes]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|date=July 2000|first=Mark|last=Howell}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2000, with Chester out of debt and all the club debts paid off, and with Chester only one point from safety in the Division, [[Ian Atkins]] was appointed in a dual role as director of football and manager, in a bid to avoid relegation. Despite increasing their player wage bill by a very large amount, going into the final game of the season in May, Chester were 23rd, and faced a three-way battle with Shrewsbury Town and Carlisle United to avoid the drop to the [[National League (English football)|Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-three/1999-2000/table/2000-04-18|title=Table: 02.05.2000|publisher=Statto|work=Tony Brown|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref> With fifteen minutes left in the [[1999\u20132000 in English football|seasons]], Chester was still above both Shrewsbury and Carlisle, but due to Shrewsbury's 2\u20131 win at [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]], Carlisle's 1\u20130 loss to Brighton, and Chester's 1\u20130 home defeat by [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] through a very late goal, Chester were relegated from the league on the final day, by goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/matches/results.sd?date=2000-05-06|title=Results and matches on: Sat, 6 May 2000|publisher=Centurycomm|work=[[Soccerbase]]|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/division-three/1999-2000/table|title=English Division Three 1999-2000: Table|publisher=Statto|work=Tony Brown|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nAtkins left, and fan favourite [[Graham Barrow]] returned as manager. Barrow completely rebuilt the team, and in the 2000\u201301 season, his side managed a respectable ninth place, reached the third round of the FA Cup for the second successive season (in a controversial loss to Blackburn Rovers) and won the [[Conference League Cup]], the first silverware for the club in over 70 years. They were also mentioned as possible promotion contenders for the next season. In spite of this success, Smith appointed [[Gordon Hill (footballer)|Gordon Hill]], an ex-Manchester United and ex-England player who was a personal friend, to become the new manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/shambles-at-chester-9196380.html|title=Shambles at Chester|first=Rupert|last=Metcalf|work=[[The Independent]]|date=23 August 2001|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nChester made a dreadful start to the [[2001\u201302 in English football|2001\u201302 season]], winning only one of their first twelve matches. Smith finally sold his interest in the club to [[Stephen Vaughan Sr.|Stephen Vaughan]] and left at the start of October 2001, with the club completely out of debt other than what it owed him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chester/1621259.stm|title=Chester back on track|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 February 2011|date=27 October 2001}}</ref> Smith returned to his homeland, to work as a teacher. He also coached American football coach and baseball at a high school in [[North Carolina]], and then later, as a Pro American football head coach. In 2003, a British court ordered Chester City to repay \u00a3300,000 in unpaid loans to Smith and his family. However, Smith still wanted to help the club, and so he accepted a settlement of far less than half of that amount.\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith is married to Sara; their daughter Shannon is also a Furman University alumnus, specialising in track and field.<ref name=\"shannon\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Chester City F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Terry}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Furman University alumni]]\n[[Category:Furman Paladins football players]]\n[[Category:Furman Paladins baseball players]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:Coaches of American football]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. managers]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c5c:6c00:2c77:5dc2:51e5:8216:c095", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Added info)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terry_Smith_(football)"}
{"title_page": "University of the Sacred Heart Gulu", "text_new": "{{short description|Private university in Uganda}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name=         University of the Sacred Heart Gulu (USHG)\n|image         = \n|motto=        \n|mottoeng=     Health of Mind, Heart and Body\n|established=  2016\n|type=   [[Private university|Private]]\n|vice_chancellor = \n|city         =      [[Gulu]]\n|country      =      [[Uganda]]\n|students     =      120+ (2017)\n|academic_staff        =      40+ (2017)      \n|campus       =     Urban\n|website      =      [http://www.ush.ac.ug/ Homepage]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Sacred Heart Gulu''' (USHG) is a private university affiliated with the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Gulu]] in [[Uganda]]. It caters to students primarily from Uganda and neighboring [[South Sudan]] and the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref name=\"One\">{{cite web| url=https://kjacksondgmailcom.wordpress.com/2016/12/05/university-of-sacred-heart-gulu-to-open-next-year-with-two-bachelor-degree-programs/ |title=University of Sacred Heart Gulu to open next year with two bachelor degree programs |accessdate=7 December 2017 | date=16 November 2016 | first=Jackson |last=Kitara |publisher=Kitara Jackson Wordpress |location=Gulu}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe university's main campus is located in the western part of the city of Gulu, adjacent to the offices and studios of ''Radio Pacis Gulu'', approximately {{convert|5|km|0}}, by road, west of the city centre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Distance between Post Office, Gulu, Uganda and Radio Pacis Gulu, Gulu, Uganda |accessdate=7 December 2017| date=7 December 2017 | url=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Post%20Office%2C%20Gulu%2C%20Uganda&toplace=Radio%20Pacis%20Gulu%2C%20Gulu%2C%20Uganda&dt1=ChIJ6cU_2TemcRcRxYC_J3-yiyY&dt2=ChIJm7vXBQqmcRcRqhi1t9AuGvw | publisher=Globefeed.com (GFC)| author=GFC}}</ref> The geographical coordinates of the university  campus are: 2\u00b046'15.0\"N, 32\u00b016'00.0\"E (Latitude:2.770833; Longitude:32.266667).<ref>{{google maps|title=Location of the Main Campus of the University of the Sacred Heart Gulu |accessdate=7 December 2017| url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/2%C2%B046'15.0%22N+32%C2%B016'00.0%22E/@2.7737112,32.2550525,5125m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d2.7708333!4d32.2666667 }}</ref> In 2016, the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Gulu donated land, measuring {{convert|51|acre|0}} for expansion of the university.<ref name=\"One\"/>\n\n==Overview==\nThe university was established to bridge the gap between the services offered by [[Gulu University]], the public institution of higher learning, and the need for higher education among the population, both locally and regionally. Courses in [[Information and communications technology]] and [[Counseling psychology]] were selected to start with, due to the high levels of suicide, alcohol and drug abuse, as a result of twenty years of the [[Lord's Resistance Army]] insurgency.<ref name=\"One\"/>\n\nCourses in the health science arena are planned for the future, in conjunction with [[St. Mary's Hospital Lacor]], [[St. Joseph's Hospital Kitgum]] and [[Dr. Ambrosoli Memorial Hospital]], in [[Agago District]]. Immediate challenges include the lack of adequate student accommodation near the current lecture rooms.<ref name=\"One\"/>\n\n==Academics==\nThe university has one faculty at the beginning; the Faculty of [[Arts]] and [[Social Sciences]]. The faculty has two departments (a) Department of [[Counselling]] and (b) Department of [[Information and Communications Technology]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://ush.ac.ug/faculty/ | title=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu: Faculty |publisher=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu (USHG) | author=USHG |location=Gulu |accessdate=7 December 2017 |\ndate=7 December 2017}}</ref> Two degrees are on offer, the [[Counselling psychology|Bachelor of Counselling Psychology]] and the [[Information system|Bachelor of Information Systems]].<ref>{{cite web| location=Gulu | url=http://ush.ac.ug/academic-program/ | title=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu: Academic Programs |publisher=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu (USHG) | author=USHG  |accessdate=7 December 2017 |date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Uganda Martyrs University]]\n*[[Lacor Hospital]]\n*[[List of universities in Uganda]]\n*[[Education in Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ush.ac.ug/ Website of the University of Sacred Heart Gulu]\n* [https://www.newvision.co.ug/digital_assets/e2bf994a-5305-4a7c-b385-2b4edca7ac50/64-University-of-Sacred-Heart_Final.pdf Call for Applications for the 2017/2018 Academic Year Intake]\n\n{{Universities in Uganda}}\n{{Gulu District}}\n{{coord|02|46|15|N|32|06|00|E|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Uganda]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Africa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Association of African Universities]]\n[[Category:Gulu]]\n[[Category:Gulu District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Private university in Uganda}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name=         University of the Sacred Heart Gulu (USHG)\n|image         = \n|motto=        \n|mottoeng=     Health of Mind, Heart and Body\n|established=  2016\n|type=   [[Private university|Private]]\n|vice_chancellor = \n|city         =      [[Gulu]]\n|country      =      [[Uganda]]\n|students     =      120+ (2017)\n|academic_staff        =      40+ (2017)      \n|campus       =     Urban\n|website      =      [http://www.ush.ac.ug/ Homepage]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Sacred Heart Gulu''' (USHG) is a private university affiliated with the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Gulu]] in [[Uganda]]. It caters to students primarily from Uganda and neighboring [[South Sudan]] and the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref name=\"One\">{{cite web| url=https://kjacksondgmailcom.wordpress.com/2016/12/05/university-of-sacred-heart-gulu-to-open-next-year-with-two-bachelor-degree-programs/ |title=University of Sacred Heart Gulu to open next year with two bachelor degree programs |accessdate=7 December 2017 | date=16 November 2016 | first=Jackson |last=Kitara |publisher=Kitara Jackson Wordpress |location=Gulu}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe university's main campus is located in the western part of the city of Gulu, adjacent to the offices and studios of ''Radio Pacis Gulu'', approximately {{convert|5|km|0}}, by road, west of the city centre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Distance between Post Office, Gulu, Uganda and Radio Pacis Gulu, Gulu, Uganda |accessdate=7 December 2017| date=7 December 2017 | url=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Post%20Office%2C%20Gulu%2C%20Uganda&toplace=Radio%20Pacis%20Gulu%2C%20Gulu%2C%20Uganda&dt1=ChIJ6cU_2TemcRcRxYC_J3-yiyY&dt2=ChIJm7vXBQqmcRcRqhi1t9AuGvw | publisher=Globefeed.com (GFC)| author=GFC}}</ref> The geographical coordinates of the university  campus are: 2\u00b046'15.0\"N, 32\u00b016'00.0\"E (Latitude:2.770833; Longitude:32.266667).<ref>{{google maps|title=Location of the Main Campus of the University of the Sacred Heart Gulu |accessdate=7 December 2017| url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/2%C2%B046'15.0%22N+32%C2%B016'00.0%22E/@2.7737112,32.2550525,5125m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d2.7708333!4d32.2666667 }}</ref> In 2016, the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Gulu donated land, measuring {{convert|51|acre|0}} for expansion of the university.<ref name=\"One\"/>\n\n==Overview==\nThe university was established to bridge the gap between the services offered by [[Gulu University]], the public institution of higher learning, and the need for higher education among the population, both locally and regionally. Courses in [[Information and communications technology]] and [[Counseling psychology]] were selected to start with, due to the high levels of suicide, alcohol and drug abuse, as a result of twenty years of the [[Lord's Resistance Army]] insurgency.<ref name=\"One\"/> \n\nCourses in the health science arena are planned for the future, in conjunction with [[St. Mary's Hospital Lacor]], [[St. Joseph's Hospital Kitgum]] and [[Dr. Ambrosoli Memorial Hospital]], in [[Agago District]]. Immediate challenges include the lack of adequate student accommodation near the current lecture rooms.<ref name=\"One\"/>\n\n==Academics==\nThe university has one faculty at the beginning; the Faculty of [[Arts]] and [[Social Sciences]]. The faculty has two departments (a) Department of [[Counselling]] and (b) Department of [[Information and Communications Technology]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://ush.ac.ug/faculty/ | title=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu: Faculty |publisher=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu (USHG) | author=USHG |location=Gulu |accessdate=7 December 2017 |\ndate=7 December 2017}}</ref> Two degrees are on offer, the [[Counselling psychology|Bachelor of Counselling Psychology]] and the [[Information system|Bachelor of Information Systems]].<ref>{{cite web| location=Gulu | url=http://ush.ac.ug/academic-program/ | title=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu: Academic Programs |publisher=University of the Sacred Heart Gulu (USHG) | author=USHG  |accessdate=7 December 2017 |date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Uganda Martyrs University]]\n*[[Lacor Hospital]]\n*[[List of universities in Uganda]]\n*[[Education in Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ush.ac.ug/ Website of the University of Sacred Heart Gulu]\n* [https://www.newvision.co.ug/digital_assets/e2bf994a-5305-4a7c-b385-2b4edca7ac50/64-University-of-Sacred-Heart_Final.pdf Call for Applications for the 2017/2018 Academic Year Intake]\n\n{{Universities in Uganda}}\n{{Gulu District}}\n{{coord|02|46|15|N|32|06|00|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Uganda]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Africa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Association of African Universities]]\n[[Category:Gulu]]\n[[Category:Gulu District]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Sacred_Heart_Gulu"}
{"title_page": "University of the Republic (Uruguay)", "text_new": "{{redirect|University of the Republic|the university in San Marino|University of the Republic of San Marino}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = University of the Republic\n|native_name = Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica\n|image = 04 - Udelar - isologotipo versi\u00f3n preferencial - positiva - rgb web.svg\n|motto = \n|mottoeng = \n|established = 18 July 1849\n|type = [[Public university|Public]]\n|calendar = \n|endowment = \n|rector = [[Rodrigo Arim]]\n|undergrad = 137,757 (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.presidencia.gub.uy/comunicacion/comunicacionnoticias/educacion-estudiantes-universitarios-crecimiento-promedio|title=Cantidad de estudiantes de la Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica aument\u00f3 un 3,5 % al a\u00f1o de 2012 a 2018|accessdate=12 December 2019|archive-url=https://www.presidencia.gub.uy/comunicacion/comunicacionnoticias/educacion-estudiantes-universitarios-crecimiento-promedio|archive-date=2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|postgrad = 6,351 (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universidad.edu.uy/renderResource/index/resourceId/30152/siteId/1|title=VII Censo de Estudiantes Universitarios de Grado|accessdate=12 December 2019|archive-url=http://www.universidad.edu.uy/renderResource/index/resourceId/30152/siteId/1|archive-date=2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|city = {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Montevideo]]\n|country = [[Uruguay]]\n|campus = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|website= [http://www.universidad.edu.uy/ www.universidad.edu.uy]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Republic''' ({{lang-es|Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica}}, sometimes ''UdelaR'') is [[Uruguay]]'s oldest public [[university]]. It is by far the country's largest university, as well as the second largest public university in [[South America]] and the [[List of largest universities and university networks by enrollment|world's 57th largest by enrollment]], with a [[student]] body of 137,757 undergraduate students in 2018 and 6,351 postgraduate students in 2012. It was founded on 18 July 1849 in [[Montevideo]], where most of its buildings and facilities are still located. Its current [[Rector (academia)|rector]] is [[Rodrigo Arim]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe process of founding the country's public university began on 11 June 1833, when a law proposed by then-Senator D\u00e1maso Antonio Larra\u00f1aga was passed. It called for the creation of nine academic departments; the President of the Republic would pass a decree formally creating the departments once the majority of them were in operation. In 1836 the House of General Studies was formed, housing the departments of Latin, philosophy, mathematics, theology and jurisprudence.\n\nOn 27 May 1838, [[Manuel Oribe]] passed a decree through which created the Greater University of the Republic.  That decree had few practical effects, given the institutional instability of the Oriental Republic of the Uruguay at that time.\n\n==Ranking==\nIn 2011, according to [[University Ranking by Academic Performance (URAP)]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.urapcenter.org/2011|title=URAP - University Ranking by Academic Performance}}</ref> it is the best university in Uruguay and 858th best university in the world.\n\nIn 2015, according to [[QS World University Rankings]], it ranks #701-750 worldwide and #38 in Latin America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universidad-de-la-rep%C3%BAblica-udelar|title=UdelaR rankings |publisher=TopUniversities|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, according to QS World University Rankings, it ranks #801-1000 Worldwide, and remains in the #38 Latin American rankings.<ref>{{cite web |title=Universidad de la Republica (UdelaR) |url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universidad-de-la-republica-udelar#wurs |website=Top Universities |accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Schools==\n[[File:2016 interior facultad de Arquitectura Montevideo.jpg|thumb|School of Architecture, Design, and Urbanism.]]\n* School of [[Agronomy]]\n* School of [[Architecture]], [[Design]], and [[Urbanism]]\n* School of [[Art]]s\n* School of [[Chemistry]]\n* School of [[economics|Economic Science]] and [[Administration (business)|Administration]]\n* School of [[Engineering]]\n* School of [[Humanities]] and [[Pedagogy|Education Science]]\n* University of the Republic [[Law School]]\n* School of [[Medicine]]\n* School of [[Nursing]]\n* School of [[Odontology]]\n* School of [[Psychology]]\n* School of [[Science]]\n* School of [[Social Science]]\n* School of [[Veterinary Medicine]]\n\n===Law School===\n[[File:2016 Facultad de Derecho de la Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica, Avenida 18 de Julio.jpg|thumb|University of the Republic Law School.]]\nThe University of the Republic [[Law School]] was established on June 18, 1838 as the Academy of Jurisprudence, making it the oldest law school in the nation. It became a branch of the University of the Republic on July 18, 1849. It is the only branch of the university that hasn't moved from the main building downtown [[Montevideo]]. It was the only law school in Uruguay until the arrival of the [[Catholic University]] in 1984.\n\nMany Presidents of Uruguay, senators, representatives and other public authorities with a law degree have graduated from this law school. Notable professors include Jorge Gamarra, Alejandro Abal, Alberto Perez Perez, Dora Bagdassarian, Helios Sarthou, Carlos Delpiazzo, [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez (Uruguayan politician)|Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez]], and Daniel Ferrere.\n\nThe [[Dean (education)|Dean]] is Dr. Cristina Mangarelli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universidad.edu.uy/prensa/renderItem/itemId/42700|title=Cristina Mangarelli es la nueva decana de Derecho|publisher=Portal Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> Its main executive organ is the Law School Council, integrated by the dean and members in representation of students, former students and professors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fder.edu.uy/cogobierno|title=Cogobierno|publisher=Facultad de Derecho, Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Schools and Institutes==\n* Licentiateship in [[Communication Studies]]\n* School of Administration\n* School of [[Library Science]] and Related Sciences\n* School of Medical Technology\n* School of [[Nutrition]] and Dietetics\n* School of [[Obstetrics]]\n* School of Odontological Technology\n\n==Other dependencies==\nThe university has its own hospital in [[Montevideo, Uruguay|Montevideo]], [[Hospital de Cl\u00ednicas, Montevideo|Hospital de Cl\u00ednicas \u201cDr. Manuel Quintela\u201d]].\n\n==Other cities==\nIn an effort to decentralize higher education, the University has opened schools in cities other than Montevideo. Its ''Regional Norte'' in [[Salto, Uruguay|Salto]] offers [[Academic degree|degree]]s in Architecture, Law and Nursing. Fragments of other degrees, which can be completed in Montevideo, are also offered there. At the ''Casa Universitaria'' in [[Rivera]], the Faculty of Sciences offers the Technicature in Management of Environmental Resources, which has a duration of two and a half years.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Uruguay}}\n* [[List of universities in Uruguay]]\n* [[Education in Uruguay]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica}}\n*[http://www.universidad.edu.uy/ Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica]\n*[http://www.fagro.edu.uy Facultad de Agronom\u00eda (Faculty of Agronomy)]\n*[http://www.farq.edu.uy Facultad de Arquitectura (Faculty of Architecture)]\n*[http://www.fcien.edu.uy Facultad de Ciencias (Faculty of Sciences)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010202132200/http://www.ccee.edu.uy/ Facultad de Ciencias Econ\u00f3micas y de Administraci\u00f3n (Faculty of Economic Science and Administration]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120623001628/http://www.fcs.edu.uy/ Facultad de Ciencias Sociales (Faculty of Social Science)]\n*[http://www.fder.edu.uy Facultad de Derecho (Faculty of Law)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20001011121936/http://www.inde.edu.uy/ Facultad de Enfermer\u00eda (Faculty of Nursing)]\n*[http://www.fhuce.edu.uy Facultad de Humanidades y Ciencias de la Educaci\u00f3n (Faculty of Humanities and Education Science)]\n*[http://www.fing.edu.uy Facultad de Ingenier\u00eda (Faculty of Engineering)]\n*[http://www.fmed.edu.uy Facultad de Medicina (Faculty of Medicine)]\n*[http://www.odon.edu.uy Facultad de Odontolog\u00eda (Faculty of Odontology)]\n*[http://www.psico.edu.uy Facultad de Psicolog\u00eda (Faculty of Psychology)]\n*[http://fq.edu.uy Facultad de Qu\u00edmica (Faculty of Chemistry)]\n*[http://www.fvet.edu.uy Facultad de Ciencias Veterinarias (Faculty of Veterinary Medicine)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20030414030932/http://www.ccee.edu.uy/eda/ Escuela de Administraci\u00f3n (School of Administration)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060924164702/http://www.odon.edu.uy/eto/ Escuela de Tecnolog\u00eda Odontol\u00f3gica (School of Odontological Technology)]\n*[http://www.eubca.edu.uy Escuela Universitaria de Bibliotecolog\u00eda y Ciencias Afines (School of Library Science and Related Sciences)]\n*[http://www.eumus.edu.uy Escuela Universitaria de M\u00fasica (School of Music)]\n*[http://www.liccom.edu.uy Licenciatura en Ciencias de la Comunicaci\u00f3n (Licentiateship in Communication Studies)]\n*[http://www.enba.edu.uy Instituto Escuela Nacional de Bellas Artes (National School of Fine Arts)]\n\n{{coord|34.90262|S|56.17653|W|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Of The Republic, Uruguay}}\n[[Category:University of the Republic (Uruguay)| ]]\n[[Category:Universities in Uruguay|Republica]]\n[[Category:Forestry education]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1849]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Uruguay]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Uruguay]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|University of the Republic|the university in San Marino|University of the Republic of San Marino}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = University of the Republic\n|native_name = Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica\n|image = 04 - Udelar - isologotipo versi\u00f3n preferencial - positiva - rgb web.svg\n|motto = \n|mottoeng = \n|established = 18 July 1849\n|type = [[Public university|Public]]\n|calendar = \n|endowment = \n|rector = [[Rodrigo Arim]]\n|undergrad = 137,757 (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.presidencia.gub.uy/comunicacion/comunicacionnoticias/educacion-estudiantes-universitarios-crecimiento-promedio|title=Cantidad de estudiantes de la Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica aument\u00f3 un 3,5 % al a\u00f1o de 2012 a 2018|accessdate=12 December 2019|archive-url=https://www.presidencia.gub.uy/comunicacion/comunicacionnoticias/educacion-estudiantes-universitarios-crecimiento-promedio|archive-date=2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|postgrad = 6,351 (2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universidad.edu.uy/renderResource/index/resourceId/30152/siteId/1|title=VII Censo de Estudiantes Universitarios de Grado|accessdate=12 December 2019|archive-url=http://www.universidad.edu.uy/renderResource/index/resourceId/30152/siteId/1|archive-date=2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|city = {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Montevideo]]\n|country = [[Uruguay]]\n|campus = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|website= [http://www.universidad.edu.uy/ www.universidad.edu.uy]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Republic''' ({{lang-es|Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica}}, sometimes ''UdelaR'') is [[Uruguay]]'s oldest public [[university]]. It is by far the country's largest university, as well as the second largest public university in [[South America]] and the [[List of largest universities and university networks by enrollment|world's 57th largest by enrollment]], with a [[student]] body of 137,757 undergraduate students in 2018 and 6,351 postgraduate students in 2012. It was founded on 18 July 1849 in [[Montevideo]], where most of its buildings and facilities are still located. Its current [[Rector (academia)|rector]] is [[Rodrigo Arim]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe process of founding the country's public university began on 11 June 1833, when a law proposed by then-Senator D\u00e1maso Antonio Larra\u00f1aga was passed. It called for the creation of nine academic departments; the President of the Republic would pass a decree formally creating the departments once the majority of them were in operation. In 1836 the House of General Studies was formed, housing the departments of Latin, philosophy, mathematics, theology and jurisprudence.\n\nOn 27 May 1838, [[Manuel Oribe]] passed a decree through which created the Greater University of the Republic.  That decree had few practical effects, given the institutional instability of the Oriental Republic of the Uruguay at that time.\n\n==Ranking==\nIn 2011, according to [[University Ranking by Academic Performance (URAP)]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.urapcenter.org/2011|title=URAP - University Ranking by Academic Performance}}</ref> it is the best university in Uruguay and 858th best university in the world.\n\nIn 2015, according to [[QS World University Rankings]], it ranks #701-750 worldwide and #38 in Latin America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universidad-de-la-rep%C3%BAblica-udelar|title=UdelaR rankings |publisher=TopUniversities|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, according to QS World University Rankings, it ranks #801-1000 Worldwide, and remains in the #38 Latin American rankings.<ref>{{cite web |title=Universidad de la Republica (UdelaR) |url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universidad-de-la-republica-udelar#wurs |website=Top Universities |accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Schools==\n[[File:2016 interior facultad de Arquitectura Montevideo.jpg|thumb|School of Architecture, Design, and Urbanism.]]\n* School of [[Agronomy]]\n* School of [[Architecture]], [[Design]], and [[Urbanism]]\n* School of [[Art]]s\n* School of [[Chemistry]]\n* School of [[economics|Economic Science]] and [[Administration (business)|Administration]]\n* School of [[Engineering]]\n* School of [[Humanities]] and [[Pedagogy|Education Science]]\n* University of the Republic [[Law School]]\n* School of [[Medicine]]\n* School of [[Nursing]]\n* School of [[Odontology]]\n* School of [[Psychology]]\n* School of [[Science]]\n* School of [[Social Science]]\n* School of [[Veterinary Medicine]]\n\n===Law School===\n[[File:2016 Facultad de Derecho de la Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica, Avenida 18 de Julio.jpg|thumb|University of the Republic Law School.]]\nThe University of the Republic [[Law School]] was established on June 18, 1838 as the Academy of Jurisprudence, making it the oldest law school in the nation. It became a branch of the University of the Republic on July 18, 1849. It is the only branch of the university that hasn't moved from the main building downtown [[Montevideo]]. It was the only law school in Uruguay until the arrival of the [[Catholic University]] in 1984.\n\nMany Presidents of Uruguay, senators, representatives and other public authorities with a law degree have graduated from this law school. Notable professors include Jorge Gamarra, Alejandro Abal, Alberto Perez Perez, Dora Bagdassarian, Helios Sarthou, Carlos Delpiazzo, [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez (Uruguayan politician)|Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez]], and Daniel Ferrere.\n\nThe [[Dean (education)|Dean]] is Dr. Cristina Mangarelli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.universidad.edu.uy/prensa/renderItem/itemId/42700|title=Cristina Mangarelli es la nueva decana de Derecho|publisher=Portal Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> Its main executive organ is the Law School Council, integrated by the dean and members in representation of students, former students and professors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fder.edu.uy/cogobierno|title=Cogobierno|publisher=Facultad de Derecho, Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Schools and Institutes==\n* Licentiateship in [[Communication Studies]]\n* School of Administration\n* School of [[Library Science]] and Related Sciences\n* School of Medical Technology\n* School of [[Nutrition]] and Dietetics\n* School of [[Obstetrics]]\n* School of Odontological Technology\n\n==Other dependencies==\nThe university has its own hospital in [[Montevideo, Uruguay|Montevideo]], [[Hospital de Cl\u00ednicas, Montevideo|Hospital de Cl\u00ednicas \u201cDr. Manuel Quintela\u201d]].\n\n==Other cities==\nIn an effort to decentralize higher education, the University has opened schools in cities other than Montevideo. Its ''Regional Norte'' in [[Salto, Uruguay|Salto]] offers [[Academic degree|degree]]s in Architecture, Law and Nursing. Fragments of other degrees, which can be completed in Montevideo, are also offered there. At the ''Casa Universitaria'' in [[Rivera]], the Faculty of Sciences offers the Technicature in Management of Environmental Resources, which has a duration of two and a half years.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Uruguay}}\n* [[List of universities in Uruguay]]\n* [[Education in Uruguay]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica}}\n*[http://www.universidad.edu.uy/ Universidad de la Rep\u00fablica]\n*[http://www.fagro.edu.uy Facultad de Agronom\u00eda (Faculty of Agronomy)]\n*[http://www.farq.edu.uy Facultad de Arquitectura (Faculty of Architecture)]\n*[http://www.fcien.edu.uy Facultad de Ciencias (Faculty of Sciences)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010202132200/http://www.ccee.edu.uy/ Facultad de Ciencias Econ\u00f3micas y de Administraci\u00f3n (Faculty of Economic Science and Administration]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120623001628/http://www.fcs.edu.uy/ Facultad de Ciencias Sociales (Faculty of Social Science)]\n*[http://www.fder.edu.uy Facultad de Derecho (Faculty of Law)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20001011121936/http://www.inde.edu.uy/ Facultad de Enfermer\u00eda (Faculty of Nursing)]\n*[http://www.fhuce.edu.uy Facultad de Humanidades y Ciencias de la Educaci\u00f3n (Faculty of Humanities and Education Science)]\n*[http://www.fing.edu.uy Facultad de Ingenier\u00eda (Faculty of Engineering)]\n*[http://www.fmed.edu.uy Facultad de Medicina (Faculty of Medicine)]\n*[http://www.odon.edu.uy Facultad de Odontolog\u00eda (Faculty of Odontology)]\n*[http://www.psico.edu.uy Facultad de Psicolog\u00eda (Faculty of Psychology)]\n*[http://fq.edu.uy Facultad de Qu\u00edmica (Faculty of Chemistry)]\n*[http://www.fvet.edu.uy Facultad de Ciencias Veterinarias (Faculty of Veterinary Medicine)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20030414030932/http://www.ccee.edu.uy/eda/ Escuela de Administraci\u00f3n (School of Administration)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060924164702/http://www.odon.edu.uy/eto/ Escuela de Tecnolog\u00eda Odontol\u00f3gica (School of Odontological Technology)]\n*[http://www.eubca.edu.uy Escuela Universitaria de Bibliotecolog\u00eda y Ciencias Afines (School of Library Science and Related Sciences)]\n*[http://www.eumus.edu.uy Escuela Universitaria de M\u00fasica (School of Music)]\n*[http://www.liccom.edu.uy Licenciatura en Ciencias de la Comunicaci\u00f3n (Licentiateship in Communication Studies)]\n*[http://www.enba.edu.uy Instituto Escuela Nacional de Bellas Artes (National School of Fine Arts)]\n\n{{coord|34.90262|S|56.17653|W|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Of The Republic, Uruguay}}\n[[Category:University of the Republic (Uruguay)| ]]\n[[Category:Universities in Uruguay|Republica]]\n[[Category:Forestry education]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1849]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Uruguay]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Uruguay]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Republic_(Uruguay)"}
