{"title_page": "University of the Humanities", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=October 2012}}\n\n'''University of the Humanities'''  (also known as '''Humanities University''')  is a private university in [[Ulaanbaatar]], [[Mongolia]], offering undergraduate and graduate programs in fields including foreign languages, translation, education, journalism, computer science, economics business.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.humanities.mn/en/Program_offerings.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-07-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703182651/http://www.humanities.mn/en/Program_offerings.aspx |archive-date=2013-07-03 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe Mongolian name: \u0425\u04af\u043c\u04af\u04af\u043d\u043b\u044d\u0433\u0438\u0439\u043d \u0443\u0445\u0430\u0430\u043d\u044b \u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0443\u0443\u043b\u044c\n\nThe university is accredited by the Mongolian National Council for Education Accreditation <ref>https://www.4icu.org/reviews/12057.htm</ref>\n\nIn 2014 it ranked fifteenth in Mongolia and 18367th in the world on the  [[Webometrics Ranking of World Universities]].<ref>http://www.webometrics.info/en/Asia/Mongolia2</ref>  It was ranked 7454th in the world in web rankings according to another source.<ref>https://www.4icu.org/reviews/12057.htm</ref>\n\nAddress: Sukhhbaatar Square \u2013 20/4, Baga Toiruu, Sukhbaatar District, P.O. Box \u2013 210646/53.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.humanities.mn/en/default.aspx}} in English\n\n{{coord|47.9221|106.9191|type:edu_region:MN|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Mongolia]]\n\n\n{{Mongolia-school-stub}}\n{{Asia-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=October 2012}}\n\n'''University of the Humanities'''  (also known as '''Humanities University''')  is a private university in [[Ulaanbaatar]], [[Mongolia]], offering undergraduate and graduate programs in fields including foreign languages, translation, education, journalism, computer science, economics business.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.humanities.mn/en/Program_offerings.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-07-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703182651/http://www.humanities.mn/en/Program_offerings.aspx |archive-date=2013-07-03 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe Mongolian name: \u0425\u04af\u043c\u04af\u04af\u043d\u043b\u044d\u0433\u0438\u0439\u043d \u0443\u0445\u0430\u0430\u043d\u044b \u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0443\u0443\u043b\u044c\n\nThe university is accredited by the Mongolian National Council for Education Accreditation <ref>https://www.4icu.org/reviews/12057.htm</ref>\n\nIn 2014 it ranked fifteenth in Mongolia and 18367th in the world on the  [[Webometrics Ranking of World Universities]].<ref>http://www.webometrics.info/en/Asia/Mongolia2</ref>  It was ranked 7454th in the world in web rankings according to another source.<ref>https://www.4icu.org/reviews/12057.htm</ref>\n\nAddress: Sukhhbaatar Square \u2013 20/4, Baga Toiruu, Sukhbaatar District, P.O. Box \u2013 210646/53.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.humanities.mn/en/default.aspx}} in English\n\n{{coord|47.9221|106.9191|type:edu_region:MN|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Mongolia]]\n\n{{Mongolia-school-stub}}\n{{Asia-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Humanities"}
{"title_page": "Chris McCandless", "text_new": "{{short description|American hiker and explorer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Chris McCandless\n| image              = Chris McCandless.png\n| image_size         =\n| other_names        = Alexander Supertramp\n| caption            = Self-portrait of McCandless on the [[Stampede Trail]], found undeveloped in his camera after his death\n| birth_name         = Christopher Johnson McCandless\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1968|2|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[El Segundo, California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date         = [[circa|c.]] August 1992 (aged 24)<!-- Please do not enter an exact date as the exact date is not known and never will be -->\n| death_place        = [[Stampede Trail]], [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Starvation]], possibly brought on by [[poisoning]]<ref>Krakauer, J., et al. (2015). \"Presence of l-canavanine in Hedysarum alpinum seeds and its potential role in the death of Chris McCandless.\" Wilderness & Environmental Medicine. doi:10.1016/j.wem.2014.08.014</ref> <!--The probable cause of death, according to the coroner\u2019s report, was starvation. However, the possibility of poisoning is not out of the question. -->\n| body_discovered    = September 6, 1992\n| education          = [[Wilbert Tucker Woodson High School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Emory University]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Johnson McCandless''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|k|\u00e6|n|d|l|\u1d7b|s}}; February 12, 1968<ref>{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=Into the Wild |publisher=Anchor Books |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |page=53 |chapter=6}}</ref> \u2013 c. August<!-- Please do not enter an exact date as the exact date is not known and never will be --> 1992), also known by the pseudonym '''Alexander Supertramp''' ('''Alex'''), was an American [[hooplehead]]<!--please explain any changes to this word on the article's talk page--> who sought an increasingly itinerant lifestyle as he grew up. McCandless is the subject of ''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]'', a nonfiction book by [[Jon Krakauer]] that was later made into [[Into the Wild (film)|a full-length feature film]].\n\nAfter graduating from college in 1990, McCandless traveled across North America and eventually hitchhiked to [[Alaska]] in April 1992. There, he set out along an old mining road known as the [[Stampede Trail]] with minimal supplies, hoping to [[Simple living|live simply]] off the land. On the eastern bank of the Sushana River, McCandless found an abandoned bus, [[Stampede_Trail#Bus_142|Fairbanks Bus 142]], which he used as a makeshift shelter until his death. In September, his [[human decomposition|decomposing]] body, weighing only 67 pounds (30 kilograms), was found by a hunter inside the bus. McCandless's cause of death was officially ruled to be [[starvation]],<ref name=\"Terra Incognita films\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> although the exact cause remains the subject of some debate.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Krakauer2013\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn January 1993, Jon Krakauer published McCandless' story in that month's issue of ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]'' magazine. He had been assigned the story and had written it under a tight deadline.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krakauer, Jon |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/how-chris-mccandless-died |title=How Chris McCandless Died |date=September 12, 2013 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref> Inspired by the details of McCandless' story, he wrote and published the more extensive biographical book ''Into the Wild'' in 1996. The book was subsequently adapted into a 2007 [[Into the Wild (film)|film]] directed by [[Sean Penn]], with [[Emile Hirsch]] portraying McCandless. That same year, McCandless' story also became the subject of [[Ron Lamothe]]'s documentary ''[[The Call of the Wild (2007 film)|The Call of the Wild]]'' (2007).\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Johnson McCandless was born in [[El Segundo, California|El Segundo]], [[California]]. He was the first child of Wilhelmina \"Billie\" McCandless (n\u00e9e Johnson) and Walter \"Walt\" McCandless. Afterwards the couple had one more child, a daughter named Carine. McCandless also had six half-siblings from Walt's first marriage, who lived with their mother in California. Author [[Jon Krakauer]] later speculated that Walt's transition between these two marriages affected McCandless deeply and shaped his [[worldview]].<ref name=\"Krakauer 1997\">{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=[[Into the Wild (book)|Into The Wild]] |publisher=Anchor |year=1997 |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |location=[[New York City]] |author-link=Jon Krakauer}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, the family relocated to [[Washington, D.C.]], and settled in suburban [[Annandale, Virginia|Annandale]], [[Virginia]], when McCandless' father was hired as an antenna specialist for the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA); McCandless' mother worked as a secretary at [[Hughes Aircraft]]. The couple went on to establish a successful consultancy business out of their home, specializing in Walt's area of expertise.\n\nMcCandless graduated from [[Wilbert Tucker Woodson High School|W.T. Woodson High School]] in [[Fairfax, Virginia]], in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Williams |first=Preston |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/23/AR2007102302042.html |title=Remembering an Athlete Who Never Returned From the Wild |date=October 25, 2007 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> He excelled academically, although a number of teachers and fellow students observed that he \"marched to the beat of a different drummer.\" McCandless also served as captain of the [[cross country running|cross-country]] team, where he would urge teammates to treat running as a spiritual exercise in which they were \"running against the forces of darkness&nbsp;... all the evil in the world, all the hatred.\"<ref name=\"Krakauer\">{{cite magazine| first=Jon|last=Krakauer|authorlink=Jon Krakauer| url = http://hudson.k12.oh.us/cms/lib08/OH01914911/Centricity/Domain/1167/Krakauer%20article%20McCandless.pdf\n | title = Death of an Innocent: How Christopher McCandless Lost His Way in the Wilds.\n | magazine = [[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]\n | date = January 1993\n | accessdate = 2008-04-04\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1986, McCandless traveled to [[Southern California]] and reconnected with distant relatives and friends. It was during this journey he learned that his father had not yet divorced his first wife when McCandless and his sister Carine were born, and had apparently maintained somewhat of a [[double life]] before the move to Virginia. It is speculated that this discovery had a profound impact on the younger McCandless.<ref name=\"Krakauer 1997 166\">{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=[[Into the Wild (book)|Into The Wild]] |publisher=Anchor |year=1997 |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |location=[[New York City]] |page=166 |author-link=Jon Krakauer}}</ref>\n\nMcCandless graduated from [[Emory University]] in May 1990, with a [[bachelor's degree]] in the double majors of [[history]] and [[anthropology]].<ref name=\"Krakauer\" /> After graduating, he donated his college savings of $24,000 to [[OXFAM]] and adopted a [[vagabond]] lifestyle, working when necessary as a restaurant food preparer and farm hand.<ref>{{Cite book |last=McCandless |first=Carine |title=The Wild Truth |date=2014 |publisher=Harper One |isbn=978-0-06-232514-3 |location=New York City}}</ref> An avid [[outdoorsman]], McCandless completed several lengthy wilderness hiking trips and paddled a canoe down a portion of the [[Colorado River]] before hitchhiking to [[Alaska]] in April 1992.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |url=https://archive.org/details/intowild00krak_1/page/5 |title=Into the Wild |date=1996 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-679-42850-X |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/intowild00krak_1/page/5 5, 32\u201336]}}</ref>\n\n==Travels==\nBy the end of summer in 1990, McCandless had driven his [[Datsun]] through California, [[Arizona]], and [[South Dakota]], where he worked at a [[grain elevator]] in [[Carthage, South Dakota|Carthage]]. A [[flash flood]] disabled his car, at which point he removed its license plates, took what he could carry, and kept moving on foot. His car was later found, repaired, and put into service as an undercover vehicle for the local police department.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=Into the Wild |date=1996 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |location=New York |pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n===Alaska===\nIn April 1992, McCandless [[hitchhiking|hitchhiked]] from South Dakota to [[Fairbanks, Alaska]]. He was last seen alive at the head of the [[Stampede Trail]] on April 28 by a local electrician named Jim Gallien, who had given McCandless a ride from Fairbanks to the start of the rugged track just outside the small town of [[Healy, Alaska|Healy]]. Gallien later said he had been seriously concerned about the safety of McCandless (who introduced himself as \"Alex\") after noticing his light pack, minimal equipment, meager rations, and obvious lack of experience. Gallien said he had deep doubts about \"Alex's\" ability to survive the harsh and unforgiving [[The Bush (Alaska)|Alaskan bush]].\n\nGallien tried repeatedly to persuade McCandless to delay the trip, at one point offering to detour to [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]] and buy him suitable equipment and supplies. However, McCandless ignored Gallien's persistent warnings and refused his offers of assistance (though McCandless did accept a pair of [[Xtratuf]]s, two sandwiches, and a packet of corn chips from Gallien). Gallien dropped McCandless off believing he would head back towards the highway within a few days as hunger set in.<ref name=\"Krakauer 1997\" />\n\nAfter hiking along the snow-covered [[Stampede Trail]], McCandless came upon an [[Stampede Trail#Bus 142|abandoned bus]] (about {{convert|28|mi|km}} west of Healy at {{coord|63|52|5.96|N|149|46|8.39|W|display=inline}}) alongside an overgrown section of the trail near [[Denali National Park]]. McCandless, according to ''Into the Wild'', attempted to continue \"heading west until I hit the [[Bering Sea]].\" However, he was deterred by the thick Alaskan bush and returned to the bus, where he set up camp and attempted to live off the land. He had {{convert|4.5|kg|lb}} of rice, a [[Remington Arms|Remington]] semi-automatic rifle with 400 rounds of [[.22 Long Rifle|.22LR]] [[hollowpoint]] ammunition, a number of books, including one on local plant life, some personal effects, and a few items of camping equipment. Self-portrait photographs and journal entries indicate he foraged for edible plants and hunted game. McCandless hunted [[porcupine]]s, [[squirrel]]s, and birds, such as [[White-tailed Ptarmigan|ptarmigan]]s and [[Canada geese]]. On June 9, 1992, he stalked and shot a [[moose]]. However, the meat spoiled within days after McCandless failed to properly preserve it.\n\nIt has been speculated that McCandless may have been responsible for [[vandalism|vandalizing]] several cabins in the area that were stocked with food, survival equipment, and emergency supplies. In response, Denali National Park Chief Ranger Ken Kehrer has categorically stated that McCandless was not considered a viable suspect by the [[National Park Service]].<ref>''Into the Wild'', page 197</ref>\n\nMcCandless' journal documents 113 days in the area. In July, after living in the bus for a little over two months, he decided to head back to civilization &ndash; but the trail was blocked by the swollen [[Teklanika River]]; the watercourse by that stage was considerably higher and swifter than when he had crossed in April. McCandless did not have a detailed [[topography|topographical]] map of the region and was unaware of a hand-operated [[tramway (industrial)|tramway]] that crossed the river a quarter-mile away from where he had previously crossed.<ref name=\"Krakauer\" /> At this point, McCandless headed back to the bus and re-established his camp. He posted an [[SOS|S.O.S.]] note on the bus, which stated: {{quote|Attention Possible Visitors. S.O.S. I need your help. I am injured, near death, and too weak to hike out. I am all alone, this is no joke. In the name of God, please remain to save me. I am out collecting berries close by and shall return this evening. Thank you, Chris McCandless. August?<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/images/chris-mccandless_sos_lancastria.jpg |title=Scan of Chris McCandless' note |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref>}}\n\n== Death ==\nMcCandless' final written journal entry, noted as \"Day 107\", simply read, \"Beautiful Blue Berries.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.adn.com/article/chris-mccandless-example-20-years-later |title=Examining Chris McCandless, 20 years after he went 'Into the Wild' |last=Medred |first=Craig |date=August 12, 2012 |website=adn.com |publisher=The Alaska Dispatch |access-date=October 2, 2015}}</ref> Days 108 through 112 contained no words and were marked only with slashes, and on Day 113 there was no entry.<ref name=\"hewitt\">{{Cite journal |last=Hewitt |first=Bill |date=October 5, 1992 |title=End of the Trail |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20108737,00.html |journal=People |publisher=Time, Inc. |volume=38 |issue=14 |issn=0093-7673 |access-date=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 6, 1992, multiple hunters who were looking for shelter for the night came upon the converted bus where McCandless had been staying. Upon entering, they smelled what they thought was rotting food and discovered \"a lump\" in a sleeping bag. The hunters quickly radioed police, who arrived the following day. They found McCandless' [[human decomposition|decomposing]] remains in the sleeping bag. It is theorized that he died from starvation two weeks before his body was found.<ref name=\"hewitt\" />\n\n===Peril===\nIn his book ''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]'' (1996), Krakauer suggests two factors may have contributed to McCandless' death. First, he offered that McCandless was running the risk of a phenomenon known as \"[[rabbit starvation]]\", from overrelying on lean game for nutrition.<ref>''Into the Wild'', page 188</ref> Krakauer also speculated<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/how-chris-mccandless-died |title=How Chris McCandless Died |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |date=September 12, 2013 |website=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> that McCandless might have been poisoned by a toxic alkaloid called [[swainsonine]], by ingesting seeds (''[[Hedysarum alpinum]]'' or ''[[Hedysarum mackenzii]]'') containing the toxin, or possibly by a [[mould|mold]] that grows on them (''[[Rhizoctonia leguminicola]]'') when he put them damp into a plastic bag. Swainsonine inhibits [[metabolism]] of [[glycoprotein]]s, which causes starvation despite ample caloric intake.<ref name=Krakauer2013/>\n\nHowever, in an article in the September 2007 issue of ''[[Men's Journal]]'', Matthew Powers states that extensive laboratory testing showed there were no toxins or alkaloids present in the ''H. alpinum'' seeds McCandless had been eating. Dr. Thomas Clausen, the chair of the chemistry and biochemistry department at [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]], said, \"I tore that plant apart. There were no toxins. No alkaloids. I'd eat it myself.\"<ref name=\"matthew_power\">Power, Matthew. {{Cite web |url=http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |title=The Cult of Chris McCandless |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124084905/http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |archive-date=November 24, 2007 |access-date=2008-08-02 |df=mdy-all}}. ''[[Men's Journal]]'', September 2007. Retrieved Jan 03, 2011</ref> Analysis of the wild [[sweet peas]], given as the cause of McCandless' death in ''Into the Wild'', found no toxic compounds, and there is not a single account in modern medical literature of anyone being poisoned by this species of plant.<ref name=\"Terra Incognita films\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tifilms.com/wild/call_debunked.htm |title=::: Terra Incognita films ::: |date=2007-08-21 |publisher=Tifilms.com |access-date=2010-12-05}}</ref> As Powers put it: \"He didn't find a way out of the bush, couldn't catch enough food to survive, and simply starved to death\".<ref name=\"matthew_power\" />\n\nIn 2013, a new hypothesis was proposed. Ronald Hamilton, a retired bookbinder at the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"Krakauer2013\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2013/09/how-chris-mccandless-died.html |title=How Chris McCandless Died |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |date=September 12, 2013 |website=The New Yorker Blog: Page-Turner |access-date=December 12, 2014}}</ref> suggested a link between the symptoms described by McCandless and the poisoning of [[Jewish people|Jewish]] prisoners in the [[Holocaust|Nazi concentration camp]] in [[Vapniarka|Vapniarca]]. He put forward the proposal that McCandless starved to death because he was suffering from paralysis in his legs induced by [[lathyrism]], which prevented him from gathering food or hiking.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/Ronald-Hamilton/ronald-hamilton-intothewild1.html |title=Chris McCandless Now I Walk Into The Wild - Ali Ingah |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref> Lathyrism may be caused by [[ODAP]] poisoning from seeds of ''[[Hedysarum alpinum]]'' (commonly called wild potato). The ODAP, a toxic [[amino acid]], had not been detected by the previous studies of the seeds because they had suspected and tested for a toxic alkaloid, rather than an amino acid, and nobody had previously suspected that ''Hedysarum alpinum'' seeds contained this toxin. The protein would be relatively harmless to someone who was well-fed and on a normal diet, but toxic to someone who was [[malnourishment|malnourished]], physically stressed, and on an irregular and insufficient diet, as McCandless was.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://health.wusf.usf.edu/post/when-edible-plants-turn-their-defenses-us |title=When Edible Plants Turn Their Defenses On Us |date=October 24, 2013 |website=usf.edu}}</ref> As Krakauer points out, McCandless' field guide did not warn of any dangers of eating the seeds, which were not yet known to be toxic. Krakauer suspects this is the meaning of McCandless' journal entry of July 30, which states, \"EXTREMELY WEAK. FAULT OF POT[ATO] SEED. MUCH TROUBLE JUST TO STAND UP. STARVING. GREAT JEOPARDY.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/bio.html |title=Chris McCandless Now I Walk Into The Wild Biography - Christopher McCandless Journal |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Krakauer published an article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' following up on Hamilton's claims.<ref name=Krakauer2013/> A sample of fresh ''Hedysarum alpinum'' seeds was sent to a laboratory for [[High-performance liquid chromatography|HPLC]] analysis. Results suggest that the seeds contained 0.394% beta-ODAP by weight, a concentration well within the levels known to cause lathyrism in humans, although the interpretation of the results was disputed by other chemists.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |last=Drahl |first=Carmen |date=October 28, 2013 |title=Chemists Dispute How 'Into The Wild' Protagonist Chris McCandless Died |url=http://cen.acs.org/articles/91/i43/Chemists-Dispute-WildProtagonist-Chris-McCandless.html |journal=Chemical and Engineering News |volume=91 |issue=43 |pages=30\u201331}}</ref> The article notes that while occasional ingestion of foodstuffs containing ODAP is not hazardous for healthy individuals eating a balanced diet, \"individuals suffering from malnutrition, stress, and acute hunger are especially sensitive to ODAP, and are thus highly susceptible to the incapacitating effects of lathyrism after ingesting the neurotoxin\".<ref name=Krakauer2013/>\n\nAnchorage reporter Craig Medred pointed out in a January 2015 article<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.adn.com/article/20150110/fiction-jon-krakauers-wild |title=The fiction that is Jon Krakauer's 'Into The Wild' |work=Alaska Dispatch News}}</ref> in the ''[[Alaska Dispatch News]]'' that [[mushroom]]s which McCandless collected, photographed,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/forum/viewtopic.php?f=11&t=8819 |title=Christopher McCandless |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref> and consumed may have also contributed to his death.\n\nIn February 2015, Krakauer published another follow-up article in ''The New Yorker'' that reported on scientific analysis of the ''H. alpinum'' seeds McCandless ate. A report in ''Wilderness and Environmental Medicine''<ref name=\":2\">Krakauer, J., et al. (2015). \"Presence of l-canavanine in Hedysarum alpinum seeds and its potential role in the death of Chris McCandless.\" Wilderness & Environmental Medicine. {{doi|10.1016/j.wem.2014.08.014}}</ref> demonstrated relatively high levels of L-[[canavanine]] in ''Hedysarum alpinum'' seeds and suggests this as the toxic component in McCandless' diet, rather than ODAP, as originally supposed by Hamilton. Krakauer goes on to speculate that L-canavanine \"was a contributing factor to\" McCandless' death.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jon Krakauer |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/chris-mccandless-died-update |title=How Chris McCandless Died: An Update |date=February 11, 2015 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=February 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe converted blue bus where McCandless lived and died has since become a well-known destination for hikers. Known as \"The Magic Bus\", the 1946 [[International Harvester]] was abandoned by road workers in 1961 on the Stampede Trail where it remains today. A plaque in McCandless' memory was affixed to the interior by his father, Walt McCandless.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sainsbury |first=Brendan |title=Lonely Planet: Alaska |last2=Benchwick |first2=Greg |last3=Bodry |first3=Catherine |publisher=Lonely Planet |year=2015 |isbn=1-742-20602-6 |edition=11 |page=274}}</ref>\n\nMcCandless' life became the subject of a number of articles, books, films, and documentaries, which helped elevate his life to the status of [[Myth#Modern mythology|modern myth]].<ref name=\"outsideonline\">{{Cite news |last=Saverin |first=Diana |url=http://www.outsideonline.com/1920626/chris-mccandless-obsession-problem |title=The Chris McCandless Obsession Problem |date=December 18, 2013 |work=Outside Online}}</ref> He became a romantic figure to some inspired by what they see as his free-spirited [[idealism]], but to others a controversial misguided figure.<ref name=\"matthew_power\" /><ref name=\"eva\">{{Cite web |url=https://evaholland.atavist.com/chasingsupertramp |title=Chasing Alexander Supertramp |last=Holland |first=Eva |date=December 5, 2013 |website=Atavist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Ottum |first=Lisa |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tr2aCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253 |title=Romantic Ecocriticism: Origins and Legacies |publisher=Lexington Publishing |isbn=9781498518024 |editor-last=Hall, Dewey W. |pages=253\u2013270 |chapter=The Miseducation of Chris McCandless}}</ref> \"The Magic Bus\" has become a pilgrimage destination for trekkers who camp at the vehicle, some of whom have gotten into their own difficulties or even died due to the [[Teklanika River]].<ref name=\"outsideonline\" /><ref name=eva /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/newlywed-swept-away-alaska-trying-reach-wild-bus-n1035306 |title=Newlywed swept away in Alaska trying to reach 'into the Wild' bus |date=July 27, 2019 |access-date=July 27, 2019 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Assessments==\nMcCandless has been a polarizing figure since his story came to widespread public attention, with the publication of Krakauer's January 1993 ''Outside'' article.<ref name=\"matthew_power\" /><ref name=eva /> While the author and many others have a sympathetic view of the young traveler,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://outsideonline.com/outside/magazine/0393/letters.html |title=Letters |publisher=Outside Online |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919001102/http://outsideonline.com/outside/magazine/0393/letters.html |archive-date=September 19, 2010 |access-date=2010-12-05 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> others, particularly Alaskans, have expressed negative views about McCandless and those who romanticize his fate.<ref name=\"peter_christian\">[[George Mason University]] English Department. Text and Community website. Christian, Peter. [http://nmge.gmu.edu/textandcommunity/2006/Peter_Christian_Response.pdf Chris McCandless from a Park Ranger's Perspective]. Retrieved August 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nAlaskan [[Park Ranger]] Peter Christian wrote:\n\n<blockquote>When you consider McCandless from my perspective, you quickly see that what he did wasn't even particularly daring, just stupid, tragic, and inconsiderate. First off, he spent very little time learning how to actually live in the wild. He arrived at the Stampede Trail without even a map of the area. If he [had] had a good map he could have walked out of his predicament [...] Essentially, Chris McCandless committed suicide.<ref name=\"peter_christian\" /></blockquote>\n\nKen Ilgunas, also an Alaskan Park Ranger and the author of ''The McCandless Mecca'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-mccandless-mecca-ken-ilgunas/1117444438 |title=The McCandless Mecca |last=Ilgunas |first=Ken |website=[[Barnes & Noble]] |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> writes:\n\n<blockquote>Before I go any further, I should say that Pete is a really good guy [...] But with that said, I think Pete is very, very wrong. [...] Because I am in the unique position as both an Alaskan park ranger [...] I feel I can speak with some authority on the subject. [...] McCandless, of course, did not commit suicide. He starved to death, accidentally poisoned himself, or a combination of the two.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kenilgunas.com/2009/10/chris-mccandless-from-another-park.html |title=Chris McCandless from Another Alaska Park Ranger's Perspective |last=Ilgunas |first=Ken |website=[[Plume (publisher)|Plume]] |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nSherry Simpson, writing in the ''[[Anchorage Press]]'', described her trip to the bus with a friend, and their reaction upon reading the comments that tourists had left lauding McCandless as an insightful, [[Henry David Thoreau|Thoreau]]-like figure:\n\n<blockquote>Among my friends and acquaintances, the story of Christopher McCandless makes great after-dinner conversation. Much of the time I agree with the \"he had a death wish\" camp because I don't know how else to reconcile what we know of his ordeal. Now and then I venture into the \"what a dumbshit\" territory, tempered by brief alliances with the \"he was just another romantic boy on an all-American quest\" partisans. Mostly I'm puzzled by the way he's emerged as a hero.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pitt.edu/~nidus/archives/spring2003/manmadecold.html |title=A Man Made Cold by the Universe |last=Simpson |first=Sherry |publisher=[[Anchorage Press]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040328080406/http://www.pitt.edu/~nidus/archives/spring2003/manmadecold.html |archive-date=2004-03-28 |access-date=15 February 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nKrakauer defends McCandless, claiming that what critics point to as arrogance was merely McCandless' desire for \"being the first to explore a blank spot on the map.\" He continues: \"In 1992, however, there were no more blank spots on the map\u2014not in Alaska, not anywhere. But Chris, with his idiosyncratic logic, came up with an elegant solution to this dilemma: He simply got rid of the map. In his own mind, if nowhere else, the ''terra'' would thereby remain ''incognita''.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/metro/02.15.96/krakauer-9607.html |title=North to Alaska |last=Young |first=Gordon |date=Feb 1996 |publisher=Metroactive.com |access-date=2010-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nKrakauer's approximately 9,000-word article \"Death of an Innocent\" (January 1993) was published in ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krakauer, Jon |url=http://chsenglishap3.weebly.com/uploads/1/3/5/2/13523052/death_of_an_innocent-original_outside_magazine_article.pdf |title=Death of an Innocent |date=January 1993 |work=Outside}}</ref> Chip Brown's full-length article on McCandless, \"I Now Walk Into the Wild\" (February 8, 1993), was published in ''The New Yorker''.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal |last=Brown |first=Chip |date=February 8, 1993 |title=I Now Walk Into the Wild |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1993/02/08/i-now-walk-into-the-wild |journal=The New Yorker |page=pg 38 |issn=0028-792X}}</ref> Jon Krakauer's non-fiction book ''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]'' (1996) expands upon his 1993 ''Outside'' article and retraces McCandless' travels leading up to the hiker's eventual death.\n\nAn [[Into the Wild (film)|eponymous 2007 film adaptation]] of ''Into the Wild'', directed by [[Sean Penn]] with [[Emile Hirsch]] portraying McCandless, received a number of awards, including Best Picture from the [[American Film Institute]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/352389/Into-the-Wild/details |title=Into the Wild |date=2007 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[Ron Lamothe]]'s documentary ''[[The Call of the Wild (2007 film)|The Call of the Wild]]'' (2007) also covers McCandless' life story.\n\nThe 2011 book ''Back to the Wild'' compiles photographs, postcards and journal entries by McCandless. A [[PBS]] documentary uncovering some additional information, with interviews, titled ''Return to the Wild: The Chris McCandless Story'', first aired on the PBS network in November 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/program/return-to-the-wild/ |title=Return to the Wild |date=November 2014 |website=PBS Programs}}</ref>\n\nCarine McCandless, Chris' younger sister, wrote the [[memoir]] ''The Wild Truth'' (November 2014), published by [[HarperCollins]]. In the book, Carine describes [[verbal abuse|verbal]], [[physical abuse|physical]] and [[sexual abuse]] her parents allegedly inflicted upon each other and their children, often fueled by [[alcoholism]]. Carine cites her and her brother's abusive childhood as one of the motivating factors in Chris' desire to \"disappear\" into the wilderness. In a statement released to the media shortly before the memoir was released, Walt and Billie McCandless denied their daughter's accusations, stating that her book is, \"fictionalized writing [that] has absolutely nothing to do with our beloved son, Chris, his journey or his character. This whole unfortunate event in Chris' life 22 years ago is about Chris and his dreams.\"<ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/mobile/article/0,,20871350,00.html|title=Chris McCandless' Sister Pens New Book Detailing Parents' Violence and Abuse|last1=Dodd |first1=Johnny|date=November 12, 2014 |work=People|publisher= |access-date=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Lillian Alling]]\n*[[Christopher Thomas Knight]]\n*[[Tomasz Mackiewicz]]\n*[[Carl McCunn]]\n*[[Richard Proenneke]]\n*[[Everett Ruess]]\n*[[Survivalism]]\n*[[Timothy Treadwell]]\n*[[Existentialism]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Christopher McCandless}}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.freewheelings.com/visiting-into-the-wild-magic-bus/ |title=Christopher McCandless \u2013 Finding the Christopher McCandless Bus |website=freewheelings.com}}\n*{{Findagrave|23573485}}\n*[http://www.christophermccandless.info ChristopherMcCandless.info] Website on Christopher McCandless.\n*[http://www.chrisspurpose.org Chrisspurpose.org ] \u2013 C J McCandless Memorial Foundation\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071012061942/http://www.emorywheel.com/detail.php?n=24325 Dispatches from the Wild] \u2013 Excerpts of McCandless' own articles published in the ''Emory Wheel'' student newspaper.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCandless, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Alaska]]\n[[Category:American nomads]]\n[[Category:Deaths by starvation]]\n[[Category:Emory University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hikers]]\n[[Category:People from Annandale, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from El Segundo, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American hiker and explorer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Chris McCandless\n| image              = Chris McCandless.png\n| image_size         =\n| other_names        = Alexander Supertramp\n| caption            = Self-portrait of McCandless on the [[Stampede Trail]], found undeveloped in his camera after his death\n| birth_name         = Christopher Johnson McCandless\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1968|2|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[El Segundo, California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date         = [[circa|c.]] August 1992 (aged 24)<!-- Please do not enter an exact date as the exact date is not known and never will be -->\n| death_place        = [[Stampede Trail]], [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Starvation]], possibly brought on by [[poisoning]]<ref>Krakauer, J., et al. (2015). \"Presence of l-canavanine in Hedysarum alpinum seeds and its potential role in the death of Chris McCandless.\" Wilderness & Environmental Medicine. doi:10.1016/j.wem.2014.08.014</ref> <!--The probable cause of death, according to the coroner\u2019s report, was starvation. However, the possibility of poisoning is not out of the question. -->\n| body_discovered    = September 6, 1992\n| education          = [[Wilbert Tucker Woodson High School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Emory University]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Johnson McCandless''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|k|\u00e6|n|d|l|\u1d7b|s}}; February 12, 1968<ref>{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=Into the Wild |publisher=Anchor Books |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |page=53 |chapter=6}}</ref> \u2013 c. August<!-- Please do not enter an exact date as the exact date is not known and never will be --> 1992), also known by the pseudonym '''Alexander Supertramp''' ('''Alex'''), was an American [[hiker]]<!--please explain any changes to this word on the article's talk page--> who sought an increasingly itinerant lifestyle as he grew up. McCandless is the subject of ''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]'', a nonfiction book by [[Jon Krakauer]] that was later made into [[Into the Wild (film)|a full-length feature film]].\n\nAfter graduating from college in 1990, McCandless traveled across North America and eventually hitchhiked to [[Alaska]] in April 1992. There, he set out along an old mining road known as the [[Stampede Trail]] with minimal supplies, hoping to [[Simple living|live simply]] off the land. On the eastern bank of the Sushana River, McCandless found an abandoned bus, [[Stampede_Trail#Bus_142|Fairbanks Bus 142]], which he used as a makeshift shelter until his death. In September, his [[human decomposition|decomposing]] body, weighing only 67 pounds (30 kilograms), was found by a hunter inside the bus. McCandless's cause of death was officially ruled to be [[starvation]],<ref name=\"Terra Incognita films\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> although the exact cause remains the subject of some debate.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Krakauer2013\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn January 1993, Jon Krakauer published McCandless' story in that month's issue of ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]'' magazine. He had been assigned the story and had written it under a tight deadline.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krakauer, Jon |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/how-chris-mccandless-died |title=How Chris McCandless Died |date=September 12, 2013 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref> Inspired by the details of McCandless' story, he wrote and published the more extensive biographical book ''Into the Wild'' in 1996. The book was subsequently adapted into a 2007 [[Into the Wild (film)|film]] directed by [[Sean Penn]], with [[Emile Hirsch]] portraying McCandless. That same year, McCandless' story also became the subject of [[Ron Lamothe]]'s documentary ''[[The Call of the Wild (2007 film)|The Call of the Wild]]'' (2007).\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Johnson McCandless was born in [[El Segundo, California|El Segundo]], [[California]]. He was the first child of Wilhelmina \"Billie\" McCandless (n\u00e9e Johnson) and Walter \"Walt\" McCandless. Afterwards the couple had one more child, a daughter named Carine. McCandless also had six half-siblings from Walt's first marriage, who lived with their mother in California. Author [[Jon Krakauer]] later speculated that Walt's transition between these two marriages affected McCandless deeply and shaped his [[worldview]].<ref name=\"Krakauer 1997\">{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=[[Into the Wild (book)|Into The Wild]] |publisher=Anchor |year=1997 |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |location=[[New York City]] |author-link=Jon Krakauer}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, the family relocated to [[Washington, D.C.]], and settled in suburban [[Annandale, Virginia|Annandale]], [[Virginia]], when McCandless' father was hired as an antenna specialist for the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA); McCandless' mother worked as a secretary at [[Hughes Aircraft]]. The couple went on to establish a successful consultancy business out of their home, specializing in Walt's area of expertise.\n\nMcCandless graduated from [[Wilbert Tucker Woodson High School|W.T. Woodson High School]] in [[Fairfax, Virginia]], in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Williams |first=Preston |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/23/AR2007102302042.html |title=Remembering an Athlete Who Never Returned From the Wild |date=October 25, 2007 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> He excelled academically, although a number of teachers and fellow students observed that he \"marched to the beat of a different drummer.\" McCandless also served as captain of the [[cross country running|cross-country]] team, where he would urge teammates to treat running as a spiritual exercise in which they were \"running against the forces of darkness&nbsp;... all the evil in the world, all the hatred.\"<ref name=\"Krakauer\">{{cite magazine| first=Jon|last=Krakauer|authorlink=Jon Krakauer| url = http://hudson.k12.oh.us/cms/lib08/OH01914911/Centricity/Domain/1167/Krakauer%20article%20McCandless.pdf\n | title = Death of an Innocent: How Christopher McCandless Lost His Way in the Wilds.\n | magazine = [[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]\n | date = January 1993\n | accessdate = 2008-04-04\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1986, McCandless traveled to [[Southern California]] and reconnected with distant relatives and friends. It was during this journey he learned that his father had not yet divorced his first wife when McCandless and his sister Carine were born, and had apparently maintained somewhat of a [[double life]] before the move to Virginia. It is speculated that this discovery had a profound impact on the younger McCandless.<ref name=\"Krakauer 1997 166\">{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=[[Into the Wild (book)|Into The Wild]] |publisher=Anchor |year=1997 |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |location=[[New York City]] |page=166 |author-link=Jon Krakauer}}</ref>\n\nMcCandless graduated from [[Emory University]] in May 1990, with a [[bachelor's degree]] in the double majors of [[history]] and [[anthropology]].<ref name=\"Krakauer\" /> After graduating, he donated his college savings of $24,000 to [[OXFAM]] and adopted a [[vagabond]] lifestyle, working when necessary as a restaurant food preparer and farm hand.<ref>{{Cite book |last=McCandless |first=Carine |title=The Wild Truth |date=2014 |publisher=Harper One |isbn=978-0-06-232514-3 |location=New York City}}</ref> An avid [[outdoorsman]], McCandless completed several lengthy wilderness hiking trips and paddled a canoe down a portion of the [[Colorado River]] before hitchhiking to [[Alaska]] in April 1992.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |url=https://archive.org/details/intowild00krak_1/page/5 |title=Into the Wild |date=1996 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-679-42850-X |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/intowild00krak_1/page/5 5, 32\u201336]}}</ref>\n\n==Travels==\nBy the end of summer in 1990, McCandless had driven his [[Datsun]] through California, [[Arizona]], and [[South Dakota]], where he worked at a [[grain elevator]] in [[Carthage, South Dakota|Carthage]]. A [[flash flood]] disabled his car, at which point he removed its license plates, took what he could carry, and kept moving on foot. His car was later found, repaired, and put into service as an undercover vehicle for the local police department.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |title=Into the Wild |date=1996 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-385-48680-4 |location=New York |pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n===Alaska===\nIn April 1992, McCandless [[hitchhiking|hitchhiked]] from South Dakota to [[Fairbanks, Alaska]]. He was last seen alive at the head of the [[Stampede Trail]] on April 28 by a local electrician named Jim Gallien, who had given McCandless a ride from Fairbanks to the start of the rugged track just outside the small town of [[Healy, Alaska|Healy]]. Gallien later said he had been seriously concerned about the safety of McCandless (who introduced himself as \"Alex\") after noticing his light pack, minimal equipment, meager rations, and obvious lack of experience. Gallien said he had deep doubts about \"Alex's\" ability to survive the harsh and unforgiving [[The Bush (Alaska)|Alaskan bush]].\n\nGallien tried repeatedly to persuade McCandless to delay the trip, at one point offering to detour to [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]] and buy him suitable equipment and supplies. However, McCandless ignored Gallien's persistent warnings and refused his offers of assistance (though McCandless did accept a pair of [[Xtratuf]]s, two sandwiches, and a packet of corn chips from Gallien). Gallien dropped McCandless off believing he would head back towards the highway within a few days as hunger set in.<ref name=\"Krakauer 1997\" />\n\nAfter hiking along the snow-covered [[Stampede Trail]], McCandless came upon an [[Stampede Trail#Bus 142|abandoned bus]] (about {{convert|28|mi|km}} west of Healy at {{coord|63|52|5.96|N|149|46|8.39|W|display=inline}}) alongside an overgrown section of the trail near [[Denali National Park]]. McCandless, according to ''Into the Wild'', attempted to continue \"heading west until I hit the [[Bering Sea]].\" However, he was deterred by the thick Alaskan bush and returned to the bus, where he set up camp and attempted to live off the land. He had {{convert|4.5|kg|lb}} of rice, a [[Remington Arms|Remington]] semi-automatic rifle with 400 rounds of [[.22 Long Rifle|.22LR]] [[hollowpoint]] ammunition, a number of books, including one on local plant life, some personal effects, and a few items of camping equipment. Self-portrait photographs and journal entries indicate he foraged for edible plants and hunted game. McCandless hunted [[porcupine]]s, [[squirrel]]s, and birds, such as [[White-tailed Ptarmigan|ptarmigan]]s and [[Canada geese]]. On June 9, 1992, he stalked and shot a [[moose]]. However, the meat spoiled within days after McCandless failed to properly preserve it.\n\nIt has been speculated that McCandless may have been responsible for [[vandalism|vandalizing]] several cabins in the area that were stocked with food, survival equipment, and emergency supplies. In response, Denali National Park Chief Ranger Ken Kehrer has categorically stated that McCandless was not considered a viable suspect by the [[National Park Service]].<ref>''Into the Wild'', page 197</ref>\n\nMcCandless' journal documents 113 days in the area. In July, after living in the bus for a little over two months, he decided to head back to civilization &ndash; but the trail was blocked by the swollen [[Teklanika River]]; the watercourse by that stage was considerably higher and swifter than when he had crossed in April. McCandless did not have a detailed [[topography|topographical]] map of the region and was unaware of a hand-operated [[tramway (industrial)|tramway]] that crossed the river a quarter-mile away from where he had previously crossed.<ref name=\"Krakauer\" /> At this point, McCandless headed back to the bus and re-established his camp. He posted an [[SOS|S.O.S.]] note on the bus, which stated: {{quote|Attention Possible Visitors. S.O.S. I need your help. I am injured, near death, and too weak to hike out. I am all alone, this is no joke. In the name of God, please remain to save me. I am out collecting berries close by and shall return this evening. Thank you, Chris McCandless. August?<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/images/chris-mccandless_sos_lancastria.jpg |title=Scan of Chris McCandless' note |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref>}}\n\n== Death ==\nMcCandless' final written journal entry, noted as \"Day 107\", simply read, \"Beautiful Blue Berries.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.adn.com/article/chris-mccandless-example-20-years-later |title=Examining Chris McCandless, 20 years after he went 'Into the Wild' |last=Medred |first=Craig |date=August 12, 2012 |website=adn.com |publisher=The Alaska Dispatch |access-date=October 2, 2015}}</ref> Days 108 through 112 contained no words and were marked only with slashes, and on Day 113 there was no entry.<ref name=\"hewitt\">{{Cite journal |last=Hewitt |first=Bill |date=October 5, 1992 |title=End of the Trail |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20108737,00.html |journal=People |publisher=Time, Inc. |volume=38 |issue=14 |issn=0093-7673 |access-date=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 6, 1992, multiple hunters who were looking for shelter for the night came upon the converted bus where McCandless had been staying. Upon entering, they smelled what they thought was rotting food and discovered \"a lump\" in a sleeping bag. The hunters quickly radioed police, who arrived the following day. They found McCandless' [[human decomposition|decomposing]] remains in the sleeping bag. It is theorized that he died from starvation two weeks before his body was found.<ref name=\"hewitt\" />\n\n===Peril===\nIn his book ''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]'' (1996), Krakauer suggests two factors may have contributed to McCandless' death. First, he offered that McCandless was running the risk of a phenomenon known as \"[[rabbit starvation]]\", from overrelying on lean game for nutrition.<ref>''Into the Wild'', page 188</ref> Krakauer also speculated<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/how-chris-mccandless-died |title=How Chris McCandless Died |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |date=September 12, 2013 |website=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> that McCandless might have been poisoned by a toxic alkaloid called [[swainsonine]], by ingesting seeds (''[[Hedysarum alpinum]]'' or ''[[Hedysarum mackenzii]]'') containing the toxin, or possibly by a [[mould|mold]] that grows on them (''[[Rhizoctonia leguminicola]]'') when he put them damp into a plastic bag. Swainsonine inhibits [[metabolism]] of [[glycoprotein]]s, which causes starvation despite ample caloric intake.<ref name=Krakauer2013/>\n\nHowever, in an article in the September 2007 issue of ''[[Men's Journal]]'', Matthew Powers states that extensive laboratory testing showed there were no toxins or alkaloids present in the ''H. alpinum'' seeds McCandless had been eating. Dr. Thomas Clausen, the chair of the chemistry and biochemistry department at [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]], said, \"I tore that plant apart. There were no toxins. No alkaloids. I'd eat it myself.\"<ref name=\"matthew_power\">Power, Matthew. {{Cite web |url=http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |title=The Cult of Chris McCandless |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124084905/http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |archive-date=November 24, 2007 |access-date=2008-08-02 |df=mdy-all}}. ''[[Men's Journal]]'', September 2007. Retrieved Jan 03, 2011</ref> Analysis of the wild [[sweet peas]], given as the cause of McCandless' death in ''Into the Wild'', found no toxic compounds, and there is not a single account in modern medical literature of anyone being poisoned by this species of plant.<ref name=\"Terra Incognita films\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tifilms.com/wild/call_debunked.htm |title=::: Terra Incognita films ::: |date=2007-08-21 |publisher=Tifilms.com |access-date=2010-12-05}}</ref> As Powers put it: \"He didn't find a way out of the bush, couldn't catch enough food to survive, and simply starved to death\".<ref name=\"matthew_power\" />\n\nIn 2013, a new hypothesis was proposed. Ronald Hamilton, a retired bookbinder at the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"Krakauer2013\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2013/09/how-chris-mccandless-died.html |title=How Chris McCandless Died |last=Krakauer |first=Jon |date=September 12, 2013 |website=The New Yorker Blog: Page-Turner |access-date=December 12, 2014}}</ref> suggested a link between the symptoms described by McCandless and the poisoning of [[Jewish people|Jewish]] prisoners in the [[Holocaust|Nazi concentration camp]] in [[Vapniarka|Vapniarca]]. He put forward the proposal that McCandless starved to death because he was suffering from paralysis in his legs induced by [[lathyrism]], which prevented him from gathering food or hiking.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/Ronald-Hamilton/ronald-hamilton-intothewild1.html |title=Chris McCandless Now I Walk Into The Wild - Ali Ingah |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref> Lathyrism may be caused by [[ODAP]] poisoning from seeds of ''[[Hedysarum alpinum]]'' (commonly called wild potato). The ODAP, a toxic [[amino acid]], had not been detected by the previous studies of the seeds because they had suspected and tested for a toxic alkaloid, rather than an amino acid, and nobody had previously suspected that ''Hedysarum alpinum'' seeds contained this toxin. The protein would be relatively harmless to someone who was well-fed and on a normal diet, but toxic to someone who was [[malnourishment|malnourished]], physically stressed, and on an irregular and insufficient diet, as McCandless was.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://health.wusf.usf.edu/post/when-edible-plants-turn-their-defenses-us |title=When Edible Plants Turn Their Defenses On Us |date=October 24, 2013 |website=usf.edu}}</ref> As Krakauer points out, McCandless' field guide did not warn of any dangers of eating the seeds, which were not yet known to be toxic. Krakauer suspects this is the meaning of McCandless' journal entry of July 30, which states, \"EXTREMELY WEAK. FAULT OF POT[ATO] SEED. MUCH TROUBLE JUST TO STAND UP. STARVING. GREAT JEOPARDY.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/bio.html |title=Chris McCandless Now I Walk Into The Wild Biography - Christopher McCandless Journal |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Krakauer published an article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' following up on Hamilton's claims.<ref name=Krakauer2013/> A sample of fresh ''Hedysarum alpinum'' seeds was sent to a laboratory for [[High-performance liquid chromatography|HPLC]] analysis. Results suggest that the seeds contained 0.394% beta-ODAP by weight, a concentration well within the levels known to cause lathyrism in humans, although the interpretation of the results was disputed by other chemists.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |last=Drahl |first=Carmen |date=October 28, 2013 |title=Chemists Dispute How 'Into The Wild' Protagonist Chris McCandless Died |url=http://cen.acs.org/articles/91/i43/Chemists-Dispute-WildProtagonist-Chris-McCandless.html |journal=Chemical and Engineering News |volume=91 |issue=43 |pages=30\u201331}}</ref> The article notes that while occasional ingestion of foodstuffs containing ODAP is not hazardous for healthy individuals eating a balanced diet, \"individuals suffering from malnutrition, stress, and acute hunger are especially sensitive to ODAP, and are thus highly susceptible to the incapacitating effects of lathyrism after ingesting the neurotoxin\".<ref name=Krakauer2013/>\n\nAnchorage reporter Craig Medred pointed out in a January 2015 article<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.adn.com/article/20150110/fiction-jon-krakauers-wild |title=The fiction that is Jon Krakauer's 'Into The Wild' |work=Alaska Dispatch News}}</ref> in the ''[[Alaska Dispatch News]]'' that [[mushroom]]s which McCandless collected, photographed,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christophermccandless.info/forum/viewtopic.php?f=11&t=8819 |title=Christopher McCandless |website=christophermccandless.info}}</ref> and consumed may have also contributed to his death.\n\nIn February 2015, Krakauer published another follow-up article in ''The New Yorker'' that reported on scientific analysis of the ''H. alpinum'' seeds McCandless ate. A report in ''Wilderness and Environmental Medicine''<ref name=\":2\">Krakauer, J., et al. (2015). \"Presence of l-canavanine in Hedysarum alpinum seeds and its potential role in the death of Chris McCandless.\" Wilderness & Environmental Medicine. {{doi|10.1016/j.wem.2014.08.014}}</ref> demonstrated relatively high levels of L-[[canavanine]] in ''Hedysarum alpinum'' seeds and suggests this as the toxic component in McCandless' diet, rather than ODAP, as originally supposed by Hamilton. Krakauer goes on to speculate that L-canavanine \"was a contributing factor to\" McCandless' death.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jon Krakauer |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/chris-mccandless-died-update |title=How Chris McCandless Died: An Update |date=February 11, 2015 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=February 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe converted blue bus where McCandless lived and died has since become a well-known destination for hikers. Known as \"The Magic Bus\", the 1946 [[International Harvester]] was abandoned by road workers in 1961 on the Stampede Trail where it remains today. A plaque in McCandless' memory was affixed to the interior by his father, Walt McCandless.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Sainsbury |first=Brendan |title=Lonely Planet: Alaska |last2=Benchwick |first2=Greg |last3=Bodry |first3=Catherine |publisher=Lonely Planet |year=2015 |isbn=1-742-20602-6 |edition=11 |page=274}}</ref>\n\nMcCandless' life became the subject of a number of articles, books, films, and documentaries, which helped elevate his life to the status of [[Myth#Modern mythology|modern myth]].<ref name=\"outsideonline\">{{Cite news |last=Saverin |first=Diana |url=http://www.outsideonline.com/1920626/chris-mccandless-obsession-problem |title=The Chris McCandless Obsession Problem |date=December 18, 2013 |work=Outside Online}}</ref> He became a romantic figure to some inspired by what they see as his free-spirited [[idealism]], but to others a controversial misguided figure.<ref name=\"matthew_power\" /><ref name=\"eva\">{{Cite web |url=https://evaholland.atavist.com/chasingsupertramp |title=Chasing Alexander Supertramp |last=Holland |first=Eva |date=December 5, 2013 |website=Atavist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Ottum |first=Lisa |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tr2aCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253 |title=Romantic Ecocriticism: Origins and Legacies |publisher=Lexington Publishing |isbn=9781498518024 |editor-last=Hall, Dewey W. |pages=253\u2013270 |chapter=The Miseducation of Chris McCandless}}</ref> \"The Magic Bus\" has become a pilgrimage destination for trekkers who camp at the vehicle, some of whom have gotten into their own difficulties or even died due to the [[Teklanika River]].<ref name=\"outsideonline\" /><ref name=eva /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/newlywed-swept-away-alaska-trying-reach-wild-bus-n1035306 |title=Newlywed swept away in Alaska trying to reach 'into the Wild' bus |date=July 27, 2019 |access-date=July 27, 2019 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Assessments==\nMcCandless has been a polarizing figure since his story came to widespread public attention, with the publication of Krakauer's January 1993 ''Outside'' article.<ref name=\"matthew_power\" /><ref name=eva /> While the author and many others have a sympathetic view of the young traveler,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://outsideonline.com/outside/magazine/0393/letters.html |title=Letters |publisher=Outside Online |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919001102/http://outsideonline.com/outside/magazine/0393/letters.html |archive-date=September 19, 2010 |access-date=2010-12-05 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> others, particularly Alaskans, have expressed negative views about McCandless and those who romanticize his fate.<ref name=\"peter_christian\">[[George Mason University]] English Department. Text and Community website. Christian, Peter. [http://nmge.gmu.edu/textandcommunity/2006/Peter_Christian_Response.pdf Chris McCandless from a Park Ranger's Perspective]. Retrieved August 26, 2007.</ref>\n\nAlaskan [[Park Ranger]] Peter Christian wrote:\n\n<blockquote>When you consider McCandless from my perspective, you quickly see that what he did wasn't even particularly daring, just stupid, tragic, and inconsiderate. First off, he spent very little time learning how to actually live in the wild. He arrived at the Stampede Trail without even a map of the area. If he [had] had a good map he could have walked out of his predicament [...] Essentially, Chris McCandless committed suicide.<ref name=\"peter_christian\" /></blockquote>\n\nKen Ilgunas, also an Alaskan Park Ranger and the author of ''The McCandless Mecca'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-mccandless-mecca-ken-ilgunas/1117444438 |title=The McCandless Mecca |last=Ilgunas |first=Ken |website=[[Barnes & Noble]] |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> writes:\n\n<blockquote>Before I go any further, I should say that Pete is a really good guy [...] But with that said, I think Pete is very, very wrong. [...] Because I am in the unique position as both an Alaskan park ranger [...] I feel I can speak with some authority on the subject. [...] McCandless, of course, did not commit suicide. He starved to death, accidentally poisoned himself, or a combination of the two.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kenilgunas.com/2009/10/chris-mccandless-from-another-park.html |title=Chris McCandless from Another Alaska Park Ranger's Perspective |last=Ilgunas |first=Ken |website=[[Plume (publisher)|Plume]] |access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nSherry Simpson, writing in the ''[[Anchorage Press]]'', described her trip to the bus with a friend, and their reaction upon reading the comments that tourists had left lauding McCandless as an insightful, [[Henry David Thoreau|Thoreau]]-like figure:\n\n<blockquote>Among my friends and acquaintances, the story of Christopher McCandless makes great after-dinner conversation. Much of the time I agree with the \"he had a death wish\" camp because I don't know how else to reconcile what we know of his ordeal. Now and then I venture into the \"what a dumbshit\" territory, tempered by brief alliances with the \"he was just another romantic boy on an all-American quest\" partisans. Mostly I'm puzzled by the way he's emerged as a hero.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pitt.edu/~nidus/archives/spring2003/manmadecold.html |title=A Man Made Cold by the Universe |last=Simpson |first=Sherry |publisher=[[Anchorage Press]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040328080406/http://www.pitt.edu/~nidus/archives/spring2003/manmadecold.html |archive-date=2004-03-28 |access-date=15 February 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nKrakauer defends McCandless, claiming that what critics point to as arrogance was merely McCandless' desire for \"being the first to explore a blank spot on the map.\" He continues: \"In 1992, however, there were no more blank spots on the map\u2014not in Alaska, not anywhere. But Chris, with his idiosyncratic logic, came up with an elegant solution to this dilemma: He simply got rid of the map. In his own mind, if nowhere else, the ''terra'' would thereby remain ''incognita''.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/metro/02.15.96/krakauer-9607.html |title=North to Alaska |last=Young |first=Gordon |date=Feb 1996 |publisher=Metroactive.com |access-date=2010-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nKrakauer's approximately 9,000-word article \"Death of an Innocent\" (January 1993) was published in ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Krakauer, Jon |url=http://chsenglishap3.weebly.com/uploads/1/3/5/2/13523052/death_of_an_innocent-original_outside_magazine_article.pdf |title=Death of an Innocent |date=January 1993 |work=Outside}}</ref> Chip Brown's full-length article on McCandless, \"I Now Walk Into the Wild\" (February 8, 1993), was published in ''The New Yorker''.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal |last=Brown |first=Chip |date=February 8, 1993 |title=I Now Walk Into the Wild |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1993/02/08/i-now-walk-into-the-wild |journal=The New Yorker |page=pg 38 |issn=0028-792X}}</ref> Jon Krakauer's non-fiction book ''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]'' (1996) expands upon his 1993 ''Outside'' article and retraces McCandless' travels leading up to the hiker's eventual death.\n\nAn [[Into the Wild (film)|eponymous 2007 film adaptation]] of ''Into the Wild'', directed by [[Sean Penn]] with [[Emile Hirsch]] portraying McCandless, received a number of awards, including Best Picture from the [[American Film Institute]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/352389/Into-the-Wild/details |title=Into the Wild |date=2007 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[Ron Lamothe]]'s documentary ''[[The Call of the Wild (2007 film)|The Call of the Wild]]'' (2007) also covers McCandless' life story.\n\nThe 2011 book ''Back to the Wild'' compiles photographs, postcards and journal entries by McCandless. A [[PBS]] documentary uncovering some additional information, with interviews, titled ''Return to the Wild: The Chris McCandless Story'', first aired on the PBS network in November 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/program/return-to-the-wild/ |title=Return to the Wild |date=November 2014 |website=PBS Programs}}</ref>\n\nCarine McCandless, Chris' younger sister, wrote the [[memoir]] ''The Wild Truth'' (November 2014), published by [[HarperCollins]]. In the book, Carine describes [[verbal abuse|verbal]], [[physical abuse|physical]] and [[sexual abuse]] her parents allegedly inflicted upon each other and their children, often fueled by [[alcoholism]]. Carine cites her and her brother's abusive childhood as one of the motivating factors in Chris' desire to \"disappear\" into the wilderness. In a statement released to the media shortly before the memoir was released, Walt and Billie McCandless denied their daughter's accusations, stating that her book is, \"fictionalized writing [that] has absolutely nothing to do with our beloved son, Chris, his journey or his character. This whole unfortunate event in Chris' life 22 years ago is about Chris and his dreams.\"<ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/mobile/article/0,,20871350,00.html|title=Chris McCandless' Sister Pens New Book Detailing Parents' Violence and Abuse|last1=Dodd |first1=Johnny|date=November 12, 2014 |work=People|publisher= |access-date=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Lillian Alling]]\n*[[Christopher Thomas Knight]]\n*[[Tomasz Mackiewicz]]\n*[[Carl McCunn]]\n*[[Richard Proenneke]]\n*[[Everett Ruess]]\n*[[Survivalism]]\n*[[Timothy Treadwell]]\n*[[Existentialism]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Christopher McCandless}}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.freewheelings.com/visiting-into-the-wild-magic-bus/ |title=Christopher McCandless \u2013 Finding the Christopher McCandless Bus |website=freewheelings.com}}\n*{{Findagrave|23573485}}\n*[http://www.christophermccandless.info ChristopherMcCandless.info] Website on Christopher McCandless.\n*[http://www.chrisspurpose.org Chrisspurpose.org ] \u2013 C J McCandless Memorial Foundation\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071012061942/http://www.emorywheel.com/detail.php?n=24325 Dispatches from the Wild] \u2013 Excerpts of McCandless' own articles published in the ''Emory Wheel'' student newspaper.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCandless, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Alaska]]\n[[Category:American nomads]]\n[[Category:Deaths by starvation]]\n[[Category:Emory University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hikers]]\n[[Category:People from Annandale, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from El Segundo, California]]\n", "name_user": "100.6.57.74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_McCandless"}
{"title_page": "University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences\n|native_name     = <big>\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629</big>\n|established     = 1990\n|type            = Public<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.university-directory.eu/Sudan/Sudan.html\n |title=Sudan academic institutions Directory\n |work=University Directory\n |accessdate=2011-09-15}}</ref>\n|chancellor      = [[Ebrahim Norin Ebrahim]]\n|city            = [[Omdurman]]\n|country         = [[Sudan]]\n|state           = [[Khartoum (state)|Khartoum State]]\n|undergrad       =\n|postgrad        =\n|master          =\n|phd             =\n|staff           =\n|website         ={{url|http://qunv.net23.net/en/}}\n}}\nThe '''University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences''' is a university in the state of [[Khartoum (state)|Khartoum]], [[Sudan]]. It is based in [[Omdurman]].<ref name=SelfEstablish/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe University of Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences was established in 1990.\nThe new university combined the existing Holy Quran College, established in 1981, and the Omdurman Higher Institute, established in 1983.\nThe Omdurman Higher Institute consisted of the Sharia College, Arabic Language College and Girls' College.\nThe university is government-owned, funded by the Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research.\n\n==Programs==\n\nThe university teaches [[Quran]], the [[Sunnah]] of the Prophet, the Arabic language and principles of religion and community life.\nStudents learn the heritage of Arabic and Islamic civilization.\nColleges are the College of the Holy Quran, Faculty of Sharia, Faculty of Arabic Language, Faculty of Da'wa and Media, Economics and Administrative Sciences, Social Sciences, Education, School of Languages, Graduate Studies and Community College.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://qunv.net23.net/en/?#content/13\n |title=About Us: Mission and Objective\n |publisher=University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences\n |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\nAlthough based in Omdurman, the university has faculties in all the states of Sudan.\n\n==Affiliations==\n\nThe university belongs to the [[Union of Arab Universities]], the [[Union of African Universities]] and [[Union of Islamic Universities]], and cooperates with the [[Islamic Organization for Culture, Education and Sciences]].<ref name=SelfEstablish/>\nIt is also a member of the [[Federation of the Universities of the Islamic World]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.fuiw.org/en/universites_membres.php\n |title       = Member Universities\n |publisher   = Federation of the Universities of the Islamic World\n |accessdate  = 2011-09-17\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930125830/http://www.fuiw.org/en/universites_membres.php\n |archivedate = 2011-09-30\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=SelfEstablish>{{cite web\n |url=http://qunv.net23.net/en/?#content/17\n |title=About Us: Establishment and Development\n |publisher=University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences\n |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\n}}\n{{coord|15.6343|32.4914|type:edu_region:SD|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences, University of the}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Sudan]]\n[[Category:South Kordofan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1990]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox_University\n|name            = University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences\n|native_name     = <big>\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0622\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629</big>\n|established     = 1990\n|type            = Public<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.university-directory.eu/Sudan/Sudan.html\n |title=Sudan academic institutions Directory\n |work=University Directory\n |accessdate=2011-09-15}}</ref>\n|chancellor      = [[Ebrahim Norin Ebrahim]]\n|city            = [[Omdurman]]\n|country         = [[Sudan]]\n|state           = [[Khartoum (state)|Khartoum State]]\n|undergrad       =\n|postgrad        =\n|master          =\n|phd             =\n|staff           =\n|website         ={{url|http://qunv.net23.net/en/}}\n}}\nThe '''University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences''' is a university in the state of [[Khartoum (state)|Khartoum]], [[Sudan]]. It is based in [[Omdurman]].<ref name=SelfEstablish/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe University of Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences was established in 1990.\nThe new university combined the existing Holy Quran College, established in 1981, and the Omdurman Higher Institute, established in 1983.\nThe Omdurman Higher Institute consisted of the Sharia College, Arabic Language College and Girls' College.\nThe university is government-owned, funded by the Ministry of Higher Education and Scientific Research.\n\n==Programs==\n\nThe university teaches [[Quran]], the [[Sunnah]] of the Prophet, the Arabic language and principles of religion and community life.\nStudents learn the heritage of Arabic and Islamic civilization.\nColleges are the College of the Holy Quran, Faculty of Sharia, Faculty of Arabic Language, Faculty of Da'wa and Media, Economics and Administrative Sciences, Social Sciences, Education, School of Languages, Graduate Studies and Community College. <ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://qunv.net23.net/en/?#content/13\n |title=About Us: Mission and Objective\n |publisher=University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences\n |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\nAlthough based in Omdurman, the university has faculties in all the states of Sudan. \n\n==Affiliations==\n\nThe university belongs to the [[Union of Arab Universities]], the [[Union of African Universities]] and [[Union of Islamic Universities]], and cooperates with the [[Islamic Organization for Culture, Education and Sciences]].<ref name=SelfEstablish/>\nIt is also a member of the [[Federation of the Universities of the Islamic World]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.fuiw.org/en/universites_membres.php\n |title       = Member Universities\n |publisher   = Federation of the Universities of the Islamic World\n |accessdate  = 2011-09-17\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930125830/http://www.fuiw.org/en/universites_membres.php\n |archivedate = 2011-09-30\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=SelfEstablish>{{cite web\n |url=http://qunv.net23.net/en/?#content/17\n |title=About Us: Establishment and Development\n |publisher=University of the Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences\n |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\n}}\n{{coord|15.6343|32.4914|type:edu_region:SD|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holy Quran and Islamic Sciences, University of the}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Sudan]]\n[[Category:South Kordofan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1990]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Holy_Quran_and_Islamic_Sciences"}
{"title_page": "University of the Commonwealth Caribbean", "text_new": "{{short description|University in Jamaica}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Jamaican English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name        = University of the Commonwealth Caribbean\n| caption     = \n| motto       = ''Fostering Leadership & Innovation''\n| established = 2004\n| type        = [[Private university|Private]]\n| president   = Dennis J. Gayle\n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| image_name  = \n| location    = [[Kingston, Jamaica]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|18.007568|-76.7813|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Commonwealth Caribbean''' ('''UCC''', formerly known as '''University College of the Caribbean''') is one of Jamaica's largest privately held tertiary education institutions operating 7 campuses:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/our-campuses|title=UCC - Our Campuses|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref> in six parishes across Jamaica.\n\nAs of 2017, the University offers professional certificate, diploma, associate, bachelor's and master's degree programs, as well as customized training programs in Jamaica.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/about-us|title=UCC - About Us|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nUCC was formed in 2004 as a result of the merger in 2002 of the Institute of Management Sciences (IMS), incorporated in 1992, and the Institute of Management & Production (IMP), incorporated in 1976.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/our-history|title=UCC - History|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation ==\nThe University of the Commonwealth Caribbean is registered and recognized by the University Council of Jamaica (UCJ), the official accreditation body for tertiary education in Jamaica<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ucj.org.jm/accreditation/accredited-programmes-and-ucj-approved-degrees/|title=Accredited Programmes and UCJ-Approved Degrees - The University Council of Jamaica|newspaper=The University Council of Jamaica|access-date=2017-02-14|language=en-US}}</ref> and also has international institutional accreditation status from the UK based Accreditation Services for Independent Colleges & Universities (ASIC).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.jamaicaobserver.com/magazines/career/UCC-accredited-by-UK-body_86493|title=UCC accredited by UK body | date=14 January 2017 | newspaper=Jamaica Observer|access-date=30 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe UCC is also recognised as a registered centre from the University of London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londoninternational.ac.uk/onlinesearch/institutions|title=Directory of Teaching Institutions {{!}} University of London International Programmes|date=2011-09-09|website=www.londoninternational.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Affiliates and partnerships ==\n\nUCC currently partners with universities, colleges, institutions and schools across the globe.\nAs of February 2017, the University of the Commonwealth Caribbean is partnered with:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/our-partners|title=Our partners|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n* Caribbean School of Medical Sciences, Jamaica<ref>http://www.csmsj.co/</ref>\n* [[Commonwealth of Learning]]\n* eMedia Jamaica<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joinemedia.com/|title=Home|website=www.joinemedia.com}}</ref> \n* [[Florida International University]]\n* Law College of the Americas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww38.lawcollegeamericas.com/|title=lawcollegeamericas.com|website=ww38.lawcollegeamericas.com}}</ref>\n* [[University of London]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.ucc.edu.jm }}\n\n{{Universities and colleges in Jamaica}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University College Of The Caribbean}}\n[[Category:Universities in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in the Caribbean by dependent territory]]\n[[Category:Education in Kingston, Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kingston, Jamaica]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|University in Jamaica}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Jamaican English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name        = University of the Commonwealth Caribbean\n| caption     = \n| motto       = ''Fostering Leadership & Innovation''\n| established = 2004\n| type        = [[Private university|Private]]\n| president   = Dennis J. Gayle\n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| image_name  = \n| location    = [[Kingston, Jamaica]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|18.007568|-76.7813|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Commonwealth Caribbean''' ('''UCC''', formerly known as '''University College of the Caribbean''') is one of Jamaica's largest privately held tertiary education institutions operating 7 campuses:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/our-campuses|title=UCC - Our Campuses|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref> in six parishes across Jamaica.\n\nAs of 2017, the University offers professional certificate, diploma, associate, bachelor's and master's degree programs, as well as customized training programs in Jamaica.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/about-us|title=UCC - About Us|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nUCC was formed in 2004 as a result of the merger in 2002 of the Institute of Management Sciences (IMS), incorporated in 1992, and the Institute of Management & Production (IMP), incorporated in 1976.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/our-history|title=UCC - History|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation ==\nThe University of the Commonwealth Caribbean is registered and recognized by the University Council of Jamaica (UCJ), the official accreditation body for tertiary education in Jamaica<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ucj.org.jm/accreditation/accredited-programmes-and-ucj-approved-degrees/|title=Accredited Programmes and UCJ-Approved Degrees - The University Council of Jamaica|newspaper=The University Council of Jamaica|access-date=2017-02-14|language=en-US}}</ref> and also has international institutional accreditation status from the UK based Accreditation Services for Independent Colleges & Universities (ASIC).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.jamaicaobserver.com/magazines/career/UCC-accredited-by-UK-body_86493|title=UCC accredited by UK body | date=14 January 2017 | newspaper=Jamaica Observer|access-date=30 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe UCC is also recognised as a registered centre from the University of London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londoninternational.ac.uk/onlinesearch/institutions|title=Directory of Teaching Institutions {{!}} University of London International Programmes|date=2011-09-09|website=www.londoninternational.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Affiliates and partnerships ==\n\nUCC currently partners with universities, colleges, institutions and schools across the globe.\nAs of February 2017, the University of the Commonwealth Caribbean is partnered with:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucc.edu.jm/our-partners|title=Our partners|website=ucc.edu.jm|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n* Caribbean School of Medical Sciences, Jamaica<ref>http://www.csmsj.co/</ref>\n* [[Commonwealth of Learning]]\n* eMedia Jamaica<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joinemedia.com/|title=Home|website=www.joinemedia.com}}</ref> \n* [[Florida International University]]\n* Law College of the Americas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww38.lawcollegeamericas.com/|title=lawcollegeamericas.com|website=ww38.lawcollegeamericas.com}}</ref>\n* [[University of London]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.ucc.edu.jm }}\n\n{{Universities and colleges in Jamaica}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University College Of The Caribbean}}\n[[Category:Universities in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in the Caribbean by dependent territory]]\n[[Category:Education in Kingston, Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kingston, Jamaica]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in North America]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Commonwealth_Caribbean"}
